<FIRST>r a AM-NavyDeath     09-22 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navy Death,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Revises Training Following Trainee's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An abandon-ship drill has been revised on
the recommendation of investigators probing the death of an aviation
officer candidate in a training pool, a Navy spokesman said Thursday.
   The changes were made although the Navy found no wrongdoing or
safety shortcomings in the June 23 death of Michael Fedie at
Pensacola Naval Air Station, said Cmdr. Dennis Hessler.
   Fedie, 22, of Altoona, Wis., died from an unexplained seizure
accompanied by acute cerebral edema, a swelling and excess of fluid
in the brain, an autopsy report concluded.
   He collapsed as he was walking from the pool after jumping off a
12-foot tower and swimming 15 yards underwater to simulate efforts
to avoid burning fuel on the surface surrounding a sinking ship.
   Fedie and other students first completed the drill wearing only
swimming suits and then did it again in flight suits and boots
before Fedie collapsed.
   One change adds an interim jump while wearing flight suits but no
boots and another is to have the students swim in flight suits and
boots to get a feel for what it is like before jumping from the
tower, said Hessler, spokesman for the Pensacola-based Naval
Education and Training Command.
   As an added precaution, students have been jumping from the side
of the pool instead of the tower since Fedie's death, but Hessler
said he expects the tower jump will be reinstated.
   Another recommendation that has been adopted is a daily check of
the telephone at the pool. The phone was working on the day Fedie
collapsed, Hessler said.
   The changes were unrelated to the cause of Fedie's death but were
among recommendations that the judge advocate general's office will
make in a final report.
   Those three recommendations were passed on to the Naval Aviation
Schools Command ahead of the report's release, which is expected
soon. Hessler said additional recommendations are expected in the
report.
   The changes affect only the aviation program at Pensacola
although similar drills are conducted for non-aviation trainees at
other bases, Hessler said.
   The death of Airman Recruit Lee Mirecki, 19, of Appleton, Wis.,
on March 2, 1988, triggered changes in procedure for training rescue
swimmers who jump from helicopters to aid downed airmen.
   Mirecki drowned after suffering fear-induced heart failure, a
pathologist testified at the court-martial of an instructor who was
convicted of negligent homicide and sentenced to 90 days in the brig.
</TEXT>
