<FIRST>r a AM-TripleHomicide     09-22 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Triple Homicide,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fifteen-Year-Old Pleads Guilty, Waives Trial In Four Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARWICK, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 15-year-old former high school football
player accused in four neighborhood murders over the past two years
waived his right to a trial Thursday and will serve six years in
reform school.
   The sentence is the maximum Craig Price could have received, even
if he had been found guilty in a trial, according to state laws
concerning minors. He also pleaded guilty to two burglary charges.
   Price goes to the strictest section of the Rhode Island Training
School almost three weeks after the bodies of Joan Heaton, 39, and
her two daughters _ Melissa, 8, and Jennifer, 10 _ were discovered
on Labor Day in their home here.
   Price lived two blocks away from the Heatons and two doors from
the house where Rebecca A. Spencer was killed in 1987. Price
admitted to killing all four in taped confessions, said state
prosector Jeffrey Pine.
   The youth stared at the table in front of him as Family Court
Judge Carmine DePatrillo told him that by pleading guilty to
deliquency by first-degree murder and burglary he would have no
court hearing chance to challenge any evidence, witnesses or give
testimony in court.
   Attorney General James E. O'Neil said after Price was taken away
that he felt no special relief at watching the youth go to the
state's juvenile prison.
   ``This is not a type of situation where you sit back and achieve
any degree of satisfaction,'' O'Neil said. ``It's just wasted human
lives.''
   He said he was frustrated because Price will only serve time
until his 21st birthday _ which he would have if he had been found
guilty in a trial.
   Investigators said the 240-pound Price, a former high school
football player known as ``Iron Man'' who was repeating the ninth
grade, never showed any remorse for the killings.
   All three Heatons had been beaten to death, and were stabbed
repeatedly.
   Spencer, who was killed in July 1987, was stabbed 58 times,
police said. Blanchard and Capt. Ronald Carter, who headed the
investigation, both said they suspected the same person in all the
killings.
</TEXT>
