<FIRST>r a PM-APArts:FilmFestival-Strapless     09-22 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Film Festival-Strapless,0362</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Romantic Drama by David Hare Will Premiere at Film Festival</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British filmmaker-playwright David Hare thinks
American love stories are unrealistic and says his latest work,
``Strapless,'' with Blair Brown and Bridget Fonda, is more
believable than current Hollywood fare.
   ``Strapless'' will have its premiere at the New York Film
Festival.
   After a screening of ``Strapless'' this week, Hare attacked Rob
Reiner's hit movie, ``When Harry Met Sally... ,'' for failing to
integrate the lead characters into the outside world.
   ``At no point was there any reference to the characters' jobs, or
to what their relationships were outside dating,'' said Hare. ``They
were people who dated, that was their primary social function. They
either were happy or unhappy according to whether they were dating.
   ``It's this way of looking at the world through people who exist
in rooms, and the minute the door closes, everything that is the
world is shut out of that room and you are simply together eating
lasagna or spaghetti or whatever kind of pasta the scene is about,''
he said.
   In ``Strapless,'' Brown stars as a 40-year-old American doctor
working in a London hospital and living with her rebellious younger
sister (Fonda). While on holiday, Brown is pursued by a romantic
entrepreneur (Bruno Ganz), who follows her back to London and
eventually persuades her to marry him.
   But Ganz, substantially in debt, suddenly flees and Brown is
forced to put her life back together again and provide support for
Fonda, who has become pregnant after a brief affair.
   Hare, who also wrote the screenplay, said he enjoyed the
challenge of creating female characters. ``There's nothing harder to
get than a member of the opposite sex. I know the benefit of writing
about women is you have such an extraordinary range of underused
actresses _ actresses able to do all sorts of things they're not
ususally given a chance to.''
   Hare also directed the 1984 drama ``Wetherby,'' and wrote the
play and screenplay ``Plenty.'' Meryl Streep starred in the film
version.
</TEXT>
