<DOCNO> AP890922-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0252EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BusAccident-Pits     09-22 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bus Accident-Pits,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Caliche Pits: A Little-Regulated Legacy Of Road Construction</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bus Accident</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of caliche pits like the one in
Thursday's fatal school bus accident line roads throughout south
Texas, a little-regulated legacy of contractors who dig up the
gravel-like material for road base and then move on.
   Nineteen students were killed when the bus plunged into the pit
following a collision with a soft-drink delivery truck. The bus
became submerged in about 12 feet of water at the bottom of the
40-foot-deep chasm.
   No guard rail separated the pit from the roadway 20 feet away and
no road signs warned of its presence. Texas Department of Public
Safety Sgt. Israel Pacheco said there was no fence around the pit,
though there may have been one before some recent road construction
nearby.
   There are no state regulations governing the pits, said officials
of the state Railroad Commission, which governs surface mining, and
the General Land Office, which oversees the state's geology.
   Federal mining regulations govern caliche pits while they are
being mined, said Bill Driscoll, executive director of a state
contractors' association, but those regulations do not apply to
inactive pits.
   Officials were unsure who had excavated the pit involved in
Thursday's accident just outside Alton or who owned the land on
which it is located.
   Caliche, a Spanish word, is defined as gravel, sand and desert
debris cemented by a porous calcium carbonate, according to state
geologist Bill Farr.
   The material occurs naturally through the Southwest and Mexico,
and ``is used quite a lot in making road base material,'' Farr said.
   ``You'll see caliche pits lining the highways all throughout the
Southwest,'' he said.
   Such a pit is ``not unusual in the (Rio Grande) Valley,'' Hidalgo
County Sheriff's Deputy Rene Torres said. ``We see that a lot down
here ... I used to go swimming in them as a kid.''
   Farr said caliche will not withstand transportation long
distances, requiring the material to be mined near where it will be
used.
   Contractors lease the ground from owners of land adjoining a
project, dig out the caliche they need, then move on, he said. All
that remains is ``the hole in the ground that left when the caliche
is removed.''
   ``What they're removing is 99 percent of what they're actually
using, so there is really nothing to fill the pit with, other than
to go dig a hole somewhere else,'' Farr said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890922-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0300EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TeacherSurvey     09-22 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Teacher Survey,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teachers Warn of Worsening Student Social Ills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two out of three teachers say they would
recommend their profession to youngsters, but many say they are
struggling with worsening social ills among students, especially
alcohol abuse, a new poll finds.
   The annual survey of teacher opinion by the Metropolitan Life
Insurance Co., released Thursday, found the number of teachers in
grades 7-12 concerned about student drinking in their schools
increased from 66 percent in 1985 to 81 percent in the latest survey.
   Drinking was considered a serious problem by 91 percent of high
school teachers polled and 87 percent of rural teachers, according
to the survey, ``Preparing Schools for the 1990s.''
   In the last five years, the proportion of teachers considering
the dropout problem serious at their schools rose from 40 percent to
52 percent.
   And 70 percent of high school teachers regard drug use as a
serious problem at their schools, up from 58 percent in 1985.
   ``American teachers, particularly those in our cities, have sent
an S.O.S. about the severity of the out-of-school problems facing
their students,'' Albert Shanker, president of the American
Federation of Teachers, said in reaction to the poll.
   ``If President Bush and the nation's governors are serious about
making education a national priority, one of the things they will
have to do is listen to the messages from the front lines, to the
problems teachers face every day in the classroom,'' Shanker said.
``And what our teachers are crying out for are solutions to the
severe problems children face, which affect the ability of schools
to do their job: poverty, ill health, drug abuse and troubled
families.''
   The survey, appearing less than a week before President Bush is
to convene an ``education summit'' with the nation's governors, was
conducted by Louis Harris and Associates. It was based on a
telephone survey of a nationally representative sample of 2,000
public school teachers from kindergarten through 12th grade polled
in May and June. The survey had a margin of error of plus or minus
three percentage points.
   On the positive side, 81 percent of teachers surveyed said they
still ``love to teach.'' Two-thirds said they would advise a young
person to enter the teaching profession, compared with 45 percent
five years ago.
   Fifty-three percent believe education reform has improved their
schools, compared with 43 percent who expressed that view in a 1984
poll. Only six percent said school reforms have had a negative
impact. The remainder said the effects were neutral.
   But teachers were less enthused about the impact of reform on
themselves: 43 percent said reform has affected teachers positively,
27 percent said they felt neutral, and 29 percent said reform has
had a negative effect on teachers.
   Eighty-six percent said they backed mentor-teacher programs in
which teachers help colleagues improve, and 55 percent supported
career ladder programs which offer teachers the chance to advance to
the level of master teacher for more pay.
   Two-thirds said they strongly backed creation of school-based
leadership committees of principals, teachers and students to
enforce school rules.
   But 64 percent say schools are getting worse at sparing teachers
administrative busy work.
   Teachers are most supportive of reform in schools where
``educators are actively involved in making decisions about teaching
and learning, new ideas flourish and student learning improves,''
said Keith Geiger, president of the National Education Association,
the nation's largest teacher union.
   ``In places where reform simply means more _ more graduation
requirements, more hours in the school day, more paperwork, teachers
are understandably less enthusiastic,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
