<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--StealthBomber     09-22 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Stealth Bomber,0157</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stealth Bomber Prototype Begins Fourth Test Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stealth bomber soared
Thursday within 90 feet of a giant Air Force jet to practice
refueling during its fourth test flight over the desert, a military
spokeswoman said.
   The sinister-looking stealth maneuvered behind and beneath the
Air Force KC-10 refueling tanker, the military version of a DC-10,
to practice for an actual refueling scheduled later, said Capt. Tess
Taft Cowan.
   ``It was a successful flight, with all primary mission objectives
being completed,'' she said.
   The stealth, a black boomerang-shaped flying wing, took off from
the base at about 1 p.m., flew for 2 hours, 53 minutes over the
Mojave Desert, then landed back at Edwards at 3:53 p.m., Cowan said.
   The refueling practice was conducted about one hour into the
flight, she said. The time and date of the next test flight were not
announced.
</TEXT>
