<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0255EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-InsuranceSuit     09-22 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Insurance Suit,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses Federal Claims in 19-State Insurance Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal claims in a lawsuit accusing major
insurance companies of conspiring to manufacture a ``liability
crisis'' and drive up rates have been dismissed by a federal judge.
   U.S. District Judge William Schwarzer's decision was released
Thursday in connection with a lawsuit filed by 19 states in March
1988 against 32 major insurance companies and reinsurers, who
provide insurance for insurance companies.
   California Attorney General John Van De Kamp announced he would
appeal the decision.
   The lawsuit claimed insurance companies in the mid-1980s agreed
to sharply reduce liability coverage for public agencies, businesses
and non-profit organizations and to stop all coverage for
environmental damages caused by pollution.
   The judge, who sits in San Francisco, issued a preliminary
decision in July dismissing the suit on grounds that insurance
companies can act together under federal law without being subject
to most types of antitrust suits.
   The states involved in the suit are: California, New York, West
Virginia, Wisconsin, Minnesota, Alabama, Massachusetts, Arizona,
Maryland, Connecticut, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Ohio, Colorado,
Montana, Washington, Alaska, Michigan and Louisiana. Texas filed a
similar suit in its state court that is preceeding to trial
independently of this action.
   The states alleged violations of federal antitrust laws and state
laws in a global conspiracy starting in 1984 that they said included
boycotts, threats, intimidation and other coersive conduct.
   Insurance companies denied the allegations, and said rate
increases resulted from claim losses due in part to broad liability
rules in many states. They also blamed investment income declines.
   Insurers are immune from federal antitrust suits unless they are
shown to have engaged in a boycott, intimidation or coercion.
</TEXT>
