<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0043EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Hugo-FirstPerson     09-22 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-First Person,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reporter Tells of Own Encounter With Hugo's Wrath</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hugo-Virgin Islands, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Hurricane Hugo tore through the
Caribbean on a beeline course for Puerto Rico, my sister called from
Tennessee to check how we were doing.
   ``We're taping up the windows and moving all the furniture into
the back rooms,'' I said. ``It's kind of exciting.''
   Within 24 hours, our home on the top floor of an 18-story
beachfront condominium would be wrecked and I was to gain an
understanding of hurricanes I could never acquire from simply
reporting on them.
   By the time I arrived from the AP office after midnight Sunday,
my wife, Mary Jane, had taken our four daughters _ Marcia, 13;
Nancy, 11; Katherine, 3; and Susan, 6 months _ to an apartment on
the 17th floor. Our neighbors there, Herb and Nancy Brown, had put
up aluminum siding on their windows.
   I decided to stay in our apartment, resting on a mattress in the
study on the side away from the sea. I put a clock on a bookcase.
Hugo, with more than 140 mph winds, was supposed to hit sometime
after daybreak.
   The wind was howling, and it started to rain. I kept getting up
to see whether the windows were holding up. Eventually, the
electricity went off. In the dark I stepped in a puddle, water from
a broken window, and moved the mattress into the hall.
   At about 6 a.m., Mary Jane had rapped on the Browns' bedroom door
and asked Herb if it was just her imagination that the bed was
shaking. It wasn't.
   While the children slept, Mary Jane came several times to check
our apartment as water spread across the floors.
   She brought up our dog, Lucky, a small, black mongrel, who had
been whining in a bathroom. It was cool, but Lucky's fur was wet and
she was panting.
   I thought, I can try to fool myself into thinking we're not in
danger, but you can't fool this animal.
   Palms were bending now. Glass was shattering, and metal was
tearing away from the building.
   Mary Jane and the girls had moved into the hall with the Browns
and spread sofa cushions on the floor. I joined them with the
mattress.
   We followed the progress of the storm on the radio and watched
through a concrete lattice in a corner of the hall. Periodically, I
went back upstairs to listen outside my apartment.
   Amazingly, the telephones were still working, and I could get
through to the office. I was talking with Bureau Chief Kernan
Turner, when there was a shatter of glass _ followed by silence.
Finally, he came back on the line after having run for cover at the
back of the office and then crawling back to the phone. Everybody
was OK, but the office was taking a beating.
   By then, our building was swaying like a ship at sea.
   We debated whether a hurricane can topple an 18-floor building.
Are you safer on the top floor or the ground floor? Nobody knew.
   We took up an offer to move the family down to the 11th floor,
where the sway was less noticeable and the wind less fierce.
   We settled outside an apartment occupied by two sisters we had
never met, Teresa and Lucy Bague. They gave our children water,
juice, crackers and Milky Way bars. Susan, the baby, was the only
one who slept much.
   Mary Jane told me later, ``I looked at you and your lips were
gray. I thought, mine must be, too.''
   Hours passed. The storm died down and then came back stronger
than ever, as if roused from fitful sleep.
   Then the hurricane hit us with all its might. Two hours later
Hugo passed and we were safe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
