<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-Drugs 2Takes 310-460 09-22 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Drugs, 2 Takes, 310-460</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Republicans Taking Drug Plan to White House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican senators, following six hours of
negotiations with Democrats, agreed late Thursday to take a new plan
for financing the war on drugs to the White House for consideration.
   Sources said the plan contained some of the selected cuts in
spending the Bush administration had wanted as a way to offset
increases in the drug program as well as an across-the-board
reduction in federal programs to raise the bulk of the money.
   Republicans said they would not consider the plan a tentative
agreement without White House approval and they indicated that there
was no rush on the part of the Bush administration to provide that.
   ``We've been on the phone to (White House chief of staff John)
Sununu all night,'' Sen. John Warner, R-Va., said emerging from the
negotiations along with other tired senators.
   Republicans said they would take the plan to the White House on
Friday and then reconvene their negotiations with the Democrats.
   Senators declined to comment on specifics of the plan. Sources
who spoke on condition of anonymity said, however, that the
across-the-board cut envisioned in the proposal would amount to 0.3
percent. That would be an increase from a 0.2875 percent reduction
in a plan that Republicans carried into the negotiating session
Thursday afternoon.
   That Republican plan would have paid for all but $23 million of
an $850 million increase in the drug war on top of the $7.9 billion
proposed by Bush.
   Offsets in selected programs under the new versions would be
determined at the committee level. Democrats are planning something
similar to that but on a larger scale in the House.
   Approval of the proposal would stave off a threatened blockade of
spending bills on the Senate floor with nine days to go before the
start of the next fiscal year when they will be needed to pay for
the operations of the government.
   Four spending bills are currently awaiting passage in the Senate
and eight others are in the pipeline.
</TEXT>
