<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Releasing Nelson Mandela from a South
African prison would mean little if the system that keeps blacks
second-class citizens is allowed to stand, his daughter says.
   ``In many ways, he'll still be a prisoner under that system,''
Maki Mandela said Wednesday during a visit to Memphis State
University.
   Mandela, 70, has been jailed since 1962 and is serving a life
sentence on conspiracy and sabotage charges.
   He has become a symbol of black South Africa's struggle to
abolish apartheid, and human rights activists around the world have
called for his release.
   Ms. Mandela, who was 8 years old when her father first went to
prison, said she was allowed a private visit with him last month.
   ``For the first time, we could visit more than 45 minutes without
the police being there,'' she said. ``It was just a nice,
fatherly-daughter exchange.''
</TEXT>
