Wednesday at Centenary College's annual media luncheon.
   Edwards, 42, said there's a big difference between the NPR
programs heard by 12 million people today and those broadcast when
he joined the network 16 years ago.
   ``In the early days it was more of a free-form magazine. There
was much less journalism than there is today,'' he said.
   It evolved into news, he said, adding, ``That's what was lacking
in radio.''
