<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0633EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>d e BC-Theater     09-22 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>`The Man Who Shot Lincoln' Opens</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``The Man Who Shot Lincoln'' comes to the
audience from limbo, something like a live, weird episode of ``The
Twilight Zone.''
   The play, not without interest but finally less than successful,
opened Thursday night at the off-Broadway Astor Place Theater. In
it, actor Edwin Booth tells us his version of his life story, in
which he and not his brother John Wilkes shoots Abraham Lincoln at
Ford's Theater.
   It's essentially a tale in which Edwin Booth plays both Othello,
overwhelmingly jealous of his wife, and Iago, whispering accusations
into his own ear.
   The conversation starts out stilted, and Sam Tsoutsouvas speaks
it with ripe plumminess and a smirk, to the discomfort of listeners.
Both dialogue and delivery improve, but not enough.
   A feeling of restlessness develops as the play progresses, though
one doesn't entirely lose interest.
   The characters include Booth's wife Mary, played with saintly
sweetness by Marcia Gay Harden. Mary dies soon after giving birth
but remains in the play as a figment of Booth's imagination.
   Conan McCarty is sprightly as a jaunty, womanizing John Wilkes
Booth, passionate defender of the Confederacy. Eric Tull shows
versatility in walk-ons as the Booth brothers' insane father, a
simpleton, and a Union officer.
   Playwright Luigi Creatore has had musicals and at least one other
drama produced. Crandall Diehl directed. Michael Bottari and Ronald
Case designed scenery and period costumes. William de Silva produced
in association with Claridge Productions Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
