<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0245EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Uprising Bjt   09-22 0809</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Uprising, Bjt,0834</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Day in the Intefadeh: Anger, Indignity, Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIT SAHOUR, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two soldiers with
submachine guns waved their arms and shouted, ordering a woman and
her three teen-age children to slap paint on a white stone wall to
cover anti-Israeli graffiti.
   Down the street, Israeli tax agents dragged furniture from a home
in lieu of unpaid taxes.
   In nearby Beit Jala, troops searched house to house for a
stone-thrower who injured an Israeli soldier.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, shops in Gaza City were shut for a
second day to protest the killing of a 21-year-old man by soldiers.
   Thursday was one more day in the intefadeh, the Palestinian
uprising against Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip
that has sometimes raged and sometimes sputtered for more than 21
months.
   It is the deaths that make headlines. But the uprising is made up
of thousands of tiny incidents: stones thrown at soldiers,
checkpoints thrown up by troops, tax or arrest raids, outlawed
Palestinian flags flown from telephone wires.
   According to the army, more than 33,000 instances of stone
throwing and tire burning occurred in the past year. That doesn't
include 756 firebombings, 130 knifings or other serious assaults, or
345 cases of arson.
   ``These numbers show the uprising is still going on,'' says a
military officer, who agreed to discuss the revolt on condition of
anonymity.
   ``The intensity is not what it once was, it's lost a lot of its
volume,'' he said, but he added that violence may flare at any
moment.
   ``You have ups and downs. It can be affected by rumors, by
factors even outside the country, not just what the army does or
people in the community do.''
   The officer said the army did everything it could to prevent more
violence when it made raids to arrest uprising activists. But he
added: ``Obviously there's an animosity to army presence.''
   An uprising leader, asked about the status of the intefadeh,
noted: ``The youngsters throw stones, of course. That's no secret.
And we have our daily battles with the settlers.''
   The man, an organizer for the Syrian-backed Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine, said Jewish settlers often fire at
stone-throwing youngsters or smashed Arab-owned cars in revenge.
   When asked what caused bigger demonstrations, he said: ``It's the
street. It's not just dozens of youngsters. The street, the people,
are ready to cooperate, sometimes the anger bursts and it happens.''
   The street did not explode Thursday, but the intefadeh went on.
   Seven youths were reported shot by soldiers in clashes with
stone-throwers in the Gaza Strip. One confrontation was in the
Jabaliya refugee camp, where the uprising started on Dec. 8, 1987.
   Since then, 573 Palestinians have been killed by soldiers or
Jewish civilians, and 40 Israelis have been slain. At least 114
Palestinians have been killed by fellow Arabs as alleged
collaborators.
   Stores were shut in Gaza City on Thursday to mark the death of
Omar Ahmed Mansour, who threw a firebomb at an Israeli patrol on
Tuesday.
   In Beit Jala, in the West Bank, the army ordered all residents to
stay off the streets while soldiers searched houses for suspects in
the stoning of a soldier a day earlier.
   A parked Israeli tourist bus was firebombed in Manger Square in
Bethlehem, near where Jesus is believed to have been born. The bus
was gutted, but no one was hurt. Soldiers closed off the square and
Arab reports said 50 youths were rounded up for questioning.
   In neighboring Beit Sahour, a stronghold of the uprising's
boycott of Israeli taxes, soldiers escorted revenue agents who were
seizing truckloads of property from homes and businesses to demand
payment for taxes.
   Other soldiers ordered anti-Israeli graffiti painted over,
pulling people out of houses to do the work. But the streets here
and throughout the West Bank are testimony that the army cannot win
its battle against graffiti.
   Slogans painted over dozens of times reappear in bright colors.
One slogan on a Beit Sahour garbage bin said: ``Shamir's office,''
referring to Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir. Another said:
``Anybody who pays taxes will be punished.''
   At a small grocery, friends of Kamal Tawfik Abu Saada, 40,
consoled him over the loss of a refrigerator display case hauled off
by tax raiders. Abu Saada said the unit had cost him about $5,000.
   He admitted he refused to pay taxes. ``It only goes to the army.
I will never pay. It's impossible.''
   Raji, 55, who refused to give his last name, said soldiers and
tax men took carpets, his furniture, a video and television set from
his house. He chuckled over the framed map of Palestine the tax men
ignored.
   ``They only wanted the furniture,'' he said. ``They want to
punish Beit Sahour.''
</TEXT>
