<FIRST>r w PM-HUD-Kemp     09-22 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD-Kemp,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kemp Will Have Financial Czar Oversee HUD Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   HUD Secretary Jack Kemp plans to create a new
job of chief financial officer for the department as part of a
response to apparent mismanagement and what Kemp says is a ``rip-off
of the poor.''
   Claire E. Freeman, HUD's assistant secretary-designate for
administration, told a congressional panel Thursday that plans were
being drafted for a job with broad responsibility for monitoring the
Department of Housing and Urban Development's spending.
   ``If any agency needs one, it certainly is HUD,'' Freeman said.
``That will be a critical position at HUD.''
   Kemp, who has acknowledged up to $2 billion may have been
misspent at the department under the Reagan administration, called
the HUD problems ``the rip-off of the poor in the housing programs''
in an appearance before another Senate committee.
   Freeman spoke at her confirmation hearing by the Senate Committee
on Banking, Housing and Urban Affairs. She has been serving in an
acting capacity for several months.
   A spokesman for HUD, Jack Flynn, said the new position has not
yet been formally announced and may be included in a package of
departmental reforms Kemp plans to announce in October.
   He said details and responsibilities are still being worked out,
but the new position would have broader authority than the current
department budget director.
   HUD has been enmeshed in scandal over allegations of influence
peddling, fraud and mismanagement stemming from the eight years in
which the department was headed by Secretary Samuel R. Pierce Jr.
   Pierce is under subpoena by a House subcommittee to testify next
Tuesday, and at least two more times, as part of the congressional
investigation into the department's problems.
   Stuart Weisberg, staff director of the House panel investigating
HUD, said the subpoenas were formally served with Pierce's attorneys
late Thursday.
   Kemp, appearing before the Senate Small Business Committee,
touched on the HUD scandals only briefly as he urged support for the
administration's proposed tax incentives for urban and rural
enterprise zones.
   He criticized the House Ways and Means Committee for failing to
approve the enterprise zone tax breaks while backing a series of
larger tax breaks for specific industries.
   ``It would be unconscionable to ignore our nation's poor, while
providing assistance to business, energy and prosperous Americans,''
he said.
   The administration's proposal would eliminate capital gains taxes
for assets within areas designated as enterprise zones. It would
also permit tax deductions of up to $250,000 for new investments,
and provide a 5 percent refundable tax credit of up to $525 for
low-income workers within the zones. The administration estimates
the cost at $50 million in fiscal 1990.
</TEXT>
