<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0318EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-VetsLoans     09-22 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vets Loans,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Audit Finds Loan Program For Vets Suffering</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal program that guarantees housing
loans to veterans faces further financial erosion from loan
foreclosures and will require more taxpayer subsidies, according to
an audit by the investigative arm of Congress.
   The General Accounting Office said the Veterans' Affairs
Department program once largely paid its way, but needed $900
million in appropriations and transfers from other programs last
year.
   The audit, which was released earlier this week, blamed the
program's problems on the high rate of defaults in depressed farm
and oil-producing areas, but it also cited problems in how the
program has been run.
   Efforts are under way in Congress to pass legislation correcting
some of the problems in the special loan program, which has
benefited about 13 million veterans, the GAO said.
   There were 43,693 foreclosures on homes financed with VA loans in
the 1987 fiscal year and 48,963 foreclosures in fiscal 1988, the
report said. There were 38,721 in the first 10 months of this fiscal
year, VA spokeswoman Donna St. John said.
   ``We expect the numbers to continue to decrease,'' she said.
   The department says it is spending $778 million on the program
this fiscal year, with $120 million of that in supplemental funds.
   The GAO says the government will have to give an extra $453
million to the program in fiscal 1990 to pay off bad loans, and will
have to transfer about $100 million from a separate program used for
direct mortgage loans to severely disabled veterans.
   But several factors could drive the need for additional money
even higher, the audit said, including a foreclosure rate that is
higher than what the department projects.
</TEXT>
