<FIRST>u w AM-US-Soviet 6thLd-Writethru a0432 09-22 1404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0432,1,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, Baker Shevardnadze Open High-Level Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th graf to include material from discussions
aboard flight to Wyoming.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush met with Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard Shevardnadze on Thursday, opening three days of high-level
talks expected to narrow a time frame for a superpower summit next
year and spur chemical and nuclear weapons cutbacks.
   After nearly two hours of discussions, Shevardnadze said the two
sides had not set a date for a summit meeting between Bush and
Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev but, ``We have concluded that
a summit is necessary. There is no doubt about that.''
   Bush, interviewed Thursday night on ABC-TV's ``Primetime Live''
show, said there will be a summit, but he did not specify a time.
When asked if it would be early next year, the president replied,
``I wouldn't say early.''
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III indicated a summit meeting
might not occur until next year, but said it would be in the United
States. Another U.S. official, speaking privately, said, ``I would
steer you away from this year, definitely.''
   The high-level meetings began with a White House session attended
by Bush, Shevardnadze and Baker. The discussions will continue
between Baker and Shevardnadze on Friday and Saturday at a
wilderness lodge near Jackson Hole, Wyo. The two arrived there late
Thursday on an Air Force jet, where Shevardnadze said he hoped ``the
the good fresh air of Wyoming will help'' bring fresh ideas.
   Discussion aboard the plane concentrated on independence
movements among the Soviet Union's Baltic republics and Gorbachev's
plans to restructure the nation's economy.
   ``In the past, the Soviet preoccupation was never to reveal a
weakness because they felt we would exploit it,'' said the U.S.
official who spoke to five reporters aboard the plane on the
condition he would not be identified. ``Now they understand we are
interested in a relationship of mutual advantge.''
   Baker said that there was ``a full discussion of a summit'' and
that ``we hope to have a general time frame fora summit which we
could announce while we're in Wyoming.''
   Shevardnadze spoke with reporters in the White House driveway
before getting into a waiting limousine. Using the same language as
Baker, Shevardnadze said the talks in Wyoming probably would set ``a
general time frame'' for a Bush-Gorbachev summit. The foreign
minister said, ``I think it is entirely possible that we'll have
something more definite for you in Wyoming.''
   Bush said Monday he felt he was ``under no rush'' to have a
summit.
   While saying the timing and site for a summit have not been
determined, Baker said, ``I think it's our turn'' to host such a
meeting. The last superpower summit was in Moscow in 1988.
   ``I think it's important that the leaders of the Soviet Union and
the United States get together periodically,'' Baker said. ``It will
have been some time if we're looking at something into next year _
and I'm not saying that's the time frame we're going to give you in
Wyoming. But I think it's important they get together from time to
time and talk about the full range of problems between these two
countries.''
   Bush and Baker met with Shevardnadze for about an hour in the
Cabinet Room, along with aides on both sides. That session was
followed by another meeting, lasting about a half hour, in the Oval
Office, that excluded most of the aides.
   Shevardnadze said he delivered a letter from Gorbachev mostly
dealing ``with the entire complex'' of arms control issues.
   Baker said the letter ``in some instances restates long-held
Soviet positions. In some instances it puts new twists on those
positions.'' He declined to elaborate, saying the document required
more analysis.
   Baker described Gorbachev's letter as a reply to a June 20 letter
from Bush. ``This is a very serious letter. It is received by us in
a serious manner,'' Baker said. He said the United States would
reply to it in Wyoming.
   Baker said he hoped the Wyoming meeting would produce
``substantial progress'' on verification and stability measures
proposed by the United States for a strategic arms reduction treaty.
   Shevardnadze, talking with reporters, was asked if Bush had
disclosed any new initiatives. Bush had said Monday he had some
ideas that would capture the imagination of the Soviet people.
   ``There have been such suggestions on the American side, and we
certainly did not come here empty-handed,'' Shevardnadze replied.
   Describing the talks with Bush, Shevardnadze said, ``It was a
very interesting conversation, held in a very good atmosphere, also
a frank atmosphere.'' He said he was very pleased.
   Baker, at a separate briefing for reporters, said Bush expressed
the belief that the Soviet Union ``had proceeded very responsibly
and in a very measured way with respect to changes that are taking
place not just in the Soviet Union but in Eastern Europe as well.''
   Baker said Shevardnadze offered assurances that the Soviet Union
was not shippng weapons to Nicaragua. Baker said that U.S. officials
emphasized that shipments from the Soviet bloc have not diminished.
He said the subject would be discussed ``at some length'' in Wyoming.
   A senior Soviet official said Shevardnadze had brought a positive
response to the U.S. idea of ``trial verifications'' which would be
carried out before the conclusion of a treaty to cut strategic
nuclear arms.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, also said the
Soviet side is carrying proposals concerning the prohibition of
weapons-grade fission materials. Gorbachev initially suggested such
a ban several months ago.
   As for the discussions on a reduction of conventional forces in
Europe, the official said Shevardnadze has brought proposals which
he believes will make possible the conclusion of an agreement within
the six months to 12 months suggested by Bush. Bush has proposed
massive cuts.
   Shevardnadze told reporters the Soviet side welcomes ``with
active support'' the ``open skies'' proposal set forth by Bush
several months ago, and wants further discussions.
   Under the proposal, the skies of both countries would be open to
reconnaissance flights of the other. It was the first time Moscow
had indicatedly publicly its interest in exploring that proposal.
   The White House session marked Bush's first direct contact with a
high-ranking Soviet official since taking office last January and
came amid complaints by congressional Democrats, as well as from
Moscow, about the pace of activity in superpower relations.
   Trying to capitalize on Gorbachev's campaign for ``glasnost,'' or
openness, the administration prepared proposals lifting virtually
all restrictions on travel by diplomats, trade representatives and
journalists in each other's countries, according to sources.
   About 90 percent of the Soviet Union is off limits to Americans,
reflecting the suspicions that marked the rule of Josef Stalin. Over
the years, the United States responded by imposing similar travel
restrictions on a large part of the United States.
   Baker's meetings with Shevardnadze are expected to produce
progress across a broad range of subjects, including in addition to
conventional arms:
   _CHEMICAL WEAPONS. The two sides are reportedly close to an
agreement to exchange information on their chemical weapons programs
and to open stockpiles and plants to inspections by the other side.
   Baker and Shevardnadze hope to resolve details, including whether
U.S. chemical weapons stored in West Germany would be covered.
   _NUCLEAR ARMS. The two sides are exploring steps to narrow
differences blocking an agreement to cut by 30 percent to 50 percent
the most deadly weapons in the superpowers' arsenals _ long-range
bombers, missiles and submarines. The Soviet delegation includes a
team of arms experts.
   The United States is withdrawing its proposal to ban mobile
long-range missiles, which Moscow has and the United States wants.
   _HUMAN RIGHTS. The Soviets have told U.S. officials that hundreds
of Jews who have been refused exit permits will be allowed to leave.
The Bush administration had presented lists of more than 500
so-called ``refuseniks.'' The Soviet Union reportedly said that
three-quarters could leave.
   _ICE CURTAIN. Baker and Shevardnadze are to sign an agreement for
regular visits between the Yupik and Inupiat Eskimos of Alaska and
Siberia, thereby shattering the so-called ``Ice Curtain'' that has
existed since the Kremlin forbade travel across the Bering Strait in
1948.
   _NUCLEAR TESTING. The two officials may reach agreement in
principle on methods of monitoring underground nuclear tests. That
would be an impetus toward Senate ratification of two long-stalled
nuclear testing treaties.
</TEXT>
