<SECOND>AM-Protected Witness, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0854,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer for New York Drug Killing Hero Seeks Police Chief's Resignation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS's grafs 2-4, `Carl Maxey ..., to CORRECT that Maxey did
not state his client's allegations; picks up 5th graf: `Morgan, in ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A civil rights lawyer called Thursday for
the police chief's resignation over the alleged mistreatment of a
protected federal witness who was a key figure in a dramatic New
York City drug-and-murder case.
   Carl Maxey's client, who was moved to Spokane a year ago under
the name Amos Hardeen, said he was hit with a nightstick and called
a racial slur by officer Patricia Madsen after she stopped him and
cited him for speeding and running a stop sign.
   He also was cited for failure to obey an officer, resisting
arrest and third-degree assault after a brief scuffle outside his
home Sept. 1.
   Maxey contends that his client, who previously went by the single
name Arjune, was branded a liar by Police Chief Terry Mangan before
completion of an internal police investigation into his claim of
racial harassment.
   Mangan, in turn, accused Maxey of ``reverse racism.''
   Arjune was a key prosecution witness in a major cocaine trial in
New York City. He also testified against two of the four people
convicted of second-degree murder in the Feb. 26, 1988, shooting
death of Edward Byrne, a 22-year-old rookie police officer who was
guarding Arjune's house at the time.
   Arjune was relocated to Spokane last year and was recently moved
to an undisclosed location after his cover was blown.
   Spokane County prosecutors decided to prosecute Arjune for
resisting arrest, a misdemeanor, but dropped the felony assault
charge, deputy prosecutor Clark Colwell said. Arjune is forefeiting
bond in the case, Maxey said.
   Mangan said at a Sept. 11 press conference that the officer
denied Arjune's accusations and had passed a polygraph test. Mangan
said Arjune, described in New York as a Guyanese immigrant, lied in
his claim of harassment and tried to use his skin color to mask
criminal activity.
   Maxey said Thursday the chief's ``inappropriate, prejudicial and
personal comments'' and ``lack of adherence to standard police
procedure'' made it impossible for his client to participate in the
internal police probe.
   ``I called (Arjune) a liar because that's exactly what he did,''
Mangan said later. ``He tried to make it a phony racial incident by
lying about our officer and saying she called him a racial slur and
hit him with her nightstick.
   ``We'd be happy to hear Mr. Hardeen's side of the story if he
decides to give it, but we have documented proof that he gave a
false account of the events.''
   ``Arjune didn't hide behind his color,'' Maxey said. ``He wears
it as a badge of honor, and he's done far more in the war against
drugs than the police chief of Spokane.''
   Bill Dempsey of the U.S. Marshal's Service headquarters in
Arlington, Va., said the agency does not discuss specific cases or
confirm that a person is in the witness protection program.
   A witness would be dropped from the program for committing a
serious crime but not necessarily for minor offenses like traffic
infractions.
   ``The program is not a shield for a witness to hide behind,''
Dempsey said. ``The object of the program is to provide protection,
not immunity from the laws of the land.''
</TEXT>
