<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     09-22 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEBURNE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A maid who discovered $100,000 at a Fort
Worth bank and turned it in with no thought of a reward is not
without honor in communities from California to West Germany.
   The woman was honored Wednesday in the northern Texas town of
Cleburne, where high school teacher Larue Barnes proclaimed the day
Nancy Carroll Day. Police escorted Ms. Carroll to a reception at
Cleburne High School, where a sign outside said: ``Welcome, Nancy
Carroll. Honesty pays.''
   The reception ended with a presentation by third-graders from
Adams Elementary School. Each wrote Ms. Carroll a letter of praise.
   ``We really, really love you. ... I'm so proud of you. ... God
bless you,'' wrote 8-year-old Kevin Webster.
   Since Ms. Carroll found the money while cleaning up at the bank
last month, cards, letters and money _ more than $700 _ have been
sent from people throughout the world with one message: ``Thanks for
being honest.'' She has carefully preserved the letters, newspaper
clippings and copies of the checks in a new photo album.
   ``Nancy Carroll should be acknowledged for her demonstration of
what a human being ultimately is,'' a man from Munich, West Germany,
wrote. Attached was a check for $100.
   Ms. Carroll said she is trying to keep a low profile.
   ``Gee, I'm sitting on top of the world,'' she said. ``It's not
going to last forever. I'm enjoying it while I can.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SMACKOVER, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maurice Faulkner has been known to pull a
prank or two, so it was no surprise that only one friend believed
him when he claimed he'd just chased a 6-foot lizard into the woods.
   ``We thought he was making it up,'' Ernie Bartlett said.
``There's not supposed to be anything like this in this part of the
country, and he has been known to josh you.''
   Faulkner told Bartlett that he thought the lizard, which was
lying in the road, was a log _ until the ``log'' lifted its head. He
stopped his truck and chased the lizard into the woods, where it
climbed a tree.
   But the lizard turned the tables, hissing loudly and thrusting
its long, forked tongue as it chased Faulkner. Eventually the
reptile burrowed into a hole in a creek bank.
   Bartlett's wife, Kay, a frequent viewer of National Geographic
television specials, identified the reptile as a monitor lizard.
   But even after a few more friends were convinced, no one wanted
to help Faulkner roam the woods of southern Arkansas at night to
seek a giant, hissing lizard.
   At daylight Sunday, a posse of seven set out armed with a shovel,
some rope, a net and a videocamera. The group captured the lizard
while the reptile was still parked in the hole with his tail
sticking out.
   The Bartletts have contacted zoos in Monroe, La., and Little Rock
about taking the lizard.
</TEXT>
