<FIRST>r w PM-FBI-Discrimination     09-22 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FBI-Discrimination,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>FBI Won't Appeal Court Order in Discrimination Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI says it won't appeal a federal court
order that directs changes in promotions and assignments to correct
what a judge called systematic discrimination against Hispanic
agents.
   The bureau made the announcement Thursday after Solicitor General
Kenneth Starr told the FBI he had accepted FBI Director William
Sessions' recommendation not to appeal the case.
   The May 5 order by a federal judge in Texas strips FBI
supervisors of the power to overrule decisions by the bureau's
career promotion board.
   It also set up a panel of three outside attorneys to decide if up
to 200 Hispanic agents should be promoted to make up for past job
discrimination.
   Sessions said in a statement that he recommended against
appealing the order after weighing ``the myriad legal, operational
and institutional considerations.''
   ``We must move beyond the frictions caused by this case to
address the many vital challenges facing the FBI in the 1990s,''
said Sessions, who added that dropping the appeal was in the best
interests of FBI employees.
   The decision was hailed by Rep. Don Edwards, D-Calif., who called
on the FBI to settle a racial harassment and discrimination lawsuit
filed by Donald Rochon, a black FBI agent now assigned to the
Philadelphia field office.
   Rochon claims he and his family were harassed by white agents
when he worked in Chicago and that he suffered retaliation by FBI
supervisors for pressing his complaints.
   ``That's exactly the right decision, something we've been urging
for many months,'' Edwards, chairman of the House Judiciary
subcommittee on civil rights, said of the FBI's decision.
   ``It's time for them to move on and get at the root causes of the
problems,'' said the congressman.
   Bureau officials refused to comment on the Rochon case, except to
cite Sessions' previous statements that he intended ``to withhold
judgment until the facts have been adjudicated.''
   In the class-action suit joined by 311 of the FBI's approximately
400 Hispanic agents, U.S. District Judge Lucius Bunton III of
Midland, Texas, directed the bureau to end its ``unsystematic
excessively subjective'' method of promoting special agents.
   Bunton said the ability of special agents in charge of field
offices to overrule promotion-board decisions was ``anathema to
nearly every reform advanced by the bureau and ordered by this court
to improve the fairness and reviewability'' of the process.
   The order followed two years of litigation launched in early 1987
by Bernardo M. Perez, then the No. 2 FBI agent in El Paso, Texas.
The suit was filed by Perez after a series of demotions from special
agent in charge of the San Juan, Puerto Rico, field office to El
Paso, which he termed an FBI ``dumping ground.''
   Bunton ordered Perez's promotion and he has since been appointed
deputy assistant director of the FBI's laboratory division in
Washington.
   In earlier rulings, the judge found that Hispanic agents were
often relegated to what one Hispanic agent has described as the
``taco circuit'' _ working in Hispanic neighborhoods or doing
language translations.
   Bunton concluded that Hispanic agents were often assigned to such
undesirable tasks as monitoring Spanish-speaking suspects on
wiretaps.
   After he took office in November 1987, Sessions reviewed all FBI
personnel and recruitment policies, saying he would tolerate no
discrimination.
   Sessions went outside the bureau to hire a new head of the
reorganized equal employment opportunity office.
   Bunton acknowledged these steps ``demonstrate energetic and
good-faith effort to correct the disparities found by this court.''
   But the judge said the FBI had to do more, saying the changes
already implemented ``while well-intentioned, are fine-tuning of a
system that requires more dramatic repair.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890922-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0332EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-IndecentRadio-TV     09-22 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Indecent Radio-TV,440</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Broadcasters Consider Reviving Program Codes ^By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Responding to growing concern over raunchy
radio and TV, the nation's major broadcasting group is considering
restoring program codes that were dropped under government pressure
in the 1970s.
   The National Association of Broadcasters will canvass its members
and study whether to restore the codes because new Federal
Communications Commission Chairman Alfred Sikes urged radio
executives to shut down ``shock radio,'' NAB spokesman Walt Wurfel
said Thursday.
   Sikes urged broadcasters at a convention in New Orleans last week
to shun programs that use sexually and racially offensive humor to
attract audiences.
   Sikes said broadcasters should revive the codes that were
abandoned in the mid-1970s after the Justice Department initiated an
antitrust lawsuit against provisions of the codes involving
advertising. New codes should be drawn up by the industry, without
government pressure, said Sikes, the chief regulator of the radio
and television industry.
   Wurfel said the NAB's executive committee, in response to Sikes'
comments, told staff members ``to conduct an assessment of the
feasibility, effectiveness, legal and legislative elements of _ and
member support for _ devising a statement of standards or guidelines
concerning programming in the public interest.''
   Sikes, a former radio station owner who came to the FCC six weeks
ago, told the broadcasters' convention they were not ``simply
recorders, transmitters and antennas. We are what we broadcast.''
   He noted that on Aug. 24 the FCC announced it was considering
action against three radio stations in Chicago; San Jose, Calif.;
and Indianapolis for possibly broadcasting indecent programming
during daytime hours.
   That action was widely viewed as a warning shot across the bow of
broadcasters from a new, no-nonsense FCC. Sikes and new
commissioners Andrew Barrett and Sherrie Marshall faced tough
questioning during their Senate confirmation hearings in July on
what they proposed to do about indecency on the airwaves.
   Wurfel said the NAB, which represents more than 6,000 radio and
TV stations and the major radio and TV networks, was hesitant about
new codes in light of the Justice Department attack on the old codes.
   ``We don't desire to get into any further antitrust action,''
Wurfel said, adding that NAB also has to weigh First Amendment
concerns and community concerns.
   The House earlier this year passed a bill that would give the
television industry a three-year antitrust exemption so it can try
to adopt voluntary guidelines on violence.
   The Senate passed a similar measure that added antitrust
exemption for guidelines on portrayals of drug use and sex, and
differences in the two bills are now being worked out in a
House-Senate conference committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
