<FIRST>r w PM-BurlIves     09-22 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burl Ives,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guitar in Hand, Ives Still Taking Folk Music Around the Country</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Age and ``the rheumatiz'' are causing Burl Ives
to move a little slower these days, but he's still enchanting
audiences with his folk ballads, poems and tales of the American
past.
   ``That's what a song is for _ to sing it,'' said the 80-year-old
celebrated folk singer and actor. ``You can't put it in a box.''
   A little thinner than in his younger years but still sporting his
trademark white goatee, Ives gave one of his increasingly rare
recitals Thursday night at the Library of Congress to help celebrate
the Year of the Young Reader, a library initiative promoting book
reading among youngsters. First lady Barbara Bush is honorary
chairman of the project.
   As he has for years, Ives starts his program with some old
favorites, like ``Barbara Allen'' and ``The Old Lady Who Swallowed
the Fly,'' throws in a couple of cowboy songs, some Irish songs, a
few verses of poetry and a finale of songs ending with a lively
rendition of ``Jimmy Crack Corn.''
   Ives is an old friend of the Library of Congress, whose vast
collection of recordings includes several hundred folk songs by the
``Wayfaring Stranger,'' as Ives calls himself.
   His songs, also including ``Foggy, Foggy Dew'' and ``Blue Tail
Fly,'' are familiar to millions of Americans who grew up in the
1940s and 1950s and to successive generations of children who heard
his recordings.
   Besides his folk song concerts, Ives was a popular stage, radio,
television and movie performer. He won an Academy Award for
supporting actor in ``The Big Country'' in 1958, and is widely
remembered as Big Daddy in the stage and movie productions of
Tennessee Williams' ``Cat on a Hot Tin Roof.''
   A degenerative bone disease has forced Ives to reduce his concert
appearances from about 40 or 50 annually to ``a few in the fall and
a few in the spring.'' He spends much of his time at his new home on
Anacortes, an island off the coast of Washington state, where he
moved recently from California.
   Ives has slimmed down from the 270 pounds he used to carry. But
the familiar goatee is still there and his blue eyes still twinkle
when he tells a story or sings a song with his deep-chested tenor.
   In a pre-recital interview, Ives said he usually practices
singing every day to stay in shape, even though his repertoire
includes songs he has been singing for 75 years or more. He learned
some from his grandmother on a farm in Jasper County, Ill., and many
others during his hitchhiking tour of America with his guitar during
the Depression.
   Some music critics say Ives represents a link between
Anglo-American folk traditions of the 19th century, whose songs he
often sings, and the folk-rock styles of the 1960s.
   Speaking for himself, Ives says he loves the Nashville sound,
``those gentle folk-like songs that depend on their lyrics for
effect and not the thump of the rhythm section.''
   He doesn't have much use for rock'n'roll.
   ``I don't dislike it and I don't like it,'' he said. ``I just
don't pay much attention to it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
