<DOCNO> AP890922-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0227EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-EducationRdp     09-22 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Education Rdp,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Will Bring Entire Cabinet to Education Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush will involve nearly every
Cabinet member in his education summit with the nation's governors
next week because ``everyone has a responsibility'' to help improve
schools, Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos says.
   ``It is a good move to involve the entire Cabinet because
certainly this is a national issue,'' Cavazos said Thursday at a
briefing on the two-day summit set for next Wednesday and Thursday
in Charlottesville, Va.
   ``We tend to think of education as being the purview of the
Department of Education,'' with its $22 billion budget, he
explained. Another $20 billion for education is spent by other
agencies, including the departments of Health and Human Services,
Labor, Defense and Agriculture.
   ``The quality of structure that each of these people will give
... in their area of responsibility can greatly impact the quality
of education,'' Cavazos said. ``Therefore, I think everyone has a
responsibility.''
   Roger Porter, Bush's domestic policy adviser, said the White
House is expecting perfect attendance from the governors of the 50
states, and several governors from U.S. territories will be there
with ``virtually the entire Cabinet.''
   The aim of the largely closed-door deliberations on the
University of Virginia campus will be to find new ideas to improve
America's schools, Porter said.
   The best ideas, including efforts to give parents more choice
over which public school their child attends, ``revolve around more
efficient use of the moneys that we are already spending,'' said
Porter.
   Such ideas do not require more money, he said.
   Democratic leaders of Congress on Wednesday unveiled their own
goals for the nation's schools and promised to press for
``adequate'' funding to help meet them.
   Porter said Americans are spending $353 billion on education at
all levels, from kindergarten through graduate school, including
more than $5,200 for every public school pupil.
   ``We're not going to be announcing any goals at the end of the
summit,'' Porter said. ``What we will be announcing will be the
process by which those goals are going to be developed.''
   The post-summit process of drawing up those goals ``will involve
parents and teachers and administrators and school boards.''
   Porter said the ideas that ``hold real promise for improving the
bottom line ... invariably expand choice for parents and students;
introduce greater flexibility, while demanding increased
accountability for results.''
   ``The president believes the current level of performance is not
acceptable and simply doing more of the same is unlikely to improve
it,'' Porter said. ``New approaches and new ideas are needed.''
   Although the agenda includes a discussion of expanding access to
higher education and training more teachers, the focus will clearly
be on problems in the lower grades.
   Porter, on leave as a professor of government at Harvard's
Kennedy School, said America's universities are ``really quite
phenomenal,'' in part because they are ``incredibly diverse and ...
highly competitive.''
   The topics for the six working groups, announced last week by the
governors, are: teaching, learning environment, governance, choice
and restructuring, a competitive work force and lifelong learning,
and post-secondary education.
   Bush will participate in each of the six working group sessions
with 16 or 17 governors and five or six Cabinet members.
   Each working group will be co-chaired by a Republican governor
and a Democratic governor, with a Cabinet member moderating the
discussion. A report will be prepared that the president and the
governors will consider in plenary sessions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
