<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0404EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-DeathPenalty     09-22 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Death Penalty,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rights Activists Decry Call For Swifter Executions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is being urged to move cautiously on a
new proposal to streamline death penalty appeals that civil
libertarians say could undermine fundamental rights of death row
inmates.
   ``We are concerned that fairness not be sacrificed for
expediency,'' said American Bar Association President Stanley
Chauvin in a letter to Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Joseph R.
Biden, D-Del.
   Chauvin said Biden should hold extensive public hearings on a
report announced Thursday by a committee appointed by Chief Justice
William H. Rehnquist. The ABA head also said the hearings should
await the lawyers' group own report on the issue due by November.
   The Rehnquist committee proposed a new system that could lead to
swifter executions. The panel, headed by retired Justice Lewis F.
Powell, proposed that fewer appeals be accompanied by more legal
help for condemned killers.
   Civil liberties lawyers accused Rehnquist of stacking the panel
and said the promise of expanded legal help is an illusion.
   ``They want to be able to kill more people faster,'' said Mary
Broderick of the National Legal Aid and Defender Association.
   ``It's a public relations ploy ... to facilitate the rush to the
gallows,'' said Leslie Harris of the American Civil Liberties Union.
   Ralph Neas of the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights said the
committee plan means less protection against abuse by police and
prosecutors in capital cases, particularly for poor blacks.
   ``Imposition of the death penalty is hopelessly tainted by race
discrimination,'' he said. ``Not only does race discrimination drive
the decision to seek and impose the death penalty, it affects every
part of the proceeding.''
   But Powell said, ``The hard fact is that the (capital punishment)
laws of 37 states are not being enforced by the courts.''
   ``I respect those who argue for outright abolition of death
punishment but it seems irrational to retain the penalty and
frustrate its fair implementation,'' he said.
   Ironically, Powell said he would vote to abolish capital
punishment if he were a state legislator, contending, ``It has not
deterred murder.''
   The United States has the highest murder rate of any nation and
is the only democracy that has the death penalty, he noted.
   Powell said the committee's report is intended to reform a system
that encourages endless legal maneuvering, years of delay and
frenzied, last-minute moves to stave off execution.
   The report was submitted to the U.S. Judicial Conference, the
policy-making arm of the federal courts. The conference postponed
any action on the report _ and any recommendation to Congress _
until its 28 judges reconvene in March.
   The committee recommended that states enact laws to limit death
row inmates to two rounds of appeals in state and federal courts.
One round would challenge a verdict directly; a second would be
based on alleged violations of the condemned individual's rights.
   The current system permits successive rounds of appeals in the
federal courts.
   There are some 2,200 convicted murderers on death row across the
nation. There have been 118 executions since the Supreme Court
reinstated the death penalty in 1976.
   Powell said only a fraction of those convicted for the 20,000
murders committed each year are sentenced to die, and that the
average lapse between conviction and execution is more than eight
years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
