<FIRST>r w PM-FlagBurning     09-22 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flag Burning,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Will Consider Flag Measures in October</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate will take up a legislation to
prohibit burning the American flag in two weeks and will consider a
proposed constitutional amendment after lawmakers return from their
October recess.
   ``The primary interest is not whether we should provide
protection for the flag but what is the proper course to provide
that protection,'' Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., said after the
Judiciary Committee sent the rival measures to the floor.
   The committee, by a 9-5 vote Thursday, approved the Democratic
statute to bar flag desecration but also voted 8-6 to send along
with an unfavorable recommendation the amendment favored by
President Bush.
   A July 14 agreement between congressional leaders required that
both measures be sent to the floor. Lawmakers plan floor action on
the bill as the last major item of business before the Senate goes
on its Oct. 6 recess and plans to take up the proposed amendment
soon after its Oct. 16 return.
   Thurmond, the committee's ranking Republican, argued that the
amendment as well as the proposed statute should get a favorable
recommendation.
   But Joseph Biden, D-Del., the panel's chairman and sponsor of the
statute, said the amendment ``does violence to the First Amendment
because it is so broad.''
   On Sept. 12, the House voted 380-38 to approve a similar statute.
The House has not yet voted on a constitutional amendment.
   The lawmakers are attempting to reverse the effects of a Supreme
Court ruling in June that threw out a Texas law used to convict
flag-burning protester Gregory Lee Johnson.
   Democrats, arguing against a change in the Constitution, said
nationwide interest in the issue has subsided after an initial
uproar. Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, said some lawmakers were
being driven by ``politics and fear.''
   ``There isn't any scourge of flag burning in this country,''
Metzenbaum said. ``It isn't one of those issues that the American
people are excited about.''
   Yet, he said, ``we are seriously thinking of cutting back on the
First Amendment just to avoid giving our opponents an issue. The
Bill of Rights is being held hostage to negative advertising spots
in the next election.''
   ``Can you imagine this?'' asked Sen. Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt.
``Some creep who wants publicity (burns the flag) and we seriously
think of changing the Constitution?''

</TEXT>
