<FIRST>r a PM-Hugo-Rescue     09-22 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hugo-Rescue,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Michigan Couple Rescued from Hugo's Chaotic Aftermath on St. Croix</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heeding a frantic radio call from St.
Croix, two men chartered a small plane and daringly rescued their
parents from the chaos and destruction on the hurricane-ravaged
Caribbean island.
   ``My father managed to get to a boat (Wednesday) and radioed my
brother and _ he only was on for a minute _ he said, `Do whatever
you can to get us out of here,''' Kim Sorrelle said Thursday. ``My
parents were in fear for their lives.''
   Besides the destruction from Hurricane Hugo, a looting frenzy was
reported on the island, which still lacks water, power and telephone
service. U.S. troops began patrolling the island Thursday under
orders from President Bush to restore order.
   ``My father said it's total anarchy,'' Sorrelle said. ``The
island is completely destroyed.''
   She said her parents, Bruce and Mary Langlois, told of seeing a
local National Guard soldier use his gun to break the lock of a
jewelry store to loot, and that people were firing rifles from
rooftops.
   Chief Warrant Officer Layton Timmons of the Virgin Islands'
National Guard acknowledged that the U.S. Coast Guard had videotaped
some guardsmen taking part in looting.
   ``When two people start looting, the whole Guard gets the wrap,''
Thomas said. ``Don't condemn the organization.''
   Sorrelle's two brothers, Joel and Bruce Langlois, flew from Grand
Rapids to Miami late Wednesday, where they chartered a small plane.
After several telephone calls to the Coast Guard and Federal
Aviation Administration, they received clearance to land in St.
Croix on Thursday afternoon, she said.
   Because the chartered plane had eight seats, the Langlois' also
rescued four other people and flew to Miami, Sorrelle said.
   ``My mother said she was never happier to see anyone in her
life,'' Sorrelle said.
   The Langlois own a wholesale grocery business and store on the
island and visit about five days every other month. They had been at
their condominium since Sept. 14.
   ``They said their building was the only one left standing in
their condo complex after the storm,'' Sorrelle said.
   The Coast Guard said Thursday that about 600 people had been
evacuated from the island.
</TEXT>
