<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     09-22 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Firm, Stocks Edge Upward</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed at 145.00 yen Friday, unchanged
from Thursday's close, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange rose slightly.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
274.44 points Thursday, added another 13.48 points, or 0.03 percent,
closing the week at 34,758.50.
   Currency dealers said the dollar remained in a narrow range ahead
of this weekend's meeting of the Group of Seven nations in
Washington. Speculation that Japan's central bank may step into the
market if the dollar rises above the 146-yen level also put the
brake on the dollar's upward moves, they said.
   ``The dollar's upswing has slowed down because players are
reluctant to buy any more dollars before the G-7 meeting tomorrow,''
said Minori Takeuchi, a trader with Chemical Bank in Tokyo.
   Financial ministers from the G-7 industrialized nations _ the
United States, Britain, West Germany, Japan, Italy, Canada and
France _ will gather in Washington on Saturday to discuss
international monetary policy.
   On the stock market, the market's main barometer started firm
with broad small-lot buying, but then eased with many investors
taking a wait-and-see position to watch moves in the exchange rates,
stock dealers said.
   ``With the approach of the weekend, the index failed to maintain
its momentum, reflecting the yen's declining trend,'' said a dealer
with Nomura Securities who spoke anonymously.
</TEXT>
