<HEAD>Rain Over Most of East; Cold Front Greet Fall in Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Hugo ripped into South Carolina today and rain and
thunderstorms that spun off of the storm were scattered across much
of the eastern United States, while an arctic cold front bore down
on the Great Lakes.
   Skies were clear over most of the West.
   Showers and thundershowers were reported Thursday from the Gulf
Coast north into the Ohio River Valley and into New England.
Thunderstorms also struck the lower Rio Grande Valley in Texas.
   The Great Lakes region was expected to usher in autumn Saturday
with a chill. A cold front approaching the area today could drop the
mercury 20 degrees overnight, according to the National Weather
Service, and frost is likely.
   Hurricane winds over 100 mph knocked out power to the entire city
of Charleston, S.C. and cracked the roof at City Hall. The storm
ripped off roofs and snapped and uprooted trees in parts of the
state.
   Temperatures elsewhere Wednesday afternoon climbed into the 90s
in much of Florida, the 80s across the south, the 90s in southern
Texas and the 80s and 90s in the desert Southwest.
   Other reports:
