<FIRST>u i PM-Quayle     09-22 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Quayle,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservative Leaders Warn Against Complacency in Battle for Liberty,
Peace</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TOK4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle and British Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher today told fellow conservative politicians not to
become complacent in the war against oppression, poverty and other
threats to democracy.
   ``Though there are many hopeful signs around us today, the
threats remain,'' Quayle said in a keynote speech to the
International Democratic Union. ``Indeed, some new threats have
appeared.''
   Quayle cited the proliferation of nuclear weapons and nations
engaged in chemical weapons research such as Libya and Iraq.
   ``Moreover ... the Soviet strategic threat remains formidable,''
he said.
   Japanese Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu, who as head of the
governing Liberal Democratic Party opened the conference of
politicians from 26 nations, noted that ``the evolution of arms
control and disarmament is moving toward dialogue and away from
confrontation.''
   Mrs. Thatcher joined Kaifu in urging support for democratic and
economic reforms in communist nations but said strong defenses were
necessary to counter military threats. She also reiterated her
opposition to unilateral reductions in nuclear and conventional
forces in Europe.
   ``It is our job as conservatives to make people aware of the
dangers and the vital importance of keeping our defenses strong,''
Mrs. Thatcher said.
   ``As we look round the world, there are still enormous problems
of conflict, subversion, oppression, poverty and environment ...
requiring our attention,'' she said.
   Mrs. Thatcher was to leave today for Moscow to meet with Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Conference speakers also cited global environmental problems,
drugs and terrorism as serious threats to mankind.
   ``We are all grateful that President Bush has mobilized the
enormous power of the United States against the drug cartels,''
Kaare Willoch, chairman of the International Democratic Union and
former prime minister of Norway, said in his report to the
conference.
   Quayle called on the other conservative leaders to support
democracies in Latin American.
   ``We must demand that the Nicaraguan government act now ... to
establish the conditions for genuine political pluralism and we must
act on our own,'' he said.
   The conference admitted a new member, the Movimiento Accion
Solidaria of Guatemala, to its ranks and elected Andrew Peacock,
leader of Australia's opposition Liberal Party, to be its new
chairman.
   On Saturday, Quayle is to visit U.S. military bases in Japan with
his wife, Marilyn. Next week, he is to hold talks with Kaifu and
other Japanese leaders before traveling to the Philippines and
Malaysia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
