<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--Korea-AIDS     09-22 0177</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Korea-AIDS,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>South To Reduce Scope of Mandatory AIDS Testing for Foreigners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans for mandatory AIDS tests for
foreigners have been drastically trimmed because of strong
opposition from other governments, the Health and Social Affairs
Ministry said today.
   Officials said the revised plans call for mandatory AIDS tests
for foreign entertainers and athletes staying in the country for 91
days or longer and for refugees.
   They said, however, that foreign entertainers and athletes who
are accompanied by spouses will be exempt.
   The ministry's original proposal also included foreigners
employed by Korean companies and government agencies, and foreign
students.
   Ministry officials said several foreign embassies warned that
their governments would be compelled to impose similar requirements
on Koreans if the original plans were carried out.
   Korean sailors returning home from overseas, prostitutes and
restaurant employees are required to be tested for acquired immune
deficiency syndrome. There is no known cure for AIDS, which destroys
the body's ability to fight disease.
   Forty-seven Koreans are infected with the deadly disease,
according to health officials.
</TEXT>
