<SECOND>PM-BRF--Britain-Exhumation,0151</SECOND>
<HEAD>Remains Of Exiled 19th Century Argentine Leader Exhumed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTHAMPTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of an exiled 19th century
Argentine leader were exhumed for return to Argentina on Oct. 1, an
Argentine official said.
   Descendants of Juan Manuel Rosas, a leading Buenos Aires governor
who died in 1877, gathered Thursday at a cemetery in the south coast
port of Southampton for the exhumation, said Julio Mera Figueroa, an
adviser to Argentine President Carlos Menem.
   Argentina tried several times to have the remains returned.
Earlier this year Britain, seeking to restore diplomatic relations
cut during the 1982 Falklands War, said it would not obstruct the
move.
   Rosas dominated Argentine politics for 20 years before being
ousted by rivals in 1852. He sought refuge in England.
   British and Argentine officials are to meet in the Spanish
capital of Madrid Oct. 17-18 to try to normalize relations.
</TEXT>
