<FIRST>u i PM-China-Entrepreneur     09-22 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Entrepreneur,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rong Yiren Says Recovery Will Be Slow, Foreigners Will Be Back</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEJ1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's top entrepreneur said today there are
still good profits to be made in the communist nation and he is
optimistic foreign investors will return despite the crackdown on
pro-democracy activists.
   Rong Yiren, chairman of the China International Trust and
Investment Corp., said it will take up to three years for China to
overcome its economic problems. He also expressed confidence that
his company, a target of recent government investigations, would
continue to prosper.
   Rong, 73, spoke to reporters as his company, knowns as CITIC,
prepares to mark the 10th anniversary of its founding as a highly
independent investment firm under the auspices of the State Council,
or Cabinet.
   He said China's economic difficulties were excessive growth, 20
percent inflation, energy and raw materials shortages and
profiteering. But he said the problems had eased somewhat under a
government austerity program that severely restricted spending and
put new market-oriented reforms on hold.
   ``My view is that in the future the situation may be a little
better, but it may take two or three years,'' Rong said.
   He said his company also is facing a tough year and profits could
be down from the record $64.6 million of last year.
   But he stressed that the recent government drive to reorganize or
shut down some freewheeling investment and trade corporations
accused of profiteering and corruption ``have nothing to do with
CITIC.''
   Rong said the company paid a $5 million fine imposed by the
government last month after a 10-month investigation into illegal
trading in foreign exchange, reselling production materials at a
profit and evading taxes.
   Foreign enthusiasm for new investment projects in China has been
dampened by the recent austerity measures and political instability
and tensions following the military suppression of the student-led
democracy movement.
   Rong said China International was pushing ahead with foreign
investment, and recently signed an agreement with Italian and South
Korean companies to set up a plastics manufacturing plant in Hong
Kong.
   The company also owns a bank in Hong Kong and has bought into
Cathay Pacific airlines, an aluminum smelter in Australia, a pulp
mill in Canada, timber in the U.S. Northwest, real estate in Arizona
and a steel plant in Delaware.
   Inside China, much of its investment goes to heavy industry,
although its 23 subsidiaries are involved in the banking, real
estate, trade, travel, hotel and publishing industries.
   Rong, scion of one of pre-Communist China's most wealthy
families, worked as a janitor during the ultra-leftist Cultural
Revolution.
   China's senior leader, Deng Xiaoping, asked him to put his
capitalist skills to work when China International was formed in
1979 to attract foreign funds.
   Although not a Communist Party member, Rong today is vice
chairman of the National People's Congress, the nation's
legislature, and chairs the All-China Federation of Industry and
Commerce.
</TEXT>
