<FIRST>r w PM-Sununu-WrightSeat     09-22 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sununu-Wright Seat,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sununu Blames GOP For Party's Failure to Win Wright Seat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Republicans narrowly lost a ``winnable''
special election for former Rep. Jim Wright's seat in Texas because
GOP officials ignored President Bush's offers to campaign there,
charges White House Chief of Staff John Sununu.
   ``The White House, from the very beginning, made it clear that we
were willing to send the president,'' Sununu said in an interview
published in today's editions of The Washington Times. ``We wanted
to send the president.''
   But Sununu said the Republican National Committee and the
Republican Congressional Committee ignored Bush's repeated offers.
   Democrat Pete Geren won the seat, which was vacated when House
Speaker Wright resigned, in a Sept. 12 special election. Geren
earned 40,210 votes to Republican Dr. Robert Lanier's 38,590.
   ``I was absolutely convinced from the beginning, and the
president was convinced from the beginning, that a Texas election in
a special election mode was winnable,'' Sununu told The Times.
   Neither RNC Chairman Lee Atwater and congressional committee
Chairman Ed Rollins was available for comment.
   Someone at the White House actually rejected a Sept. 7
congressional committee request for the president to make a
satellite television appearance, John Buckley, the group's director
of communications, told The Times. That decision was reversed the
next day after Atwater telephones Sununu aboard an Air Force One
flight to New Orleans, Buckley said.
   Bush talked live with the GOP candidate via satellite at a forum
of 400 supporters 48 hours before the polls opened.
   ``My understanding is they got everything they asked for,'' said
Leslie Goodman, a spokeswoman for Atwater.
</TEXT>
