<DOCNO> AP890922-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0555EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Philippines     09-22 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Clash With Leftists Protesting Quayle Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police clashed today with about 1,000
leftists protesting next week's visit of Vice President Dan Quayle,
and officials said at least six people were arrested.
   Officials also said military units in the capital had been placed
on alert following a series of bombings that killed at least two
people and injured 14.
   President Corazon Aquino said there was no evidence of a new coup
attempt but that the bombings could be ``intended to destabilize the
government.''
   Witnesses said today's clashes occurred as members of various
left-wing organizations tried to march to the U.S. Embassy to demand
that Quayle's visit be canceled. He is to arrive Tuesday.
   Marchers were blocked by about 30 policemen who beat the
protesters with truncheons and began firing tear gas, witnesses
said. Protesters then hurled small homemade explosives at the
police, injuring several officers and at least three news
photographers.
   Police said the six arrested included a Japanese student, Taizo
Hisano, 27, of Kyoto University.
   ``I can't believe what police did,'' Hisano told reporters as he
was being led away.
   Police said those arrested would be charged with illegal assembly.
   During the march, protesters unfurled banners saying ``Quayle,
you're not welcome here'' and ``Dismantle the U.S. bases.'' Leftists
have promised bigger demonstrations during Quayle's three-day visit.
   Several Manila newspapers reported the government was concerned
about a possible new attempt to topple Mrs. Aquino before she leaves
for the United States in November. She pledged to go ahead with her
visit to Canada and the United States despite the bombings and
military alert.
   Two people were killed Saturday when assailants hurled a grenade
in a crowded market area in downtown Manila. On Monday, 14 people
were injured in a grenade blast at another market. A third grenade
exploded Monday in suburban Pasig, but there were no injuries.
   ``The red alert ... was to abort more possible bombing
incidents,'' military Chief of Staff Gen. Renato de Villa said
today. He told reporters Mrs. Aquino had ordered the alert Thursday
and troops would increase mobile patrols and checkpoints in greater
Manila.
   Late Thursday, troops were stationed at the Mendiola Bridge,
about 300 yards from Mrs. Aquino's residence.
   Mrs. Aquino has survived at least six armed attempts against her
government since she took office after a popular uprising toppled
President Ferdinand Marcos three years ago. Similar small-scale
bombings preceded coup attempts in November 1986 and in January 1987.
</TEXT>
