<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890922-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0639EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HershLibelTrial     09-22 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hersh Libel Trial,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kissinger Sought as Witness in Libel Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorneys for a former Indian prime minister
are seeking the testimony of Henry Kissinger in a $100 million libel
suit against journalist Seymour Hersh.
   Attorney Cyriac Kappil said Thursday he was giving Kissinger the
opportunity to appear voluntarily before invoking a subpoena of the
former secretary of state, who was the subject of Hersh's 1983 book,
``The Price of Power.''
   Kappil also said he was considering using a videotaped deposition
made by Kissinger if he was unsuccessful in procuring his direct
testimony.
   Morarji Desai, India's prime minister from 1977 to 1979, has
accused Hersh of defamation for presenting Desai as a paid CIA
informant in the book.
   Hersh testified on Thursday that while he made some biographical
mistakes about Desai in the book, he was convinced of Desai's role
with the CIA.
   ``The thing that's important there is to know the sources were
sources I had the utmost confidence in,'' Hersh testified. ``That
was the driving force behind what I wrote.''
   Hersh acknowledged errors of fact _ among them the mispelling of
Desai's first name and the year in which Indira Gandhi, Desai's
rival, returned to power in India.
   The mistakes, which are not the subject of the lawsuit, were made
in the first printing of the book but corrected in later editions,
he said.
   Questioned about his accuracy in reporting and writing, Hersh
said his objective was to be truthful.
   ``I follow the truth, is what I'm trying to do,'' he said.
   Hersh, who testified that six sources told him Desai worked as an
informant for the CIA, acknowledged that in two 1983 interviews he
had said there were only two sources for this information.
   Under questioning, Hersh declined to reveal the name of one
source, an Indian foreign service officer in Washington, D.C. Hersh
said he submitted part of his manuscript prior to publication to the
source for verification of its accuracy.
   Under U.S. libel law, Desai's attorneys must convince the
six-member jury that Hersh knowingly printed false, negligent or
malicious material.
   Hersh won the Pulitzer Prize for international reporting in 1970
for his articles exposing the My Lai massacre in Vietnam. He was
also a reporter for The Associated Press and The New York Times
before resigning the latter to pursue his own writing and reporting
projects.
