<FIRST>r a PM-People-PattiDavis     09-22 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Patti Davis,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan Daughter Writes Novel About `My Father's War' In Nicaragua</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patti Davis, at odds with parents Ronald and
Nancy Reagan when she wrote her first book takes aim at a family
target again in a new novel about fighting in Nicaragua that she
calls ``my father's war.''
   ``Deadfall,'' the second novel by the daughter of the former
president and first lady, is a political thriller scheduled to hit
the bookstore shelves next week, about one month before the release
of Mrs. Reagan's memoirs.
   The book is about a young couple who try to make a documentary
film on the horrors of the guerrilla war in Nicaragua, with the plot
twisting around spies, stolen film, murder and evidence of America's
illegal involvement in the war.
   ``The CIA created, armed and financed the contras,'' said Ms.
Davis, 36, of Santa Monica. ``My father backed them with everything
he had. It was my father's war and almost everyone in Nicaragua has
lost somebody as a result of it.''
   Ms. Davis said her father's support of the Central American armed
conflict made it too dangerous for her to go to Nicaragua to
research her book.
   ``I couldn't go down there, being his daughter, and expect not to
feel those people's wrath,'' she said.
   Her first novel ``Home Front,'' about child smothered by her
father's political career, widened the rift between her and her
family. It created an embarrassing situation for Reagan, who was
sounding his frequent call for a return to family values.
   Ms. Davis makes no excuses, saying she had to write her first
novel honestly about something she knew _ even if the truth was
unpleasant to some.
   ``Anyone who hasn't been living in a coma for the last eight
years knows that we're not a close-knit family,'' she said.
</TEXT>
