<BYLINE>William Hammon</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEMINOLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William M. Hammon, a retired missionary and
physician widely known for his research on polio and tropical
diseases, died Tuesday at age 85.
   Hammon received the presidential Medal of Freedom in 1946.
   In the 1950s, he worked with Dr. Jonas Salk researching a vaccine
for polio. Hammon had been a professor of epidemiology at Harvard
University and traveled throughout Africa, the Pacific Islands and
Asia practicing public health medicine.
   He was awarded the Outstanding Civilian Service Award from the
U.S. Army in 1973, was president of several national medical and
scientific societies and was a consultant with the World Health
Organization and Pan American Sanitary Bureau.
