<TEXT>
   Murry Dickson, a baseball pitcher who
compiled a 172-181 record in 18 major league seasons in the American
and National leagues, died Thursday of emphysema. He was 73.
   Dickson pitched for St. Louis, Pittsburgh and Philadelphia in the
National League and New York and the old Kansas City A's in the
American League. His career spanned three decades from the late
1930s to the late 1950s.
   His best seasons were with the Cardinals in 1946, when he was
15-6 with a 2.88 earned run average, and for the Pirates in 1951,
when he compiled a 21-16 record.
   Dickson led the National League in losses three straight seasons
_ 21 in 1952 with the Pirates, 19 in 1953 with the Pirates and 20 in
1954 with the Phillies.
