<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0647EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-MedicalWaste     09-22 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medical Waste,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most Hospitals Properly Disposing of Infectious Waste, Survey Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While most hospitals follow uniform guidelines in
disposing of infectious medical waste, the offices of doctors,
dentists and other health care providers form a vast unregulated
source of potentially harmful waste, medical researchers say.
   The volume of medical waste produced by these other facilities
could exceed the 6,000 tons of refuse churned out daily by
hospitals, according to a report in today's Journal of the American
Medical Association.
   The researchers said one-fourth of the states don't regulate how
clinics dispose of their waste, while in about half the states,
doctors' and dentists' offices fall outside the regulations.
   There are 278,000 private doctors' and dentists' offices, 16,400
nursing homes, and thousands of walk-in surgery centers, dialysis
centers and blood banks across the nation.
   In contrast to the lack of control over these facilities, 44
states regulate hospitals, and the survey found that 82 percent of
the hospitals responding said they complied with disposal guidelines
developed by the federal Centers for Disease Control.
   Seventy-five percent of the hospitals in the survey complied with
waste disposal guidelines set by the U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency, which has a broader classification of infectious waste than
the CDC.
   ``I think it's generally good news that the vast majority of
hospitals are in compliance with the CDC and EPA recommendations,''
said Dr. William Rutala, administrative director of the Department
of Hospital Epidemiology of North Carolina Memorial Hospital in
Chapel Hill. ``I believe it indicates the seriousness with which
hospitals manage their medical waste.''
   Rutala led the team of researchers who compiled the study.
   He said that even in cases of non-compliance, no hospital could
identify an infection problem, excluding needle-stick injuries, that
was attributable to the disposal of infectious waste.
   Problems relating to medical waste disposal have come to public
attention due to concerns about the spread of the AIDS virus and
several highly publicized incidents. In August 1987, several hundred
tons of garbage _ including syringes and other medical waste _
washed ashore on New Jersey beaches.
   The researchers said that, at a minimum, ``the EPA should
spearhead a coordinated and consistent interstate approach to
infectious waste management.''
   Rutala said the survey data came from questionnaires sent in July
1987 and January 1988 to 441 randomly selected hospitals in 48
states.
   Infectious waste accounts for 15 percent of the total hospital
waste, the study said. The American Hospital Association estimates
that U.S. hospitals spend as much as $466 million per year to
dispose of such waste.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
