<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Also Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mostly higher in light trading late
this morning, but traders say its upward potential was limited until
this weekend's Group of Seven meeting is over. Gold prices also were
up.
   Investors are awaiting the outcome of the weekend meeting in
Washington of economic policy makers from the seven major
industrialized countries, dealers said.
   The G-7 nations are the United States, Japan, West Germany,
France, Britain, Italy, and Canada.
   ``No one knows whether we'll go up or down after the G-7,'' said
a dealer at a U.S. bank in Frankfurt.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar finished unchanged at 145.00 yen. Later, in London, it
was quoted at a higher rate of 145.38 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Thursday:
   _ 1.9445 West German marks, up from 1.9435
   _ 1.6845 Swiss francs, up from 1.6830
   _ 6.5745 French francs, up from 6.5710
   _ 2.1876 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1920
   _ 1,399.60 Italian lire, down from 1,401.00
   _ 1.1810 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1842
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5795 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5805 late Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $364.00 a troy ounce,
compared with late Thursday's $363.25. At midmorning, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $364.10.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $364.00 compared with $363.50 late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 26 cents to close at a bid
$364.37.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.17 a troy ounce,
up from Thursday's $5.14.
