<FIRST>r a PM-FrankEndorsement     09-22 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Frank Endorsement,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gay Rights Groups Urge Frank to Stay On</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gay rights activists and other longtime backers of
U.S. Rep. Barney Frank gathered in Boston to support the embattled
congressman in the face of an investigation into his involvement
with a male prostitute.
   A joint statement issued Thursday by the 13 local and national
groups endorsed Frank, arguing that the congressman has been
unfairly tarnished because he is gay. Similar scandals involving
heterosexuals have been much shorter lived in the news media, the
groups claimed.
   ``Much of the discussion of this matter has centered on Barney's
acknowledged homosexuality,'' said Steven Tierney, co-chairman of
the Massachusetts Gay and Lesbian Political Caucus, who read the
joint statement.
   The groups endorsing Frank included the National Organization for
Women, the Massachusetts Women's Caucus, the Gay and Lesbian
Advocates and Defenders and the AIDS Action Committee.
   They said Frank is entitled to a fair hearing before the House
ethics committee.
   ``Congressman Frank welcomes expressions of support,'' said Doug
Cahn, a spokesman for Frank.
   Several Frank supporters said that Frank's behavior in his
acknowledged affair with male prostitute Stephen L. Gobie and his
admitted solicitation of other male prostitutes had to be weighed
against his record in Congress.
   ``This happened two to four years ago,'' said Robert Wheatley, a
retired Unitarian Universalist minister. ``Barney has already gotten
his act together. He was honest and forthright and he said he made a
mistake.''
