<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Unrest     09-22 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Azerbaijani Blockade Prevents Armenian Newspapers from Publishing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armenian newspapers couldn't publish their latest
editions because a blockade by the neighboring republic of
Azerbaijan has cut off their supply of paper, the Communist Party
newspaper Pravda reported today.
   The newspapers printed Thursday in the Armenian capital, Yerevan,
would have carried major news: the shake-up in the Communist Party's
ruling Politburo that replaced conservatives with key players in the
reform programs of President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Pravda denounced the Azerbaijani action, saying: ``It is
difficult to believe that in our socialist government, one of the
union republics could find itself in an encircling economic
blockade.''
   Soviet press accounts earlier blamed the cutoff in freight
shipments to Armenia on striking Azerbaijani railway workers.
   More than 100 people have died in ethnic violence in the southern
republics of Armenia and Azerbaijan in the past 19 months, mosly
because of a territorial dispute over Nagorno-Karabakh, a largely
Armenian area within Azerbaijan.
   The main rail and road routes to Armenia pass through Azerbaijan,
and Pravda said today those routes remain closed. Even basic
foodstuffs such as pasta and rice have disappeared in Yerevan, it
said.
   ``The workers of the republic are finding themselves unwilling
strikers,'' because their factories have been forced to shut down
for lack of raw materials, Pravda said.
   Even the print shop of Armenia's Communist Party Central
Committee has not received a shipment of newsprint since Aug. 26,
the labor newspaper Trud said.
   Pravda said restoration in the area of Armenia devastated by last
year's earthquake has halted and that a team of Norwegians was
preparing to give up its construction of a 200-bed hospital and go
home because it has been waiting for their supplies for months.
   On Thursday evening, more than 100 Armenians in Moscow broke the
ban on demonstrations on Red Square to protest being driven from
their homes in Baku, the capital of Azerbaijan.
   Witnesses said Moscow police cordoned off the vast square
adjacent to the Kremlin, preventing other Armenians from joining the
protest and keeping foreign and Soviet tourists from the area. It
was not clear if the police forced the demonstrators to leave.
</TEXT>
