<FIRST>r a PM-KingDay     09-22 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-King Day,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Plans King Bill-Signing Celebration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Rose Mofford plans a bill-signing celebration
to enact a state workers' holiday in honor of slain civil rights
leader Martin Luther King Jr.
   The Arizona Senate voted 17-11, followed by a 37-21 vote in the
House, to swap state employees' paid Columbus Day holiday for the
paid King Day.
   The voting Thursday ended years of disappointment for backers of
a King holiday. Mrs. Mofford's signature will cap a struggle that
began in 1975 for King supporters.
   ``I'm delighted,'' the Democratic governor said, adding that she
planned to sign the bill soon in the state Capitol rotunda, ``where
there is plenty of room.''
   The holiday became a national issue after former Gov. Evan Mecham
revoked an executive order by his predecessor, Gov. Bruce Babbitt,
which some said enacted the holiday illegally.
   The uproar that ensued included protest marches, tourist boycotts
and convention cancellations by national organizations. Arizona is
one of only four states in the nation which does not have a King
holiday.
   Boosters said Arizona already has lost $256 million in convention
and tourism business because it has no paid King holiday and that
the state could lose $200 million in business if its bid for the
1993 Super Bowl is rejected.
</TEXT>
