<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0920EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Dance     09-22 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dance,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Indian Dance Company Is Enthralling</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Indian Dance Theater, its 23 dancers
and musicians coming from 17 tribes, is presenting a fascinating
two-hour show, through Oct. 1, at the Joyce Theater.
   The 15 dances, seen Thursday night, are said to be authentic,
traditional Indian dances, staged by Hanay Geiogamah, a member of
the Kiowa-Delaware tribes from Oklahoma, and Raoul Trujillo.
   One can enjoy them as dance or study them more deeply for
meaning. An explanation of each dance is written in the program.
   ``Hoop Dance,'' a solo by Eddie Swimmer, a Cherokee from North
Carolina, is remarkable. While dancing, he picks up thin metal hoops
and puts them around his body, knees and arms, at various angles,
until he looks like a man inside a cage. Notes say he has danced
with 42 hoops.
   Six men with eagle wings down their arms performed ``Eagle
Dance.'' As they walked through steam, they seemed to be soaring
over clouds. In a second version, as danced in another region, they
would squat and stand, again seeming to fly.
   Many of the dances had face paint, elaborate costumes in sunburst
colors, much fringe and headdresses. Dance steps were often a step
and hesitation or step and hop. Our interest was held less by the
costumes than on the countless, interesting variations of movement.
   In ``Buffalo Dance,'' Fabian Fontenelle, from the Zuni Pueblo in
New Mexico, who also plays drums with a rock group, Satschal's, and
Morgan Tosee, a member of the Comanche Tribe, had fur-covered heads.
They were kept in line by Lavina Colwash, of the Yakima Tribe and
Confederated Tribes of Warm Springs, Ore., and Cassie Soldierwolf,
from the Northern Arapahoe Tribe in Wyoming. Sometimes the buffalo
escaped the young women to butt their heads together.
   We also liked ``Drum Call'' by Wade Baker of the Hidatsa-Cree
tribes from North Dakota and Joe Bellanger, member of the Chippewa
Tribe, Red Lake Band, from Minnesota. The drumming was both a
challenge, like old-time jazz cutting contests, and a duet.
   The troupe was founded in 1987 by concert producer Barbara
Schwei, to develop greater awareness of American Indian dances,
dances done by many tribes and dances unique to specific tribes.
   A ``Dance in America'' PBS special has been taped, for airing in
February.
   A tour, beginning Oct. 10, takes the company to Calgary, Canada;
Billings and Helena, Mont.; Spokane, Tacoma and Bellingham, Wash.;
San Diego, Riverside and Los Angeles, Calif.; Tucson; Moorhead and
Minneapolis, Minn.; Indianapolis; Des Moines; Dayton; Skokie,
Springfield and Chicago, Ill.; Interlochen and East Lansing, Mich.
Then the company tours for six weeks in Europe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
