<FIRST>r i PM-Duarte 1stLd-Writethru a0472 09-22 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Duarte, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0472,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Duarte Improves But Remains in Critical Condition</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with improvement in Duarte's condition,
comments, edits to trim. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former president Jose Napoleon
Duarte's condition improved today, but he remained in critical
condition, his doctor said.
   Dr. Jose Luis Saca, Duarte's personal physician, said outside
Duarte's home that the ex-president ``awakened better, without a
doubt. But it is a relative improvement, within a condition that
remains critical.''
   He said Duarte, who suffers from liver cancer, was breathing
``much better'' and that he did not need oxygen this morning. The
former president slept about two hours last night and another hour
this morning before getting out of bed to drink milk and eat some
cold cereal, Saca said.
   Duarte continues to be connected to a plasma bag by which he is
fed intravenously and medicated. Saca said he would sharply reduce
the dose of sedatives Duarte has been receiving for the past two
days.
   ``He wants to be more alert to be able to talk with his family,''
the doctor said.
   Duarte, 63, spent most of Thursday in bed, saying brief goodbyes
to friends and colleagues who visited him at his home in this
capital's affluent San Benito neighborhood.
   His wife, Ines, and the couple's six children _ four daughters
and two sons _ were at his side throughout the day.
   Duarte rose from his bed in the evening and was seated in a
wheelchair, said Dr. Jose Luis Saca, his personal physician. He said
Duarte was having great difficulty breathing and was hooked up to
oxygen most of the day.
   ``He is very critical,'' Saca said late Thursday night. ``It is a
matter of hours _ maybe 24 or 48. But the fatal denouement could
also come any minute.''
   Saca said Duarte was being fed intravenously and was heavily
sedated.
   He said Duarte's liver was carrying out ``only minimal
functions'' and that his lungs had probably been damaged by the
spreading cancer.
   Duarte, a devout Roman Catholic, received last rites early
Thursday from his confessor, Monsignor Fredy Delgado.
   President Alfredo Cristiani, a rightist inaugurated June 1 as
Duarte's successor, visited Duarte Thursday to pay his last
respects. The two men have been harsh antagonists, but Saca said
their farewell was warm and that Cristiani's visit appeared to lift
Duarte's spirits.
   His cancer was diagnosed in June 1988, with one year remaining in
his five-year term as president. He has been in critical condition
since Tuesday, when his condition deteriorated sharply while he was
attending a meeting of regional Christian Democrats in Guatemala.
   Duarte had been receiving chemotherapy periodically until last
month, when he was judged too weak to survive its debilitating
side-effects. The treatment reduced the once-stocky engineer to a
gaunt shadow of his former self.
   Imprisoned by army rulers who took over shortly after he ran for
president in 1972, Duarte left the country and returned after a 1979
coup. He joined the ruling junta in 1980 and was named president in
December of that year. He was elected president in a popular vote in
1984.
   He failed to reach a peace agreement with leftist rebels fighting
the government for the past 10 years in a war that has killed an
estimated 70,000 people, mostly civilians. Cristiani's government
has agreed to revive the peace talks.
</TEXT>
