<HEAD>15-Year-Old Gets Six Years in Reform School for Killings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT W. TROTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARWICK, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 15-year-old who admitted he killed two
women and two girls in his neighborhood was ordered to reform school
for six years, the maximum term allowable under state law.
   Craig Price waived his right to a trial Thursday and pleaded
guilty to the four slayings _ three earlier this month, the fourth
two years ago _ and the two burglaries during which the killings
occurred.
   State Attorney General James E. O'Neil, who unsuccessfully pushed
for legislation allowing juveniles under age 16 to be tried as
adults on capital charges, expressed frustration that state law
requires Price be freed at age 21.
   ``It's a crying shame that it takes a tragedy to wake ... a
community up,'' O'Neil said.
   Price admitted to police in taped confessions that he killed Joan
Heaton, 39, and her daughters Melissa, 8, and Jennifer, 10, whose
bodies were found in their home on Labor Day, said prosector Jeffrey
Pine. Price lived two blocks from the Heatons and two doors from the
house where the prosecutor said Price confessed he killed Rebecca A.
Spencer in 1987.
   Family Court Judge Carmine DePatrillo sentenced Price to the
strictest section of the Rhode Island Training School, and ordered
that he undergo psychiatric evaluations.
   Price, who smiled and nodded in the direction of a friend as he
was led into the Kent County Courthouse, stared at the table before
him as the judge explained the plea arrangement to him.
   An autopsy showed that Ms. Heaton and her daughters suffered
numerous bruises and broken bones and were stabbed repeatedly.
Spencer, who had planned to move from her home the next day, was
stabbed 58 times, police said. Her death had remained unsolved until
Price was implicated in the other three deaths.
   Investigators said the 240-pound Price, a former high school
football player known as ``Iron Man'' who was repeating the ninth
grade, never showed any remorse for the killings.
