<HEAD>Man Guilty of Using Toddler as Shield in Gun Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man convicted of using a toddler as a shield
during a gunbattle that left the boy seriously wounded faces a
maximum prison term of 15 years.
   Sentencing for Eric Casseus was scheduled for Oct. 10 after a
jury Thursday found him guilty of assault, reckless endangerment and
endangering the welfare of the 3-year-old child, Gregory Alvarez.
   ``This defendant's crime, grabbing a little boy from his mother
and using him as a shield against flying bullets, was depraved,''
said District Attorney Elizabeth Holtzman.
   Elizabeth Sack Felber, Casseus' lawyer, said she would appeal the
verdict. Casseus, 19, told police he was an innocent bystander
mistakenly identified by the child's mother, Modesta Alvarez.
   Casseus, who was shot in the leg, did not testify during his
week-long trial. Prosecutors put Gregory on the witness stand to
show the jury his chest wounds.
   Gregory was walking alongside his mother Feb. 1 when members of
two youth gangs began firing at each other over drugs, police said.
   Mrs. Alvarez took cover between two parked cars with Gregory and
a younger child she was pushing in a carriage. Casseus, one of eight
people involved in the gun fight, grabbed Gregory and held him up as
a shield.
   Casseus let the child go after a bullet went through the boy's
chest and pierced his lungs. The toddler is still recovering.
