<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru   09-22 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0560,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Group Gains Legal Status</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads throughout to ADD more background on dispute over the
student union, past strikes, government complaint. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today legalized a
pro-Solidarity student union and upheld its right to strike over
political and school issues.
   Chants of ``NZS, NZS'' _ the Polish initials for the Independent
Students Association _ broke out in the packed courtroom when the
justices legalized the group, which was banned after the 1981
martial law crackdown.
   ``It should have happened a long time ago,'' said one student
among the 100 spectators.
   The students won the right to include a strike provision in their
charter, a clause that had blocked legalization of the association
even after the Solidarity movement was legalized in April.
   NZS is Poland's largest student union with a strong and vocal
following at universities and high schools. It is the last of the
Solidarity movements to be legalized following the ban on
associations independent of the Communist government that was
imposed after the December 1981 martial law crackdown.
   Since 1980, it has been an alternative to the
Communist-sanctioned Polish Students Association.
   NZS was denied registration on May 23 even though Solidarity and
the independent farmers union Rural Solidarity were legalized after
April accords reached in ``round-table'' talks with Communist
authorities.
   In May, the court said that the labor law did not apply to
students and that they therefore could not claim the right to
strike. The student association refused to change its charter, which
claims the right to strike.
   Registration was delayed again Sept. 9, even though Solidarity's
Tadeusz Mazowiecki had been installed as the East bloc's first
non-Communist prime minister and the government prosecutor told the
court it had no objection to the group's registration.
   Despite the ban, NZS has since 1987 been well represented at
Solidarity demonstrations and has staged its own protests to draw
attention to problems at schools, including low stipends, outdated
equipment, the lack of research and library materials and other
shortages.
   The pressure to legalize NZS grew as the Oct. 2 start of the new
academic year approached. There was concern that failure to register
the association would be met by student protests that could create
instability as the new government tries to reverse Poland's economic
crisis.
   Students, joined by professors and members of parliament,
celebrated the decision in the hallways of the Warsaw courthouse.
   ``At last,'' one said.
   ``We've been functioning anyway but it is nice to be legal
again,'' another said.
   Education Minister Henryk Samsonowicz, a Solidarity supporter who
was Warsaw University rector until he was removed under martial law,
met Wednesday with the national coordinating committee of NZS to
discuss the way the union would function after it was legalized.
   Student strikes demanding the group's registration took place
nationwide during the spring. Students also struck in sympathy to
workers during a wave of labor strikes in May and August of 1988.
   The students then put banners across the university gates, held
rallies, signed petitions, slept on the floors of academic buildings
and sometimes obstructed access to the campus. The government had
complained that the striked played havoc with normal campus life.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
