<FIRST>u i PM-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethru a0530 09-22 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0530,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tamils Kill Human Rights Activist; 18 Others Slain</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with human rights activist killed, two
deaths in Colombo. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A human rights activist was shot and
killed in northern Sri Lanka, witnesses said today, and the
government reported 18 other people were slain in ethnic warfare in
the south.
   Rajani Tiranagma, 40, was gunned down Thursday as she was walking
to her home in Jaffna town, 190 miles north of Colombo, said
residents who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Mrs. Tiranagma, a Tamil married to a Sinhalese, was head of the
anatomy department of Jaffna University.
   No one claimed responsibility for the killing, which witnesses
blamed on two Tamil gunmen. Tamils have been fighting for a separate
homeland in the north and east of Sri Lanka since 1983.
   Ethnic violence that has left scores dead in recent weeks
prompted officials to cancel a major memorial service for the late
Prime Minister Solomon Dias Bandaranaike, said memorial committee
member Upali Rupesinghe.
   About 25,000 people attended last year's ceremony for
Bandaranaike, who was assassinated on Sept. 26, 1959 by a Buddhist
monk. It is the first time the annual service has been canceled.
   Military officials and a government statement put latest
casualties at 18 people killed in five incidents in the south, where
Sinhalese extremists are fighting the government.
   Police discovered 11 bodies with gunshot wounds Thursday in
Heerassagala village, 55 miles northeast of Colombo, said military
officials who customarily are not identified by name. Identities of
the victims were not immediately known.
   Three Sinhalese militants were killed by government troops in two
incidents in the south, a government statement said.
   Two Sinhalese civilians were shot and killed by Sinhalese
radicals in Liyangolla village, 100 miles east of Colombo, the
military officials said.
   In the capital, two unidentified people were found shot and
killed in two separate incidents, military officials said without
elaborating.
   The People's Liberation Front, a Sinhalese group, started a
violent campaign against the Sri Lankan government after it signed a
peace accord with India in July 1987 to end a Tamil insurrection.
   The Sinhalese accuse the government of giving too many
concessions to the mainly Hindu Tamils, who account for 18 percent
of Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
   At least 5,000 people have died since the accord was signed.
About 11,000 others have been killed in the Tamil insurgency. Tamils
said the dominant Sinhalese discriminate against them in jobs and
education.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
