<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1134EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Mecham     09-22 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mecham,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Asked To Overturn Impeachment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Evan Mecham says the state Supreme
Court should have jurisdiction over his his effort to be reinstated
and that he should be paid more than $600,000.
   ``One of the very key things that the judicial branch is for on
the higher levels is to make sure the executive nor the legislative
branch violates the constitution and violates people's rights,''
Mecham said after a hearing Thursday in state Supreme Court on his
petition for special action.
   Mecham, who last year became the nation's first governor removed
by impeachment in nearly 60 years, is asking the state's highest
court to review his case.
   The ousted governor called comments by Justice Stanley Feldman
and Deputy Attorney General Kathy Cook saying they could not enter
into the case ``baloney.''
   Ms. Cook told the justices that the separation of powers
prevented them from examining the legislative branch's impeachment
provision, and Feldman appeared to agree, saying: ``We can't make
the Senate do anything. They are a separate branch of government.''
   Ms. Cook also said Mecham and his supporters ``suffered no
violation of their constitutional rights.''
   Mecham's lawyer, however, said lawmakers violated the state and
federal constitutions when they impeached and ousted Mecham last
year. He asked the justices to restore Mecham to office and pay him
more than $600,000.
   ``Either the constitution means what it says, or it isn't worth
the paper its written on,'' Mecham's attorney, Donald MacPherson,
told a packed courtroom.
   The justices took the case under advisement but did not say when
they would decide what to do with it.
   Mecham is running for governor in 1990 and wants the money to
help him in his new campaign. He was removed from office April 4,
1988, on charges he misused money in a state protocol fund and tried
to obstruct an investigation into the actions of an underling.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
