<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0601 09-22 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0601,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aoun Accepts Arab League Peace Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Beirut Life-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 3rd pvs, `I am...' to ADD that other side
already accepted the peace plan. Pickup 4th, `Ibrahimi...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian leader Michel Aoun today
accepted a seven-point Arab peace plan aimed at ending the
6-month-old bloodbath between his forces and Syrian troops, who
control 70 percent of the country.
   Arab League envoy Lakhdar al-Ibrahimi made the announcement after
an hour-long meeting with Gen. Aoun at his office in a bunker under
the bomb-ravaged presidential palace in Beirut's suburb of Baabda.
   ``I am glad to inform you that the general has accepted the terms
(of the plan) and has agreed that we start working to implement
them,'' said Ibrahimi, assistant secretary-general of the 22-member
Arab League.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem who heads a
Syrian-backed Cabinet vying for legitimacy with Aoun's Christian
government, and Parliament speaker Hussein Husseini, a Shiite
Moslem, have already accepted the plan.
   Shiite militia chieftain Nabih Berri and Druse warlord Walid
Jumblatt, who are Syria's main allies in Lebanon also have endorsed
it.
   Ibrahimi, an Algerian diplomat, was asked by an Arab League
committee to head a security committee to supervise the cease-fire
and monitor ships to ensure no weapons supplies reach Lebanese
factions.
   Aoun initially said he would not send a representative to such a
committee because it did not include a Syrian representative. He
said Syria was trying to portray the crisis as one among Lebanese
factions, even though Syrian forces in Lebanon are the main party
fighting his Christian troops.
   But France and the United States, traditional backers of the
Christians, and several Arab governments voiced support for the
peace plan and urged Aoun to display flexibility to avoid further
bloodshed.
   ``Thank God, all the brethren in Lebanon have agreed that we
start implementing this plan,'' Ibrahimi said.
   The Arab League plan, drafted by leaders of Saudi Arabia, Morocco
and Algeria, calls for a cease-fire, lifting of blockades and
opening Beirut airport.
   It also invites the 73 surviving members of Lebanon's 99-seat
Parliament to meet outside the country to formulate political
reforms. These would give the country's Moslems, an estimated 55
percent of the population, an equal share of power with the
traditionally dominant Christians.
   In another development, an oil tanker carrying badly needed
gasoline for Lebanon's besieged Christians played hide-and-seek for
three hours with Syrian artillery before slipping into port before
dawn.
   Police said the Lebanese-flagged Timex Star ran the gantlet of
radar-controlled Syrian shellfire to deliver its cargo of 660,000
gallons of fuel at Jounieh, 12 miles north of Beirut.
   ``The captain ducked into a bay north of Jounieh, putting
mountains between him and the Syrian radar and blocking it. Then he
hugged the coast to slip into port,'' a police spokesman said.
   The spokesman, who demanded anonymity, said the Syrians used
long-range artillery in Moslem west Beirut, from mountains
overlooking the Christian enclave and in north Lebanon, in their
effort to sink the Timex Star.
   The Christians, critically short of fuel after a 6-month-long
Syrian blockade, began unloading the fuel 15 minutes after the
tanker docked.
   Syrian attempts to sink the tanker caused an artillery duel
between the Syrians and Aoun's forces in and around Beirut that left
two people killed and seven wounded, police said. That raised the
toll to 929 killed and 2,738 wounded since the latest fighting began
March 8.
   The Christians control a 28-mile strip of coast north of Beirut.
With their enclave ringed on its three landward sides by the Syrians
and their Lebanese Moslem militia allies, the coastal strip is their
only lifeline.
   In the 14-year-old civil war, more than 150,000 people have been
killed and more than 1 million of Lebanon's 4 million people have
been displaced.
</TEXT>
