<FIRST>r w PM-JailedMother 1stLdWritethru a0479 09-22 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jailed Mother, 1st Ld Writethru, a0479,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Votes to Free Mother Jailed in Custody Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Deletes reference to Parris introducing the bill in the 2nd
graf; inserts new 8th graf with reaction.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation aimed at freeing a District of
Columbia mother, jailed for more than two years in a child custody
dispute, is headed to President Bush's desk after passing the Senate
early today.
   ``I haven't spoken directly with the president, but we're told he
is sympathetic and that the White House staff will encourage him to
sign it,'' Rep. Stan Parris, R-Va., said.
   The measure would limit civil contempt of court jailings in the
nation's capital to one year in child custody cases. Passed by the
House on Wednesday, the measure is drawn to deal with the case of
Dr. Elizabeth Morgan.
   Both houses voted by unanimous consent for the bill.
   Morgan was sent to jail in August 1987 after refusing a judge's
order to produce her daughter, Hilary, for court-ordered visits with
Dr. Eric Foretich, Morgan's ex-husband and the girl's father.
   Morgan has alleged that Foretich sexually abused the child, who
now is 7 years old. Foretich has repeatedly denied those charges.
   Morgan's attorneys have argued that her continued jailing
violates her constitutional rights. In August, a three-judge appeals
court panel agreed, ruling that because she is unlikely to produce
her daughter, the effect of keeping her in jail has gone from
coercive to unconstitutionally punitive.
   Foretich's attorney, Elaine Mittleman, said today the law is
unconstitutional and threatened court action to block Morgan's
release.
   The full District of Columbia Court of Appeals is now considering
the case.
   The congressional measure, which would apply retroactively to the
Morgan case, would allow prosecutors to file criminal contempt
charges after someone has been jailed for six months. That would
guarantee a jury trial before a different judge than the one who
issued the contempt citation.
   The measure would expire after 18 months.
</TEXT>
