<SECOND>PM-Israel,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspected Collaborators Clubbed to Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel-Uprising, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians clubbed to death two Arabs
suspected of collaborating with Israel, Arab and army reports said
today.
   The army announced it is improving procedures for notifying
families when relatives are detained, following numerous complaints
from lawyers and families unable to locate suspects in military
custory.
   An army spokesman said new detainees will be required to write
postcards to their family that will be mailed daily from detention
centers. There was no such procedure in the past, he said.
   Lists of prisoners also will be forwarded more rapidly for
posting in military government offices, he said, and families that
still cannot find missing relatives can appeal to the military
government for assistance.
   The new measures come after the Israeli Association for Civil
Rights appealed to the Supreme Court to intervene. The case was
dropped when the army agreed to implement new rules.
   At least 50,000 Palestinians have been detained for varying
periods during the 21-month-old Palestinian uprising, according to
the Israeli Information Center for Human Rights.
   Also today, a Jerusalem court acquitted a Shin Bet security
service agent suspected of negligence in the death of a Palestinian
during interrogation, an attorney for the agent said. The agent was
acquitted for lack of proof of the case against him, the attorney
said.
   Awad Hamdan, 23, died in custody in July 1987, two days after his
arrest for allegedly belonging to an illegal organization, a charge
usually applied to members of the PLO and other Palestinian groups.
   Israeli officials reportedly first claimed Hamdan died of a heart
attack or was bitten by a snake. The family later appealed to the
Supreme Court saying torture marks were visible on Hamdan's body.
   The mass-circulation Yediot Ahronot reported a pathological
examination showed Hamdan died of pneumonia which he may have
contracted during his interrogation.
   Palestinian suspects have often complained of being submitted to
cold showers during Shin Bet interrogations.
   A general strike shut down the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip
today. The strike was called to show solidarity with jailed
activists and deportees.
   At least 9,392 Arabs currently are jailed, 2,124 of them under
laws allowing the army to hold them without trial for up to one
year. Sixty Palestinians have been deported from the occupied
territories during the uprising.
   Masked enforcers beat 36-year-old Saeed Abu Jazar to death near
his Rafah town house in the Gaza Strip, Arab journalists and Israel
radio said. Arab reports said Jazar was accused of collaborating
with Israel and dealing in drugs.
   Also in Rafah, Nawal Abu Nims, 30, was reported hospitalized in
critical condition from a beating by masked youths who accused her
of being a prostitute.
   At Israel's Ketziot prison camp in the Negev desert, Palestinian
inmates killed another suspected collaborator, 23-year-old Karim
Abed Kareem, Arab reports said. The army confirmed his death and
said it was checking the circumstances.
   At least 116 Palestinians accused of collaborating have been
killed by fellow Arabs during the uprising, and 573 have been killed
by Israeli troops or civilians. Forty Israelis also have died.
</TEXT>
