<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1243EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     09-22 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Minister Tries to Assure Cambodians as Vietnam Withdraws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATTAMBANG, Cambodia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defense minister said Friday that
government troops can defend Cambodia against a guerrilla coalition,
despite a surge in nearby fighting that has accompanied the
withdrawal of Vietnamese soldiers.
   Defense Minister Tea Banh spoke at a farewell ceremony for
departing soldiers on the second day of Vietnam's troop withdrawal.
Vietnam has promised to have all of its 26,000 troops out of
Cambodia by Sept. 26.
   Officers from the two countries embraced, and hundreds of
townspeople laughed and cheered as girls tied Cambodian scarves
around the necks of Vietnamese troops.
   ``I'm very, very happy to be going home,'' said Nguyen Hoang Thy,
21, who spent three years in Cambodia. ``It's been sad because we
lost a lot of people fighting here.''
   Vietnam says more than 25,000 of its people have died in Cambodia
since it invaded on Christmas 1978 to oust the Khmer Rouge, which
killed hundreds of thousands of people during its rule from 1975 to
1978.
   The Khmer Rouge is the strongest in the three-party guerrilla
coalition fighting the government installed by Vietnam. Many
analysts say Cambodia's army, estimated at 50,000, is poorly trained
and led and could have problems fighting the guerrillas alone.
   In an interview with reporters in Phnom Penh on Friday, Deputy
Defense Minister Ke Kim Yan said as many as 450 Khmer Rouge
guerrillas were shelling the Pailin area of Battambang province with
up to 2,000 mortar rounds per day.
   ``We are mobilizing all our men so we will not lose Pailin,'' Ke
Kim Yan said.
   Pailin's forests and mountains could provide good hiding places
for the guerrillas, while gem mines in the area could help bankroll
the opposition forces.
   The guerrillas maintain bases along the Thai-Cambodian border,
not far from Battambang.
   ``We have built up our home forces both quantitatively and
qualitatively to the point that they can take the place of
Vietnamese troops in defending the territory along the western
region,'' Tea Banh told the farewell ceremony.
   Other farewell ceremonies were held in Pursat and Kompong Chhnang
provinces north of Phnom Penh.
   In the town of Pursat on Wednesday night, two hours of steady
artillery shelling was heard in the distance.
   Cambodian officials say 20 foreign observers are monitoring the
Vietnamese pullout.
   ``I won't report that I have proof of a complete withdrawal, but
we believe that Vietnam is withdrawing all its troops,'' said Bali
Ram Bhagat, an observer from India who watched the troop movements
at Battambang.
   At Battambang, townspeople lined the streets, cheering and waving
Cambodian and Vietnamese flags as the Vietnamese waved back from
their of Soviet and aging U.S.-made trucks.
   Orange-robed Buddhist priests showered the departing Vietnamese
officers with water in a blessing.
   India is the only major non-communist country that recognizes the
Phnom Penh government instead of the guerrilla coalition. Besides
India, the only official non-socialist government officials seen
observing the troop movements were from Belgium.
   China arms the guerrillas, while Thailand shelters them.
</TEXT>
