<FIRST>u a PM-US-Soviet 3rdLd-Writethru a0626 09-22 0910</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Soviet, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0626,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker, Shevardnadze to Consider Summit Date</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 8 grafs to update; picks up 6th graf pvs, Baker suggested...;
cuts last 5 grafs to trim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>JACKSON HOLE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III,
noting a ``new openness and candor,'' raised expectations today of
superpower arms control agreements as he opened talks in a lakeside
lodge with Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   The sessions, which wind up with a fishing date Sunday morning,
are designed to produce a general time frame for President Bush's
first summit meeting with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
sometime next year.
   The Soviets also are hinting they are in a mood to compromise on
some tough arms control issues. And Baker, posing for pictures with
Shevardnadze, took an upbeat stance.
   ``I believe and I think most would agree that there is a new
opennes and candor in our relationship,'' he said. ``And I think
that hopefully we'll be able to take some steps that are
unprecedented....''
   Shevardnadze, asked to comment on Bush administration statements
that a summit would be held sometime next year, said, ``We'll be
discussing this today.''
   Baker said, ``I think we will have an announcement before we
leave about a general time frame for this.''
   The two men began the day with a discussion with close advisers,
then spoke briefly to reporters on the terrace of the Jackson Lake
Lodge overlooking the Grand Tetons mountain range and a pair of
moose grazing on the flatlands below.
   In a meeting with several dozen aides from both sides,
Shevardnadze declared that ``it is high time to move from mutual
understanding to mutual action. Because, from our meetings, I
understand that conceptually there is a full understanding'' between
the two sides.
   Baker suggested that they move immediately to another meeting
with their closest advisers, forgoing a planned session with the
entire delegation, and allowing working groups to negotiate on sharp
reductions in nuclear, chemical and conventional forces as well as
other issues.
   The two posed for pictures before starting their two days of
talks deep in the Rocky Mountains that could set a course for
further superpower weapons cutbacks.
   
   Baker suggested that they move immediately to another meeting
with their closest advisers, forgoing a planned session with the
entire delegation, and allowing working groups to negotiate on sharp
reductions in nuclear, chemical and conventional forces as well as
other issues.
   ``We want to preserve and strengthen the improving international
environment,'' Baker said as he arrived Thursday night.
   Shevardnadze told reporters on his arrival aboard a U.S. Air
Force jet that his meeting with President Bush at the White House on
Thursday was ``a good beginning'' for the talks.
   ``We see the emergence of good prospects,'' the Soviet minister
said, although Bush said no summit was likely until near the middle
of 1990. ``We need some fresh ideas and hopefully the good fresh air
of Wyoming will help to bring them forward,'' Shevardnadze said.
   Shevardnadze, speaking to reporters after his meeting with Bush,
said, ``We have concluded that a summit is necessary. There is no
doubt about that.''
   Bush said in an ABC-TV interview Thursday night that there would
be a summit with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev. Asked whether
it would be early next year, he replied, ``I wouldn't say early.''
   A top Soviet arms control negotiator, Viktor Karpov, told
reporters that a ``deadlock'' over Star Wars strategic defenses was
blocking a proposed Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty (START).
   A senior U.S. official, however, later said, ``I don't think it
is correct to say there is a deadlock.''
   The Soviets want the Americans to spell out how they will adhere
to an agreement reached at the December 1987 summit that both sides
will honor the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty that curbs
strategic defenses.
   Karpov, reviving an idea broached in 1988, said the Soviet Union
sought agreed guidelines on the extent to which certain weapons
could be tested in space, an idea that the United States has spurned.
   Although no START deal is expected during the Wyoming meeting,
and perhaps not for the summit next year, Baker and Shevardnadze
were expected to announce several other agreements before they fly
to New York on Sunday afternoon for a United Nations meeting:
   _Chemical weapons: The two sides reportedly are close to an
agreement to exchange information on their chemical weapons programs
and to open stockpiles and plants to inspections by the other side.
Baker and Shevardnadze hope to resolve details, including whether
U.S. chemical weapons stored in West Germany would be covered.
   _Human rights: The two sides were to issue an agreement on
expanding dialogue beyond traditional issues, such as Soviet
emigration, to new areas, including occupational safety, the
environment and criminal justice.
   _Ice curtain: An agreement was expected to allow easier visits by
Alaskan Eskimos to their distant kin in Soviet Siberia, banned since
the Kremlin blocked passage across the Bering Strait in 1948.
   Although public attention centered on arms control and prospects
for a summit, Baker and Shevardnadze began their talks aboard the
plane with a discussion of the Soviet economy and the ethnic
problems that were dealt with at a stormy Soviet Communist Party
Central Committee meeting in Moscow this week.
   Shevardnadze ``discussed mistakes that had been made in the
past'' and explained how Moscow would grant some Baltic republics
greater economic autonomy, said one senior U.S. official.
</TEXT>
