<FIRST>r a AM-AirportName     09-22 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Airport Name,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Angry Over Plan to Rename Houston Airport After Leland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City Council members are being inundated with
calls from residents upset with a proposal to rename Houston
Intercontinental Airport after Rep. Mickey Leland, who died in a
plane crash last month.
   But Councilman Rodney Ellis, a Leland friend, said he would move
forward with the idea, which he hopes the council will consider next
week, even though most of the 50 calls his office received opposed
the name change.
   Renaming the airport ``is a fitting tribute for someone who has
served with distinction,'' Ellis said.
   Some council members said they felt torn between their desire to
honor thee congressman, whose plane crashed in Ethiopia, and to
adhere constituents' wishes.
   Councilman Larry McKaskle said he could not support the change
when his constituents were so overwhelmingly opposed. Councilman
Frank Mancuso recalled similar moves to rename the airport.
   ``Louis Macey (a former councilman) proposed to change the name
to Eisenhower Airport,'' Mancuso said. ``When Kennedy was
assassinated, they wanted to name it after him. There's going to be
an outcry over this.''
   Mancuso said a name change could be expensive because signs,
brochures and other materials would have to be reprinted.
   McKaskle and Mancuso said they would favor naming a street or
park in Leland's memory.
   In Washington, Sens. Lloyd Bentsen and Phil Gramm introduced
legislation Thursday that would name a downtown Houston federal
building after Leland.
</TEXT>
