<FIRST>u i AM-China-Opposition Bjt   09-22 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Opposition, Bjt,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exiles Hold Inaugural Meeting of New Chinese Opposition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Refugees who fled the violent suppression of China's
pro-democracy movement joined fellow Chinese from around the world
Friday to establish a new opposition in exile aimed at continuing
the battle begun on Tiananmen Square.
   The three-day meeting of the Federation for Democracy in China,
held at the Sorbonne, opened with a moment of silence to honor those
killed June 3-4 when soldiers marched into Beijing to crush the
student-led movement. Hundreds, and perhaps thousands, died.
   ``Bringing democracy to China requires that we battle together,
shoulder to shoulder,'' said Wu'er Kaixi, the 21-year-old Beijing
University student who delivered compelling speeches in Beijing's
Tiananmen Square at the height of the spring protests. ``Our
strength continues, we are hopeful. Be confident.''
   Among those in the crowd of about 500 were photographer Henri
Cartier-Bresson, actor Yves Montand, political leaders and human
rights activists from throughout Europe and four members of Poland's
once-banned Solidarity movement, which has inspired the Chinese
group.
   ``We Poles know the cost of freedom, human rights. Fighting for
these things takes a long time,'' Solidarity member Zbigniew Chlap
told the packed university amphitheater. ``We hope that before long,
it will be possible to establish in China this Chinese Solidarity.''
   Delegates to the meeting were divided into four regional groups _
China, Europe, Asia and North America. Thirty delegates and more
than 20 observers have come from the United States.
   Prominent Chinese exiles, including former Communist Party
members, artists, intellectuals, students and business people, plan
to use the meeting to establish rules for the federation and elect
leaders.
   The group will be based in Paris with branch offices in North
America and Asia, where significant support has come from Chinese
living in Taiwan and Hong Kong. The group hopes to mobilize the
support of more than 35 million Chinese living outside their
homeland.
   Many of those involved say the federation will serve as the basis
for an effective opposition party to Communist rule in China if
conditions ever permit exiles to go home.
   Wan Runnan, one of China's most influential independent business
executives before the crackdown, said the pro-democracy movement
``has moved from an emotional stage into a more deliberative one.''
   ``The Chinese Communist Party is very organized. In order to
challenge it, we must be organized as well,'' Wan said.
   He said the movement has suffered from a lack of strategy,
organization and clear goals.
   ``We can no longer depend on reform within the system to achieve
a better China. We must form an independent party to counterbalance
the Communists. Now is the time,'' he said.
   The federation, which emphasizes that it is independent and
non-violent, will push for international economic sanctions to
intensify China's economic difficulties. With that, it hopes to
force the government toward political change.
   Wan said goals include ending one-party rule and developing a
market economy.
   Chen Yizi, an influential adviser to ousted Communist Party
leader Zhao Ziyang and the most senior official known to have
escaped after the crackdown, chaired the opening session.
   In an interview before the meeting, he said economic conditions
in China continue to deteriorate.
   Inflation in the first six months of the year ran at an annual
rate of 35 percent in the biggest cities and 28 percent nationwide,
according to Chen
   During the decade that Chen headed China's Institute for Economic
Structural Reform, one of three influential think tanks, per capita
wages rose 260 percent for peasants and 70 percent for urban workers.
   Chen _ like Wu'er, Wan and others at the meeting _ is now on
China's wanted list, accused of ``counterrevolutionary crimes.''
Zhao was ousted for sympathizing with the pro-democracy protesters.
   On Thursday in Beijing, Chinese foreign ministry spokesman Li
Zhaoxing called the fugitive pro-democracy leaders ``criminals'' and
said the new federation is a subversive organization.
</TEXT>
