<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1427EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-GSAOfficial     09-22 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GSA Official,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>GSA Official Resigns After Security Probe Report Surfaces</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The acting No. 2 official of the General
Services Administration resigned abruptly after being told that
``adverse information'' about him had turned up in a security
investigation, GSA officials said Friday.
   The information surfaced a year ago but had been held from the
man and other top GSA officials, the GSA said.
   Richard G. Austin, acting administrator of the agency that serves
as the federal government's landlord, said David Godfrey submitted
his resignation as chief of staff on Sept. 15, effective Oct. 15.
   Austin said he had several conversations with Godfrey after
learning of information about him that had been turned up in a
security investigation.
   Dale Bruce, a GSA spokesman, said the agency's security office
had known about the information, ``or at least a portion of it,''
for a year but had not made it known to the administrator's office.
   ``I find this unacceptable,'' Austin said. He said he has ordered
two of his top assistants to ``review the process that we had in
place and ... assure that a similar situation like this doesn't
happen again.''
   Bruce described the information only as ``what we call adverse
information in his security file.'' Austin, however, said it
included ``possible substantial outstanding debts incurred in
Texas.''
   Godfrey was a Midland, Texas, banker, real estate developer and
business engaged in oil and gas operations before he became the
regional administrator for the GSA in 1987.
   A telephone call to Godfrey's office seeking comment was referred
to the agency's public affairs office.
   Bruce said security personnel apparently withheld the information
because, with the 1988 presidential election coming up, they
``thought the problem would go away and take care of itself'' as the
new administration took over.
   Bruce said the matter first came to Austin's attention about a
month ago, when Godfrey's name came up for promotion from acting
chief of staff to chief of staff. He said the acting administrator
sent the agency's general counsel and a representative of the GSA
inspector general to Texas to ``really look into the matter, and
they determined the seriousness of the problem.''
   ``The fact the information was not divulged over this period of
time is totally reprehensible,'' Bruce said.
   Sally K. Marshall, the GSA's personnel director, declined to
comment.
</TEXT>
