<FIRST>u a PM-Bush 5thLd-Writethru a0591 09-22 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0591,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Says Liberal Democrats Cherish Taxes.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs grafs 2, In remarks; 4, This election, and 10, Florio a
liberal Democrat, to update.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, taking a break from
foreign policy concerns to help a Republican gubernatorial
candidate, said today that liberal Democrats ``cherish new taxes
like moths drawn to a flame.''
   In a speech at fundraiser for GOP candidate Rep. Jim Courter,
Bush painted the gubernatorial contest as a choice between ``the old
and new New Jerseys.''
   He said Republican leadership would champion the environment,
education, jobs and the war on drugs, and that New Jersey's
residents should ``oppose those liberal Democrats who cherish new
taxes like moths drawn to a flame.''
   ``This election will decide whether New Jersey continues to have
the kind of leadership which balances a sound economy and sound
ecology...or whether its leadership says `no' to highter taxes and
`yes' to extending the prosperity of the last eight years,'' Bush
said.
   Organizers said the $500-a-person event raised $700,000 for
Courter's uphill fight.
   Bush interrupted his concentration on foreign affairs to appear
on Courter's behalf a day after meeting with Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard Shevardnadze to discuss U.S.-Soviet relations. He was
beginning a four-day trip that was to culminate with a United
Nations address on Monday.
   Before leaving for New Jersey, Bush attended a ceremomny at the
Justice Department honoring that agency's 200th anniversary. Then he
took the mike on an Agriculture Department radio call-in show and
fielded questions from farm broadcasters for about 15 minutes.
   In his radio remarks, Bush reiterated his support for a reduction
in the capital gains tax, now headed for House action, saying lower
rates would greatly benefit farmers when they sell equipment or
their farms.
   ``Half of all farms sold will be eligible'' for an exclusion from
paying higher capital gains rates under the measure supported by the
administration, Bush said.
   Courter is opposed by Democratic Rep. James Florio in the contest
to succeed Republican Gov. Thomas Kean.
   Florio, a liberal Democrat who ran a close campaign in 1981
against Kean, has been given a double-digit lead over Courter in
public opinion surveys. Kean is not seeking re-election.
   The Nov. 6 election marks one of two gubernatorial races in the
nation this year. The other is in Virginia.
   Today's visit by Bush was part of a hard-fought effort to keep
the governor's seat in the Republican column, and the president was
arriving as both Florio and Courter debuted their first television
ads.
   The campaign has been marked by controversy over abortion and
homosexual issues.
   Florio favors the right to abortion, while Courter has been
accused of vacillating on the issue. He has said he personally
opposes abortion, but would not force his views on state residents.
   Courter has also rankled homosexuals by saying he supports
legislation to bar them from jobs that involve children, although he
later softened the comment by saying he would not push for such
changes in the law.
   Bush will spend the night at his vacation home in Kennebunkport,
Maine, and then take a day trip Saturday to Boston, where he will
speak to a luncheon of the Archdiocese of Boston Catholic Lawyers
Guild.
   On Monday, he will travel to New York for his first speech as
president to the United Nations General Assembly.
   Aides have been working on the speech and were expected to factor
in the results of the Shevardnadze meetings. Shevardnadze and
Secretary of State James A. Baker III headed to Wyoming on Thursday
night to continue the discussions that began at the White House.
   A range of arms control issues were on the agenda as well as
laying the groundwork for a superpower summit meeting between Bush
and Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev at a yet-to-be-decided time.
   While at the United Nations, where Bush served as U.S. ambassador
in the mid-1970s, the president will meet with numerous ambassadors
and ministers as well as U.N. General Secretary Javier Perez de
Cuellar.
   Bush also will host a luncheon for heads of delegations and a
reception for dignitaries on Monday evening.
</TEXT>
