<DOCNO> AP890922-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1357EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-BusAccident 2ndLd-Writethru a0641 09-22 0830</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bus Accident, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0641,0850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Funerals Begin, Investigation Continues in Aftermath of Tragedy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to RECAST; SUBS 14th graf, `Investigators from...',
to CLARIFY that caliche is naturally occurring material.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos MCA3, MCA4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal and state investigators inspected a
delivery truck's brakes today to see if they could have failed
before it rolled past a stop sign and rammed a school bus into a
watery pit, killing 19 students.
   At least 64 people were injured after the bus was struck by a Dr
Pepper truck Thursday morning. Four students remained in critical
condition at hospitals this morning, including one who was
unconscious and on a respirator, officials said.
   The National Transportation Safety Board and the Texas Department
of Public Safety planned to inspect the bus and the truck throughout
the day, said DPS Sgt. Israel Pacheco.
   ``They're checking the mechanical condition of the vehicles,
particularly since the Dr Pepper truck driver was claiming that the
brakes failed,'' Pacheco said.
   Both drivers had records of traffic violations, the DPS said.
Truck driver Ruben Perez, 25, was convicted of speeding in 1987. Bus
driver Gilberto Pena, 46, was ticketed for running a red light in
March 1988, but records didn't indicate whether he was driving a
school bus at the time.
   Perez was treated and released Thursday, and Pena remained in a
hospital today in stable condition, officials said.
   The DPS said today that the number of people on the bus was 86,
including the driver, rather than 81 as previously reported. Pacheco
said several students who escaped the bus with minor injuries walked
away from the accident and were not immediately counted.
   The bus was designed to carry 83 people, said Herman Light,
quality assurance director for the manufacturer, Blue Bird Body Co.
of Fort Valley, Ga.
   Pacheco said state law allows for one student to be standing for
every student seated on the bus.
   Hidalgo County District Attorney Rene Guerra, who visited the
scene, said the case will be presented to the next grand jury.
   ``Presently, there may be some criminal negligence here,'' he
said. ``It might possibly be involuntary manslaughter if
recklessness can be attributed to the driver or the company.''
   The truck passed a state inspection last week, according to
officials at Coca-Cola Co., which owns the truck.
   NTSB spokesman David Rayburn said the investigation would include
weighing the truck and bus. The impact pushed the bus more than 40
feet.
   Investigators from the Texas attorney general's office also
probed the roadway and edge of the caliche pit, which had no fence
or railing. Caliche is the Spanish name for naturally occurring
substance often used in construction, generally made up of gravel,
sand and desert debris cemented by a porous calcium carbonate,
according to state geologist Bill Farr.
   More than 50 residents gathered at the edge of the pit until dark
Thursday, many still having trouble believing what happened.
   ``Half the school was crying,'' said Rosie Gil, 15. She said she
knew seven victims.
   Alton, population 3,000, and the larger neighboring city of
Mission, where the junior high and high school students were headed
for school, prepared to bury the first of the victims today.
   Aurora Hernandez sat with teary eyes in the lobby of Mission
Hospital Thursday afternoon, after visiting her 18-year-old
daughter, Sara Hernandez, in intensive care. Doctors, she said, were
pumping water out of Sara's lungs.
   ``I thought I was going to die,'' Alex De Leon, 18, said as he
stood in front of Mission Hospital in muddy pants and hospital
slippers, with cuts on his face and bruised hands. ``It just filled
up with water real quick.
   ``I opened up a window, took out my sister, took out a couple of
friends and it was already full of water, and you could smell the
diesel,'' he said.
   Four boats, firefighters from six departments and about 10 divers
helped in the rescue.
   ``We had to break the glass of the windows to get in,'' said Al
Nye, a diver who pulled seven bodies from the bus.
   All the dead were 12 to 18 years old, according to police.
   Students' families met with counselors and school officials at
the city's community center.
   Mike Cox, a public safety spokesman in Austin, said it was the
worst school bus accident in Texas history. The nation's worst such
accident was in 1976, when 28 Yuba City, Calif., high school
students and a teacher were killed after their bus plunged off a
freeway ramp. In 1959, 27 people were killed when a bus went into a
creek in Prestonsburg, Ky.
   Mission school Superintendent Ralph Cantu canceled classes today
and all extracurricular activities for the weekend ``because we've
had a tragedy. How can you be cheering at a football game when
something like this has happened?''
   A community memorial service was scheduled in place of the
football game tonight at the school district's Tom Landry Stadium.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
