<FIRST>u w AM-US-Panama     09-22 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Panama,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Accuses Noriega of Stalling on Visit of Rights Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Friday accused Panama
of engaging in widespread repression, alleging that Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega is refusing to cooperate with an Organization of
American States mandate for a human rights inspection.
   Deputy spokesman Richard Boucher said the Noriega-led government
has decided not to allow the Inter-American Human Rights Commission
to visit Panama until after Nov. 1.
   This move is ``clearly designed'' to ensure that the commission's
report on Panama won't be ready for consideration by an OAS foreign
ministers meeting that convenes Nov. 13 in Washington, Boucher said.
   The OAS issued a call Aug. 23 for the commission to visit Panama
``at the earliest possible date,'' he said.
   ``While Noriega uses delaying tactics to try to minimize adverse
publicity, the human rights situation in Panama continues to be
atrocious. Basic human rights such as freedom of the press and
freedom of assembly are denied,'' Boucher said.
   ``Scores of political prisoners remain in regime jails. We and
the rest of the international community look forward to hearing the
commission's report and we will continue to press for the
restoration of human rights and democracy in Panama.''
