<FIRST>r i AM-PandaBabies     09-22 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panda Babies,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panda Gives Birth to Twins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jingjing, a giant panda at the Chengdu Zoo, has
given birth to twins after being artificially inseminated, the
official Xinhua News Agency reported Friday.
   It was the second birth this year among China's captive pandas,
making it a banner year. The rare black-and-white animals, whose
numbers have dropped sharply in the wild to about 1,000, do not
breed readily in captivity.
   Xinhua said Jingjing's cubs, born Thursday, weigh 3.5 ounces
each. It gave no other details about them.
   Pandas refuse to nurse more than one cub at a time, so staff at
the zoo in southwestern China are nursing the second cub, Xinhua
said.
   Jingjing bore her first cub in 1987. The two latest were the
products of insemination with frozen semen, Xinhua said, a technique
that Chinese scientists favor.
   The Fuzhou Zoo in eastern China reported the birth of a cub in
June but did not say how the mother, Qingqing, was inseminated.
   Official tallies of the number of pandas in captivity in China
vary widely, but recent reports put the figure at more than 80.
Another panda in Chengdu's zoo, Meimei, has been given the title
``hero mother'' for bearing nine cubs since 1980. Six have survived.
</TEXT>
