<FIRST>r a AM-VailHousing     09-22 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vail Housing,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Shortage Hits Vail Mayor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VAIL, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rental housing is so scarce in Vail these days
that Mayor Kent Rose says he may be forced to resign and move.
   Rose's predicament is a glaring example of what some are calling
the worst housing crunch ever in Vail. With more than 5,000 seasonal
employees expected to arrive in the next two months, virtually no
rental properties are available.
   ``I'd like to stay in town and continue what I'm doing,'' said
Rose, a structural engineer. ``I've got two more years left on the
council. But, deeper than that, I`ve been here for about 18 years
now and would like to be able to live in the community that I've
invested in. This is really hard.''
   Rose learned just before Labor Day that the townhouse he has
rented for more than a year is up for sale.
   Unwilling to risk having to find a new home during the ski season
when rental property is next to impossible to find, Rose gave
himself until the end of this month to find a home for his family.
   If he doesn't find a place, Rose said he may have to look for
housing outside Vail, which would force him to resign as mayor.
   According to some property managers, rental costs have risen by
10 percent to 20 percent during the past year. And although there
are tiny efficiency apartments that rent for $400 to $600, the
average rent for a two-bedroom condominium runs closer to $800 or
$900.
   ``I don't know if (the seasonal workers) are going to find a
place to live,'' Rose said. ``I guess the old cord-wood theory
applies _ stack them in as tight as you can get them.''
</TEXT>
