<DOCNO> AP890922-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1519EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-USAirCrash 4thLd-Writethru a0620 09-22 1038</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USAir Crash, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0620,1067</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Box Yields No Useful Info on Crash; Crew Suspended, To Be Questioned</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with FAA spokesman saying pilot's,
co-pilot's licenses were suspended; tail section of plane lifted from water.
Picks up 10th graf, `The crash...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAYNER PIKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot and co-pilot of a jetliner that
careened into the East River had their licenses suspended and have
agreed to be interviewed by investigators, who hope they can explain
why they aborted their takeoff, federal officials said today.
   Information recovered from flight data and cockpit voice
recorders failed to explain the crash, which killed two women
passengers, officials said. There were reports of the pilot
vanishing and the co-pilot claiming his colleague had been acting
irrationally.
   Spokesmen for both the Federal Aviation Administration and the
National Transportation Safety Board said Thursday that they did not
know where the cockpit crew went after their USAir Boeing 737 ran
off a runway at LaGuardia Airport late Wednesday.
   But a spokesman for the NTSB, which is running the investigation,
said today that the absence of the pilot and co-pilot was not
unusual and had not hampered the probe.
   ``It's not at all unusual for us not to interview a pilot on the
same day as the accident,'' spokesman Ted Lopatkiewicz said. In this
case, he said, investigators arranged on Thursday afternoon through
the pilots' union and the airline to interview the pilots.
   Pilot Michael Martin and co-pilot Constantine Kleissaf have the
right to decline NTSB interviews, but if they do, the NTSB can
subpoena them, said Rachel Halterman, an NTSB spokeswoman.
   ``We've tried to contact him but we have not been able to do
so,'' Fred Farrar, a spokesman for the Federal Aviation
Administration, said Thursday.
   He added: ``There was no indication of why he was aborting. Until
we know why the guy aborted the takeoff, we have no way of knowing
the cause of the accident.''
   Farrar said today that the two had their licenses suspended, and
would have to go through a recertification procedure before they
could fly again. He said he did not know if the license suspension
was for the crash or for not being available after the crash.
   The tail section of the jet was lifted from the water this
morning, the Port Authority said.
   The crash of Flight 5050 late Wednesday split the fuselage of the
plane, which was headed for Charlotte, N.C. The tail of the plane
was partly submerged 10 feet from the runway while the nose skidded
onto a trestle in the river that held runway lights.
   Of the 59 survivors, including all six crew members, 45 people
were treated at hospitals and eight remained hospitalized as of
Thursday, according to USAir.
   Local law-enforcement officials were probing reports that the
co-pilot told Port Authority police shortly after the crash that the
pilot was behaving oddly in the cockpit.
   ``We suspect (Martin's) behavior may have played a part in the
accident,'' a law enforcement source said.
   Investigators quoted Kleissaf, 29, as saying that he was at the
controls of the jetliner as it roared down the runway and that
Martin started ``mumbling and acting irrationally,'' newspapers
reported today.
   The New York Times said the co-pilot gave his report to Port
Authority police, but Port Authority spokesman John Hughes said he
knew of no interviews that agency police had with the crew.
   USAir Chairman Edwin Colodny declined to discuss any possible
causes of the crash, saying the NTSB had jurisdiction.
   ``The captain is taking advice of his own counsel,'' Colodny said
at a news conference.
   Farrar said it was unclear whether the pilot or co-pilot was at
the controls during the crash.
   ``We've tried to contact (the pilot) but we have not been able to
do so,'' said Farrar. ``There was no indication of why he was
aborting. Until we know why the guy aborted the takeoff, we have no
way of knowing the cause of the accident.''
   The cockpit recorder had ``no noises or voices that suggested
there was any problem with the takeoff or why the takeoff was
aborted,'' said James Kolstad, acting chairman of the NTSB.
   The flight data show the plane swerved slightly instead of moving
straight down the runway and showed some ``deviations'' in rudder
movement, Kolstad said, but it was not immediately clear how that
might have affected takeoff.
   The pilot had flown 737s for only two months and the co-pilot was
in a 737 cockpit crew for the first time, the Times reported,
quoting airline industry officials.
   Officials said whoever was at the controls of the plane radioed
the control tower that he was aborting takeoff moments before the
jet slid into the East River.
   Survivors clung to the wings of the broken aircraft or grasped
driftwood after the plane slid into the water.
   ``The pilot seemed to be accelerating but didn't have enough
power to get the plane up,'' passenger Larry Martin said. ``He put
on the brakes. The plane took a dip and the next thing I knew all
hell broke loose.''
   Stunned passengers scrambled out doors and onto wings. Some
escaped down an emergency chute and found themselves in about 25
feet of water.
   Flight attendants threw them seat cushions, which are designed to
float.
   Police scuba divers freed some 15 people from the cabin, while
rescuers in boats scooped people from the water and wings.
   ``We just grabbed on to a big piece of wood and held on for dear
life,'' said passenger Tom Newberry, 27, who was heading to North
Carolina to be married Saturday.
   Police said the two passengers killed were Betsy Brogan, 37, of
Gray, Tenn., and her mother-in-law, Alyce Brogan, 69, of Vixton, Va.
   Port Authority officials said light rain at the time of the crash
was not a factor. The Port Authority of New York and New Jersey
operates the airport.
   The plane was delivered in January and had no history of
mechanical problems, USAir spokeswoman Nancy Vaughan said.
   In June, the FAA ordered most Boeing 737-400s grounded because of
two incidents in which engines failed. Airlines were ordered to
replace certain engine parts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
