<HEAD>Deer Wanders Into BART Tunnel; Police Shoot Injured Animal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deer wandered into a subway tunnel and
delayed thousands of commuters for 1{ hours Friday morning, and
police later shot the animal after it was hit by a train.
   The deer was about a mile and a half into the 3\-mile-long
Berkeley Hills tunnel that carries BART commuters between Concord
and Daly City, said Bay Area Rapid Transit System spokesman Sy
Mouber.
   The deer was first spotted at 7 a.m. by a Daly City-bound train.
A 7:38 a.m. train then hit the deer, leading BART officials to
believe the animal had left.
   But a 7:56 a.m. train again spotted the deer up and running in
the tunnel. BART officials cut off power on the tunnel line shortly
after 9 a.m. and began working to remove the deer. Trains moved on
only one track, causing delays because trains had to move in both
directions.
   BART police shot the deer because it was injured and officials
believed it could threaten workers, Mouber said.
</TEXT>
