<FIRST>r a AM-BoyShot     09-22 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boy Shot,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Sentenced To Up To 15 Years For Child's Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge wept as he sentenced a man to the
maximum term in prison for shooting a 7-year-old boy during a drug
dispute.
   Lonnie Summers, 22, was sentenced to 12{ to 15 years on Thursday
by Common Pleas Judge Marvin R. Halbert. Summers also was ordered to
pay $500,000 in restitution, a $25,000 fine and $2,000 in court
costs.
   Summers was convicted last December of wounding Ralph Brooks Jr.
during a drug shootout in south Philadelphia. The boy, who had been
playing in his grandparents' yard, was left paralyzed from the waist
down by a .45-caliber bullet that severed his spine.
   Halbert dabbed his eyes with a tissue several times while reading
statements written by Kimberly Brooks, the boy's mother, and Barbara
White, Ralph's grandmother, on the costs of the child's medical
treatment and the emotional trauma. The judge's shoulders heaved
slightly as he spoke.
   Tears rolled down Assistant District Attorney Rayford Means' face
as he described the effect the shooting has had on the child's life
and his family.
   ``He will never experience dancing with a date at a prom or
walking his girlfriend home or playing baseball,'' Means said. ``Not
only is Ralph Brooks Jr. living a miserable life, so is his family.''
   The boy undergoes therapy once a week and must be turned at least
every three hours while he sleeps, Means said.
   During the hearing, Means produced witnesses who said the
neighborhood where the Brooks family lives has become a safer,
cleaner environment since the shooting. The children's neighborhood
playground has been renamed in honor of the 7-year-old.
   Referring to that testimony, Summers' lawyer, Eugene Tinari, said
afterward his client has been made a ``scapegoat'' in the city's war
on drugs.
   ``The prosecution is saying now that we have him, that is the end
of the problem,'' Tinari said.
   Tinari said he will file a motion within 10 days asking for a
reduction in sentence.
   The child's parents, Kimberly and Ralph Sr., who sat two rows
behind Summers during the proceedings, shied away from cameras.
Ralph was in school, Mrs. White said.
</TEXT>
