<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Convent     09-22 0526</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Convent,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Glemp Says `Significant Progress' Made in Convent Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal Jozef Glemp, leader of the
country's Roman Catholic Church, on Friday announced ``significant
progress'' toward ending the dispute over a convent at Auschwitz.
   His remarks came one day after Jewish leaders in London reported
Glemp agreed in a letter to move the convent from the perimeter of
the former Nazi death camp in southern Poland. On Tuesday, the
Vatican issued a statement saying it should be moved.
   On his return from London on Friday, Glemp spoke to reporters and
briefly praised British Jewish leaders for their ``calm'' approach
to the controversy.
   ``That is why there is significant progress (that) ... will
influence positively the conclusion of this argument,'' he said.
   He did not refer to the London letter, and reporters did not ask
him about it. However, he said: ``We understand better what it means
in the Jewish sense to respect a place that is sacred.''
   Glemp noted Jews and Christians have different traditions about
cemeteries, with Christians more likely to put places of worship at
burial grounds.
   The primate had opposed moving the convent despite an agreement
between Catholic cardinals and Jewish leaders that the Carmelite
nuns would be moved to an interfaith cultural center away from the
camp. The center has not been built.
   Although the Polish church has made no official statement, all
indications were that Glemp bowed to the wishes of Polish-born Pope
John Paul II and will no longer oppose the move.
   Stefan Wilkanowicz, acting as a mediator in the conflict on
behalf of Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki, said Thursday night
that the decision to move the convent had been settled.
   The convent angered many Jews who suspect the Catholic church of
trying to insert itself into what they regard as a Jewish
catastrophe. Of the 4 million who died at Auschwitz, 2.5 million
were Jews.
   The Solidarity newspaper Gazeta Wyborcza Friday published for the
first time in Poland a 1987 agreement in which the church originally
agreed to move the convent. It also published the text of the
Vatican statement, which had not been prominently carried by state
media.
   Auschwitz could be considered ``the biggest cemetery in the
history of the Jewish nation,'' the newspaper said.
   The church failed to meet a Feb. 22 deadline to relocate the
nuns. That deadline was in the 1987 agreement signed in Geneva by
Jewish leaders and Archbishop Franciszek Macharski of Krakow.
   After protests, Macharski last month said the 1987 commitment
could not be fulfilled because of the ``aggressive'' atmosphere.
   The Glemp letter was made public in London by Sir Sigmund
Sternberg, a philanthropist who heads the International Council of
Christians and Jews. Glemp handed the letter to Sternberg at a
dinner at the Polish Embassy in London on Tuesday.
   It said: ``It is essential not only to move the convent outside
the perimeter of the site, but also to set up the new cultural
center.''
   Shimon Cohen, a spokesman for the chief rabbi of Britain, Lord
Immanuel Jakobovits, said the letter ``will undoubtedly be a
substantial contribution to restoring Catholic-Jewish harmony.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
