<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Ethics     09-22 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Ethics,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ethics Post Contender Withdrawn From Consideration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AssociatePress Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Houston judge and religious leader who was
President Bush's choice to head the Office of Government Ethics has
been removed from consideration for the post as the result of an FBI
background check, White House officials said Friday.
   One official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that Paul
Pressler was taken out of the running because of a ``personal
situation'' unearthed by the FBI probe and not because there was any
evidence of wrongdoing.
   Pressler is a Houston civil court judge and a national leader of
the fundamentalist movement within the Southern Baptist Convention.
   Pressler, who was in San Francisco on Friday, could not be
reached for comment. A woman answering the phone at his hotel
extension said ``he's not taking any calls from reporters.''
   The Washington Post, which first reported that Pressler's name
had been removed from consideration in a story in Friday's editions,
cited ``ethics problems'' in the background of the man Bush wanted
to run the ethics office.
   White House officials confirmed the account but said, without
further elaboration, that the problem was one of a potential ethical
problem. ``He just wasn't the right man for the job,'' said one
official.
   Thus, the job remains vacant even though Bush made the post a
major issue in his 1988 election campaign and promised to name a
tough administrator to head the office shortly after taking office
last January.
   ``It's a position of great importance for the president. We're
looking for the best candidate,'' said deputy press secretary Alixe
Glen.
   Pressler's name was sent to the Federal Bureau of Investigation
in July for a routine background check.
   The ethics position, part of the Office of Personnel Management,
reviews personal financial filings of federal oficials and
interprets conflict-of-interest laws and rules.
   The Post said that Pressler had been a controversial candidate
for the post even before the FBI check ``because of the key role he
played in the fundamentalist movement,'' one that ``would buy more
animosity than good will.''
   During his campaign, Bush made ethics-in-government a major
issue. In a July 1988 campaign speech, for instance, he said he
would enforce an ``exacting code of conduct.''
   ``To give effect to this commitment, I will establish an office
at the highest level of government _ that of senior counselor to the
president, whose first responsibility will be ethics.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
