<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Refuseniks     09-22 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Refuseniks,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Jewish Refuseniks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Friday arrested a group of Jewish
refuseniks who demonstrated near the Kremlin to push for their right
to emigrate, a witness said.
   The demonstration was timed to coincide with meetings in
Washington between Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze and
President Bush and other U.S. officials.
   Vadim Kotlyar said his uncle, Mark Kotlyar, and most of a group
of about 30 demonstrators were hustled onto buses by police about
five minutes after they began their demonstration on the steps of
the Lenin Library in downtown Moscow.
   Kotlyar, a Soviet emigre who now lives in Sun Valley, Idaho, said
police told the protesters they did not have official permission for
the demonstration.
   No force was used in arresting the demonstrators, and no one
resisted, he said.
   ``The people were taken into buses,'' Kotlyar said. ``It seemed
that almost all of them were detained. It was done very swiftly.''
   His uncle, from Kiev, has been denied permission to emigrate for
more than a decade because Soviet officials claim he has access to
state secrets, Kotlyar said.
   One of the leaders of the group, Alexander Rappoport, was
sentenced to five days in jail, said his wife Elena.
   Three others were given jail sentences and the remainder of those
arrested were fined and released, she said.
   The law requires that demonstrators receive permission from city
authorities to hold demonstrations. But protesters say that in many
cases city authorities deny permission for no reason or never
respond.
   Refuseniks regularly call demonstrations during meetings between
Soviet and U.S. officials to publicize their plight.
   U.S. officials say human rights questions are among those that
they are planning to discuss with Shevardnadze.
   Jewish emigration from the Soviet Union has climbed rapidly in
the last two years.
   More than 30,000 have emigrated already this year, including
6,000 who left last month, according to figures of the
Intergovernmental Committee on Migration in Geneva.
   The increase has created a huge backlog of Soviet Jews who wish
to settle in the United States.
   But others are denied permission to emigrate either because of
their alleged access to state secrets or because relatives refuse to
waive financial claims against them.
</TEXT>
