<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Americans     09-22 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Americans,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Ban Two U.S. Citizens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two American citizens of Latvian descent have been
barred from entering the Soviet Union for the next five years for
allegedly violating travel restrictions, the Tass news agency said
Friday.
   According to Tass, Juris Kaza and Peteris Elferts came to Latvia
with valid visas but broke regulations by traveling to areas closed
to foreigners. It did not say whether the two already have left the
Soviet Union, nor did it indicate where they are from in the United
States.
   KGB secret police in Riga, the Latvian capital, told Tass that
Kaza arrived on a tourist visa.
   ``He sneaked into a helicopter on Aug. 23, used by a camera team
of Latvian television, to fly over a wooded area, and filmed
territory closed to foreigners,'' Tass said.
   Aug. 23 was the date of a demonstration throughout the Baltic
republics marking the 50th anniversary of a secret agreement between
Josef Stalin and Adolf Hitler dividing Eastern Europe into spheres
of influence on the eve of World War II. More than a million Baltic
residents joined hands in a human chain to mark the anniversary.
   Tass reported that around the same time, Elferts was in Latvia at
the invitation of friends and frequently traveled to closed areas.
   ``In one of the regions, he filmed a guarded military facility,''
it said.
   Tass also said Elferts refused to register with police, as
required of all visitors.
</TEXT>
