<FIRST>r i AM-BuddDeath     09-22 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budd Death,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zola Budd's Father Fatally Shot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The father of track star Zola
Budd was found shot to death at his farm and apparently was
murdered, police said Friday.
   Frank Budd, 56, suffered two shotgun wounds to his left side
Thursday evening at his home near the central city of Bloemfontein,
said Sgt. Marelize Visagie. She said a truck and shotgun were
missing from the farmhouse.
   ``I don't know what to say. What can a person say?'' Ms. Budd,
23, said on learning of her father's death.
   Ms. Budd and her father did not communicate in recent years and
he did not attend his daughter's April 15 wedding in Bloemfontein.
   Budd, a retired printer, was divorced from Ms. Budd's mother and
lived alone. The independent South African Press Association
described him as a ``bitter man'' estranged from most of his family.
   Ms. Budd's career has been dogged by bans barring South African
athletes from international competition because of the country's
policies of race discrimination.
   She left South Africa for Britain in 1984 and, amid controversy,
was hurriedly granted a British passport so she could compete in the
1984 Summer Olympics in Los Angeles.
   Ms. Budd set several distance-running world records and twice won
the world cross-country championship while living and training in
Britain. But she was pursued by anti-apartheid protesters who said
she should not be allowed to compete.
   In May 1988, she returned to South Africa suffering complete
mental exhaustion, according to her coach John Bryant.
   When Ms. Budd married South African businessman Mike Pieterse,
she indicated she would remain in her homeland indefinitely.
   She recently won a six-mile road race in Bloemfontein, her first
competition in South Africa since she went to Britain five years ago.
</TEXT>
