<FIRST>r w AM-PersonalIncome     09-22 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Personal Income,1st Ld-Writethru a0648,,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bargains Account for August Spending Gain Despite Slower Incomes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 11th graf pvs `Personal consumption ...' with 1 graf to
INSERT dropped word `billion' in figure $21.1 billion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumers taking advantage of bargains
increased their spending in August by 0.9 percent even though
incomes rose only 0.4 percent, the government said Friday in another
report pointing toward continued economic expansion.
   The Commerce Department said the jump in consumer spending
followed a 0.6 percent gain in July and was the largest since a 1.1
percent advance in April.
   Income growth, meanwhile, slowed from a 0.7 percent advance in
July, in large part because of strikes against several major
telephone companies. Nevertheless, personal incomes have increased
for nine consecutive months.
   ``Consumers are still basically positive in their attitudes,
largely based on a favorable job outlook,'' said David Jones, an
economist with Aubrey Lanston &amp; Co., a New York government
securities dealer.
   ``As long as the job sector holds up, and it certainly seems
likely to do so, I think consumers will continue to spend, at least
when they're given a bargain.''
   Jones pointed to strong rebate-induced sales of automobiles in
August as an example of consumer bargain-buying and a major element
of that month's consumer spending gain.
   ``In a sense, that's good,'' he said. ``As long as consumers buy
only when given a bargain, that will limit the potential for
inflation.''
   William K. MacReynolds, forecasting director for the U.S. Chamber
of Commerce, also attributed the boost in consumer spending in part
on declining prices and said the report ``indicates that consumer
confidence will keep the economy from slipping into a deep
downturn.''
   ``This is a good sign for businesses which have suffered from
slow growth in consumption and falling profits since last October,''
he said.
   Consumer spending is watched closely as a barometer of economic
health because it accounts for about two-thirds of the nation's
economic activity. Other recent reports show an economy continuing
to grow, although at a slower pace as the Federal Reserve continues
to keep short-term interest rates high to contain inflation.
   Personal consumption spending, which includes everything except
interest payments on debt, rose $31.8 billion in August, compared
with a $21.1 billion advance in July.
   Purchases of durable goods, cars and other big-ticket items
expected to last more than three years, rose $22.9 billion after
gaining $3.4 billion in July.
   MacReynolds said the resurgence in durables spending doesn't
create new inflationary pressures because prices in that sector have
risen less than 2 percent in the last year and ``durables production
has lagged behind the rest of the economy, leaving ample capacity to
expand.''
   Non-durable goods purchases fell $3.6 billion after increasing
$4.8 billion in the previous month.
   Purchases of services, which includes housing costs, rose $12.5
billion compared with a $13 billion increase in July.
   Americans' disposable, or after-tax income rose 0.4 percent in
August, down slightly from a 0.7 percent after-tax increase in July.
But their savings rate, savings as a percent of disposable income,
fell 6.7 percent after gaining 1.7 percent in the previous month.
   The key component of the income category, wages and salaries,
decreased $9.2 billion in August compared with a $23.5 billion
increase in July. Payrolls at manufacturing companies rose by $3.2
billion, up from a July increase of $2.1 billion.
   Overall, personal consumption spending came in at an annual rate
of $3.51 trillion in August after $3.48 trillion in July.
   Personal incomes totaled $4.47 trillion at an annual rate in
August after a revised $4.45 trillion in July.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
