<FIRST>u w AM-IRAs     09-22 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IRAs,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nearly Half of Benefits from Democrats' IRA Proposal Would Aid the
Well-off</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Budget-Taxes, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly half the benefit of a Democratic
proposal to allow all workers tax-deductible Individual Retirement
Accounts would go to those with incomes above $75,000, the Senate
Finance Committee said Friday.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, chairman of the committee and author
of the IRA proposal, released the figures to show that the plan
still would provide far less benefit to the richest Americans than
would President Bush's competing plan to cut the capital-gains tax.
   The capital-gains cut recommended by Bush would deliver 15.1
percent of its benefits to those with incomes under $75,000,
according to a study by the staff of the Joint Committee on
Taxation. That compares with 50.9 percent for Bentsen's bill and
14.7 percent for the capital-gains cut voted by the House Ways and
Means Committee.
   At the other end of the income scale, those over $200,000 a year
would get 6.7 percent of the tax benefits of the IRA proposal, 60
percent of Bush's capital-gains reduction and 60.2 percent of the
Ways and Means cut in capital-gains taxes.
   The Finance Committee staff noted that the estimates do not take
into account that Bentsen's proposal would permit penalty-free
withdrawals from IRAs to make the down payemnt on a first home or to
pay for a college education.
   ``It is anticipated that those proposals would provide even more
benefits to lower- and middle-income Americans,'' the Finance
Committee staff wrote.
   The House may consider next week a plan by the Democratic
leadership to eliminate the capital-gains cut from the Ways and
Means bill and substitute the IRA expansion. Democrats contend IRAs
would do more to encourage saving than would a capital-gains
reduction.
   The 1986 tax overhaul restricted tax-deductible IRAs to
lower-income workers and to those with higher incomes who are not
covered by company pensions.
   Bentsen's plan would allow any worker regardless of income who is
not now eligible for a fully deductible IRA to deduct up to $1,000 a
year in contributions.
</TEXT>
