<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia-ToxicRum     09-22 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Toxic Rum,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>21 Dead After Drinking Toxic White Rum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARRANQUILLA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 21 people died after
drinking toxic white rum and scores others were hospitalized in
critical condition in this city on Colombia's Caribbean coast,
officials said Friday.
   The victims, most of them fishermen, street vendors or day
laborers, suffered blindness, vomiting and chills, said officials
from the mayor's office. Bodies of the first victims were discovered
late Thursday along city streets; four more bodies were found Friday
afternoon.
   The General Hospital of Barranquilla said 17 people died
overnight.
   ``The lab tests show remnants of methylic alcohol in the urine of
those who died,'' General Hospital toxicologist Orlando Cepeda Diaz
said. ``It is a catastrophic and worrisome situtation because the
patients are arriving at the hospital in terminal condition.''
   Cepeda Diaz said many of the victims stumbled into the hospital
blind and vomiting; all told authorities they had recently drank
some white rum.
   Officials said the rum in question was sold for 40 cents, when
the normal price is $1.50. Police said nine people have been
arrested in connection with the case and more than 300 bottles of
the rum confiscated.
   The hospital broadcast radio warnings for anyone who drank white
rum the last three days to go immediately to the hospital for tests.
