<SECOND>AM-BRF--Armed Teachers,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parish Approves Plan for Armed Police At Schools</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSSIER CITY, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The school board has approved a plan to
hire armed police officers to patrol high schools.
   Under the program, which the Bossier Parish School Board approved
unanimously Thursday night, a teaching-certified police officer
would be hired for each high school to assist in law enforcement, to
counsel troubled youth and to teach safety and drug education.
   ``It's designed to be a preventive measure that will blend
education and law enforcement,'' said David Walden, a public schools
drug education supervisor in Bossier, in northern Louisiana. ``If
the current trend of violence in the schools is not abated, this
program is going to be milquetoast compared to what's coming down
the pike.''
   The officers would wear uniforms or plainclothes and carry
standard service revolvers, Walden said. The program could begin as
early as spring, officials said.
   The school system, which had 24 drug-related suspensions last
year, has had three this year and one gun confiscation, he said.
