<FIRST>u w AM-AdsCanceled     09-22 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ads Canceled,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Advertisers Bow To Logger Pressure And Cancel Ads For Audubon Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A National Audubon Society television special
on the forests of the Northwest will be shown without any
commercials after nine companies bowed to pressure from loggers and
yanked their advertising, Turner Broadcasting System Inc. said
Friday.
   While Turner Broadcasting declined to release the names of the
companies, they included Ford Motor Co., Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.,
which was advertising its Discover Card, and Stroh Brewery Inc.
   Earlier this month, Stroh withdrew its underwriting of the
Audubon Society's television series after Northwest loggers
threatened to quit drinking that brand of beer.
   ``Due to concerted and apparently organized pressure from the
timber industry, many of the advertisers scheduled for the upcoming
World of Audubon special `Ancient Forests: Rage Over Trees' have
canceled their commercials for that time period,'' Turner
Broadcasting said in a statement released in Atlanta.
   Turner said the show will be broadcast as scheduled Sunday night
with public service announcements and promotions for future shows
replacing the commercials.
   ``Turner Broadcasting is committed to the goals and objectives of
the National Audubon Society,'' the statement said. ``We will
continue to telecast World of Audubon specials despite pressure from
special interest groups.''
   David Krupp, a Ford spokesman in Detroit, confirmed that his
company had ``canceled its participation'' in the show on Northwest
forests but added that Ford would continue to advertise in other
Audubon Society televsion specials.
   ``The Ford dealers in the Northwest area asked us to cancel and
because we try to accommodate when we can the requests of our
dealers and customers we decided to withdraw,'' said Krupp.
   Dean Witter Reynolds canceled its lone 30-second commercial
because ``as a general rule we try not to be controversial,'' said
James Flynn, a company spokesman on Long Island, N.Y.
   Flynn said that while his company hadn't received any direct
telephone calls from loggers, its parent company, Sears, had
received a handful.
   Company officials were also aware of Stroh's decision to drop its
underwriting for the series, said Flynn.
   The timber industry and environmentalists have been locked in a
bitter struggle for months over the future of logging in the virgin
forests of the Northwest, which provide prime habitat for the
northern spotted owl.
   The Audubon Society is among the environmental groups that have
sought to have the owl protected as a threatened or endangered
species and logging in the old-growth forests halted.
   ``National Audubon will never be intimidated by timber industry
bullying,'' said Peter Berle, Audubon president. ``We have not and
will not change one second of this documentary ...''
   Berle said pressure from the timber industry represented the
``last gasp in a desperate effort to stop the American people from
seeing a major doumentary film about the public debate over
protection of the Northwest's remaining ancient forests on public
lands.
   ``We firmly believe the public will be furious about this attempt
at censorship, which runs counter to every principle of free speech
embodied in the First Amendment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
