<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru a0713 09-22 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0713,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Leader Arrives in Moscow, Gorbachev Meeting Planned</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with Mrs. Thatcher's arrival.
Picks up graf 3 pvs, `It is...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN IAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher arrived in
Moscow on Saturday prepared to offer support for Soviet reforms but
expressing caution on defense issues.
   Mrs. Thatcher's plane landed in the Soviet capital shortly after
midnight for a stopover en route home from a four-day official visit
to Japan. She was greeted in Moscow by Yevgeny Primakov, chairman of
the Soviet of the Union, one of two chambers of the Supreme Soviet
parliament.
   She was to meet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev at the Kremlin
later in the day.
   It is a working visit with special emphasis on disarmament
issues, according to the official Soviet news agency Tass.
   ``Although the views of the two countries do not always coincide,
meetings between the leaders of the U.S.S.R. and Britain have given
an additional impetus to the search for compromise and points of
contact,'' it said.
   In Tokyo, Mrs. Thatcher stressed the need for caution and strong
defenses while urging the West to suppport reformers like Gorbachev.
   ``Even if communism seems to be in terminal decline, we cannot
overlook the fact that communist states still control immensely
powerful military forces,'' she told the International Democratic
Union, an organization of right-of-center political parties.
   ``You do not prevent war by disarmament. You prevent war by
quietly being prepared and having a sure defense,'' she told
reporters Thursday.
   Tass, in a political commentary on her visit, said, ``Western
plans to modernize short-range nuclear weapons, with Britain
insisting on their implementation, are worrying to the U.S.S.R.''
   At the same time, Tass said, ``the Soviet Union is interested in
the way the British will act on the issue of reducing conventional
armed forces and armaments in Europe in the light of the new round
of Vienna talks'' which began this week.
   Mrs. Thatcher has praised Gorbachev's efforts to restructure the
Soviet economy and government.
   ``What Mr. Gorbachev has attempted to do in the Soviet Union is,
I believe, in the interests of liberty as a whole and in the
interest of all other nations as well which believe in the cause of
democracy,'' she said in Japan.
   ``Since he has been general secretary, and now president of the
Soviet Union, his policies have been bold, courageous and
visionary,'' she said. ``Indeed, they are of historic proportions.''
   However, Mrs. Thatcher said the Soviet Union and other East bloc
countries need help with basics such as management and
administrative skills. ``It is very difficult to go from a centrally
planned economy ... to accepting responsibility and knowing how to
go about it,'' she said.
   Tass said, ``The Soviet Union is interested in cooperating with
Britain in all-European affairs (especially) ... prospects of
integration processes in Europe in connection with the establishment
of a united market there.''
   It said the two leaders ``will undoubtedly discuss specific
issues of Soviet-British cooperation, such as the establishment of
joint ventures and Britain's assistance in training personnel.''
   Mrs. Thatcher's meeting with Gorbachev will be the fifth since he
became the Soviet leader in 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
