<FIRST>r w AM-US-Angola 370   09-22 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Angola, 370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leader Of African Lobby Says U.S. Aid to UNITA Increased Fivefold</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a major African American lobbying
group said Friday that U.S. aid to Angolan rebels has increased more
than fivefold.
   Randall Robinson, director of TransAfrica, said in an interiew
that U.S. aid rose from $15 million to $80 million a year to make up
for lost aid from South Africa.
   The aid is covert and no verification could be obtained from
other sources. Robinson said he received his information from
congressional sources.
   The United States has supported the Union for the Total
Independence of Angola, UNITA, in its 14-year civil war with the
Luanda government, which has been backed by 50,000 Cuban troops and
Soviet and East German advisers.
   Under a U.S.-sponsored agreement signed in December, Cuba agreed
to withdraw and South Africa agreed to grant independence to
neighboring Namibia.
   Earlier, South Africa had pledged to stop its support for UNITA.
That support reportedly totaled $80 million annually and consisted
mostly of non-lethal items.
   Robinson said he would leave Saturday for Angola to meet with
Marxist President Jose Eduardo dos Santos and that he would invite
dos Santos to visit the United States.
   Robinson said he had received assurances from members of Congress
that the Angolan leader would be welcom on Capitol Hill despite the
absence of U.S. diplomatic relations.
   He urged President Bush to receive dos Santos as he will Jonas
Savimbi, head of UNITA, next month.
   ``We're responsible in a major way for the devastation of
Angola,'' said Robinson, whose group has been at the forefront of
legislation to impose sanctions on South Africa. ``We ought to stop
fueling that.''
   He urged the Bush administration to grant diplomatic recognition
to Angola, which gained membership with overwhelming support in the
International Monetary Fund and World Bank earlier this week.
   The United States has said it will only establish diplomatic ties
when the government reaches a peace agreement with UNITA and agrees
to fair elections.
   The sides signed a temporary U.S.-backed cease-fire in June, but
the truce and peace talks have crumbled.
</TEXT>
