<HEAD>Civil Rights Commission Fires Director for Off-Color Comments</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents may be offensive to some readers.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's civil rights commission fired
its executive director over complaints from three employees that he
kissed a female staffer's ear and used the word ``nigger'' in the
office.
   The Providence Human Relations Commission voted 8-1 Thursday
night to dismiss Joseph T. Fowlkes Jr. He was suspended with pay in
June for investigation of the allegations by the commission.
   Fowlkes, who is black, has been active in Rhode Island civil
rights activities for more than 20 years. He acknowledged that he
used the word ``nigger'' in the office, but he said he meant no harm.
   Three members of Fowlkes' staff, Christine Caffey, Christine
Roundtree and Debra Santos, said he once kissed another employee's
ear in the office. They also said he explained his tardiness on one
occasion by saying he ``had to kick three women out of my bed.''
   Fowlkes maintained the kiss was innocent and said he was joking
when he said he ``had to run three women out of my house.''
