<FIRST>u w AM-Poland-FoodAid     09-22 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Food Aid,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pork Bellies Destined for Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter said
Friday that between 7,000 and 10,000 metric tons of pork bellies
will be sent to Poland as part of a U.S. aid package promised by
President Bush.
   The pork bellies will be part of $108.4 million in food aid
pledged by Bush on Sept. 14. Yeutter said the pork will be donated
under the Food for Progress program authorized by 1985 farm law.
   The Agriculture Department expects to announce in the near future
offers to buy the pork bellies from commercial providers, he said.
Pork bellies are the source of sliced bacon for American consumers.
   A delivery schedule will be worked out with Polish officials, but
Yeutter said shipments probably will be in the winter months when
food shortages can be aggravated by severe weather.
   Bush, in an appearance earlier Friday at a USDA radio show with
farm broadcasters, said that in considering aid to Poland or the
Soviet Union one of the things that is ``absolutely essential is the
reform of their systems.''
   ``They have got to move toward market economies. And I want to
help the Polish people. I'd like to help the Soviets, the people. I
don't want to see the people in these republics that are struggling
for their _ more freedom _ to be set back.''
   Bush said the United States has ``got to insist, as we help with
aid, on the reforms that are necessary. Otherwise, we are simply
putting money down a rathole.''
   Yeutter said in a statement that the pork bellies ``will help
ease food shortages and high prices facing the Polish people at this
time. In consultations with USDA officials, the Polish government
requested pork product donations to help meet current critical food
needs facing the country.''
   The Food for Progress program allows the use of ``U.S. food
resources more effectively in support of countries making
commitments to introduce or expand free enterprise elements in their
agricultural economies,'' the announcement said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
