<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     09-22 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0237</SECOND>
<HEAD>Renewed Rocket Attacks Kills 13 in Midday Crowds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weeklong lull was broken Friday when
at least three rockets blamed on U.S.-backed guerrillas exploded on
midday crowds in Kabul, killing 13 people.
   Such attacks have rocked the capital, sometimes daily, all summer
long. But Kabul had been generally quiet for a week until Friday's
attack, which officials said also wounded 48.
   The latest rocket attacks occurred just before noon in a poor
residential neighborhood and a business district at a time when many
people were walking to meet relatives or visit mosques.
   ``There were many, many people on the street,'' said one resident.
   The Avicina hospital said the casualties included men, women and
children hit when the rockets fell on a crowded thoroughfare near
the ancient Shor Bazaar.
   People in the area dug a grave at the side of the road and filled
it with severed hands and other body parts, residents said.
   They piled stones over the grave, erected a flag and lit as
candle that sputtered in a sudden downpour.
   The government blames the Pakistani-based guerrillas for the
attacks.
   However, the guerrillas claim they only fire at military targets
and the Soviet-backed government fires on civilians in its own
capital.
   At least 300 people have been killed and more than 700 injured in
the rocket attacks since June.
</TEXT>
