<FIRST>r w AM-Labor-Solidarity     09-22 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Labor-Solidarity,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Secretary Praises Polish Union Movement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole on Friday
praised the AFL-CIO for its ``unswerving support'' of Poland's
Solidarity free trade union movement.
   ``This support began in the difficult days of the birth of
Solidarity, and greatly contributed to the breathtaking changes in
Poland today,'' she said.
   Mrs. Dole added that ``the ramifications for democracy if this
experiment succeeds _ and it must _ are limitless.''
   She spoke at a ceremony posthumously honoring former AFL-CIO
President George Meany and three other Americans by inducting them
into the Labor Department's Labor Hall of Fame, which involves a set
of permanent exhibits in the department's headquarters building.
   Also addressing the gathering was AFL-CIO President Lane
Kirkland, who said that ``the four men that we honor today were
unanimous in their faith in trade unionism's value to a free and
democratic society.''
   ``They viewed the labor movement as the natural mechanism through
which working people could help one another _ and thus an essential
element of national progress,'' Kirkland said.
   In her speech, Mrs. Dole declared that ``the spirit of George
Meany can be seen in the unswerving support that Lane Kirkland and
the AFL-CIO has provided to Poland's Solidarity union.''
   She noted that she and her husband, Senate Minority Leader Bob
Dole, R-Kan., recently visited Poland, arriving there the same day
that Solidarity's Tadeusz Mazowiecki was elected prime minister.
   ``We attended a Solidarity caucus after that election,'' she
said. ``And in that room, one could almost feel the spirit of
democracy come to life. It was a feeling that I will always
remember, and both Bob and I returned from our journey committed to
doing more for Poland.''
   In addition to Meany, others inducted into the Labor Hall of Fame
were:
   _John L. Lewis, founder of the Congress of Industrial
Organizations and former president of the United Mine Workers;
   _James P. Mitchell, who served as labor secretary during the
Eisenhower administration and helped develop federal job training
programs; and
   _A. Philip Randolph, founder of the Brotherhood of Sleeping Car
Porters and an early leader of the civil rights movement.
</TEXT>
