<FIRST>r w AM-ImpeachmentAmendment     09-22 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Impeachment Amendment,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia Senator Wants Judicial Impeachment Trials in Supreme Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The senator presiding over the impeachment
trial hearings of U.S. District Judge Walter Nixon said Friday he
plans to introduce a constitutional amendment moving such trials
from the Senate to the Supreme Court.
   The high court has ``the most constitutional perspective on both
the protections and the sensitivity of federal judgeships,'' said
Sen. Wyche Fowler, D-Ga., in an interview.
   The amendment, which he said would be co-sponsored by Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., would apply only to federal judges,
leaving the trial of other federal officials impeached by the House
of Representatives to the Senate.
   An impeachment voted by the House serves as an indictment for
trial before the Senate. A two-thirds vote of the Senate is required
for conviction, which carries only one penalty _ removal from office
and disqualification from ever holding federal ``office of honor,
trust or profit.'' Such a removal does not bar ordinary criminal
proceedings.
   In the 200-year history of the United States under the
Constitution, The Senate has tried only 15 impeachments. Three of
them have been in the last three years and all three were of federal
judges.
   Impeachment proceedings are tremendously time-consuming. Fowler
said he spent all of August reading up on the Nixon case prior to
the four-day trial before his special 12-member committee earlier
this month.
   That committee will summarize the undisputed evidence for the
full Senate in a report that also will include the disputed evidence
with explanations of each side's position. The summaries and
explanations, with a transcript of the committee's hearings, will go
to each senator to read before the full Senate takes up the case.
   The Senate will spend at least one full day hearing arguments
from the House prosecutors, the defense attorneys and Nixon himself
if he chooses to speak. The senators then will debate in secret.
   The impeachment of Nixon, chief federal judge in southern
Mississippi, arises from his conviction of perjury for lying to a
grand jury about his involvement in a drug case against a son of a
wealthy businessman. He is serving a five-year sentence.
   The trial of U.S. District Judge Harry Claiborne in 1986 took the
committee 10 days and 18 hours of Senate floor time before the
Senate voted to remove Claiborne from office. According to Sen. Bob
Dole, R-Kan. who was majority leader at the time, the Senate floor
proceedings took more time than all but the most major issues.
   Senate committee hearings in the impeachment case against U.S.
District Judge Alcee Hastings of Florida took four weeks during the
summer. His case is awaiting action by the full Senate.
   Under the Constitution, federal judges are appointed for life and
can be removed from office only by resignation, death or an
impeachment conviction by the Senate.
   Fowler said the Supreme Court has more time for these cases.
   His plan for a constitutional amendment is not the first call for
a change in the discipline of federal judges.
   Rep. Robert Kastenmeier, D-Wis., chairman of the House Judiciary
subcommittee on courts, intellectual property and the administration
of justice has proposed strengthening federal laws governing the
judges and setting up a commission to study the impeachment process.
   The number of U.S. district judgeships has grown from 409 to 575
in the last 11 years and is expected to expand.
   ``Having experienced three criminal prosecutions against federal
judges in the recent past, a growing number of felony cases brought
against sitting judges can be expected as judgeships are added to
the judicial system,'' Kastenmeier said in a recent article
published in the Kentucky Law Journal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890922-0179 </DOCNO>
