<FIRST>r i AM-Italy-Yeltsin     09-22 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Yeltsin,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italian Newspaper Denounces Pravda in Yeltsin Flap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian newspaper took the Soviet newspaper Pravda
to task Friday for reprinting an article about Moscow political
maverick Boris Yeltsin ``for political purposes.''
   The article, which claimed Yeltsin had gone on a drinking and
shopping binge during a U.S. visit, was reprinted from the Italian
paper, La Repubblica, on Monday. But the Communist Party daily
apologized for reprinting it Thursday, saying the reporter who wrote
it had not seen anything of the kind.
   In an editorial and letter from the reporter, Vittorio Zucconi,
La Repubblica charged Friday that Pravda tried to use the article
for political rather than journalistic ends.
   ``The editorial board of La Repubblica deplores ... the political
use by Pravda,'' the editorial said.
   It said the reprint was part of a ``political confrontation''
taking place in Moscow.
   Yeltsin, the former Communist Party chief of Moscow, was stripped
of that post almost two years ago by Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, who denounced him as overly ambitious.
   In a remarkable political comeback in March, Yeltsin won 89
percent of the vote when he ran against an establishment candidate
to represent Moscow in the new national legislature, the Congress of
People's Deputies.
   The left-of-center Repubblica, one of Italy's largest newspapers,
expressed ``regret'' that Yeltsin suffered ``unjust political
damage'' from Pravda's use of its article.
   A flushed and angry Yeltsin, who returned home Monday from his
nine-city U.S. tour, accused Pravda of seeking ``revenge for the
fact that Americans received us with admiration.''
   In his letter Friday, Zucconi said he had based his account on a
Sept. 13 article in the Washington Post and on Russian emigrant
sources.
   ``If the sources gave inexact information to the Post, to us, and
to other publications which spoke with them, or if they later
changed their account in view of the fuss made by Pravda, we can
only acknowledge and offer our regrets,'' his letter said.
</TEXT>
