<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Yeltsin     09-22 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Yeltsin,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeltsin Celebrates Pravda Apology with Supporters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet politician Boris N. Yeltsin met with
thousands of supporters on Friday and celebrated Pravda's apology
for reprinting an article claiming he drank and spent his way across
the United States on a recent tour.
   ``I'm thankful for your understanding, and for the fact that you
did not believe this lie, slander, this action that evidently was
directed against me,'' he told cheering supporters in Zelinograd, 19
miles northwest of Moscow.
   Just over 1,000 people jammed into a hall in Zelinograd and
photographers on the scene said about 20,000 more listed to his
speech on speakers outside.
   It was Yeltsin's first public appearance since he returned from a
nine-city tour of the United States on Monday. That same day, the
Communist Party daily Pravda reprinted an article by the Italian
newspaper La Repubblica saying the silver-haired populist engaged in
a drinking and spending binge in the United States.
   Pravda apologized to Yeltsin on Thursday, printing a small item
saying the journalist who wrote the story hadn't actually seen
Yeltsin do any of the things he described. Yeltsin previously
described the report as ``garbage.''
   La Repubblica on Friday apologized for the article, saying its
sources for the article misled their reporter.
   On Tuesday and Wednesday, Yeltsin took part in a full meeting of
the Communist Party Central Committee on ethnic issues. The Central
Committee has the power to take disciplinary action against its
members, including removing them from the party policy-making body.
   ``They expected after this planned action that I would declare at
the plenum that I was leaving the Central Committee,'' Yeltsin told
the crowd, which frequently interrupted him with cheers and applause
during his hourlong remarks.
   ``I was only smiling sitting in the hall,'' he added.
   Yeltsin said he also didn't back down from criticism he made of
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reform program while in America.
   ``At the end of the plenum, Gorbachev says, `Yeltsin returned
from America. He says how good it is in America, and we were all
criticized by him, including we Central Committee members and the
Presidium headed by me,''' Yeltsin told the crowd.
   ``I told him, `Right, it was just like you describe it.'''
   Gorbachev brought Yeltsin to Moscow in 1985 to serve as Moscow
Communist Party chief, and Yeltsin quickly became a leading advocate
of Gorbachev's policy of greater openness.
   But Yeltsin was forced out of his job in November 1987 after
criticizing the party at a Central Committee meeting, and
subsequently lost his post as a candidate, or non-voting, member of
the ruling party Politburo.
   He completed a remarkable political comeback this year, first
winning 89 percent of the vote in Moscow for a seat in the new
Congress of People's Deputies, and then being chosen a leader of a
group of deputies that is the Soviet Union's first organized
legislative opposition in almost 70 years.
   Yeltsin gained wide popularity for attacking special privileges
enjoyed by top party and government officials. He also accuses
Gorbachev of proceeding too slowly in his reform program.
</TEXT>
