<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1907EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Congress-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru a0654 09-22 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0654,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDs: New throughout with talks break off, fresh quotes from Byrd,
Hatfield</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate talks aimed at financing the war on
drugs broke off Friday amid squabbling between Republicans and
Democrats over how much to take away from defense and provide for
drug treatment, education and prevention.
   ``There comes a time when you have to fish or cut bait,'' Senate
Appropriations Committee Chairman Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., told
reporters at the end of five days of closed-door bargaining. He said
the White House made the going tougher by being a ``shadow
participant'' in the talks.
   Failure to reach agreement threatens partisan skirmishing and a
logjam of money bills on the Senate floor with eight days to go
before the start of the new fiscal year, when the money will be
needed.
   No further negotiations were planned, although Byrd said, ``I'm
always at the other end of the telephone.'' The leader of Republican
negotiators, Sen. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore., said he hoped ``we'll all
take a clear-eyed, Monday-morning view.''
   Democrats were proposing to add $1 billion to the $7.9 billion
drug-fighting program announced by President Bush. Of the extra
money, $800 million would be aimed at stemming demand for drugs
through education and prevention programs as well as treatment _ the
so-called ``demand side'' of the drug problem. The rest would go to
local law enforcement.
   The Democratic program would be financed through an
across-the-board cut of 0.3 percent in federal spending plus
additional, selected cuts to be determined by congressional
committees.
   These additional, selected cuts would be at an overall rate of
0.144 percent. Committees, however, would be free to reduce spending
in some areas more and other areas less.
   Republicans were offering to add $850 million to the program,
including $750 million for demand-side programs and the rest for
local law enforcement. It would be financed through an
across-the-board cut in spending of 0.4 percent, according to
Hatfield.
   Republicans, however, were holding out for additional flexibility
to protect defense procurement from the full brunt of
across-the-board cuts.
   Over a week of negotiations, Byrd cut his proposed increase by
more than half, and the inclusion of selected cuts which were not
part of his original proposal represented a partial concession to
the Bush administration.
   He told a news conference Republicans asked for concessions ``and
we said, okay, we'll do that, but let's beef up that treatment side,
that prevention side.'' He and other Democratic lawmakers scoffed at
the notion that their proposal would weaken defense.
   ``The administration was unwilling to let a $300 billion defense
budget bear a less than one half of one percent cut to beef up the
war on drugs,'' Sasser told reporters.
   Hatfield said that he was surprised that the Democrats did not
press on with negotiations.
   ``I was highly expectant that this was the day we were going to
finalize the agreement,'' Hatfield said. He acknowledged that at one
point the negotiators had discussed the possibility of raising the
overall increase to $900 million but that this was never
incorporated in a formal offer.
   The breakoff in talks threatened what Sen. James Sasser, D-Tenn.,
chairman of the Senate Budget Committee, described as ``some
procedural disorder on the floor of the United States Senate.''
   Republicans have been holding up final action on four
appropriations bills and eight others are still being fashioned in
the Senate.
   Earlier, Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, said
Republican senators seemed ready to accept a billion-dollar boost
for the $7.9 billion Bush wanted. But he said there were still
problems at the White House.
   ``I believe the only obstacle or the only remaining participant
to give consent is the president,'' Mitchell said.
   Republican senators indicated the administration was concerned
about the impact on the Pentagon and added that they, too, had
concerns.
   ``To the extent that defense has to be hit, I think that we have
to impose the maximum of flexibility,'' said Sen. John Warner,
R-Va., emerging from a meeting with top administration officials.
   ``Take tanks. It would mean a severe reduction in the number of
tanks that could be produced next year,'' said Sen. Ted Stevens,
D-Alaska.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
