<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1927EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Hugo-Glance 1stLd-Writethru a0752 09-22 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0752,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summary of Hurricane Developments</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with storm weakening and no longer being tracked</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a summary of developments Friday associated with
Hurricane Hugo:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>DISASTER DECLARED</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush declared seven counties of South Carolina a
disaster area, making the state eligible for federal loans for
rebuilding, repairs, and restoration of utilities.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ELEVEN DEATHS REPORTED</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ten deaths were reported in South Carolina, eight of them in
counties surrounding Charleston and one near Columbia, S.C., and one
person died in North Carolina.
   Earlier, at least 20 people, and as many as 26, died as the storm
surged across the Caribbean.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>THE STORM</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Hugo was downgraded to a tropical storm at 6 a.m. Friday. By 6
p.m., Hugo had all but lost the characteristics of a tropical storm
and was weakening, although the weather system featured maximum
sustained winds of 40 mph and torrential rains. Its last location
was in Pennsylvania, just west of Pittsburgh, at latitude 40.5
degrees north and longitude 81 degrees west. Officials said no
further tracking would be done.
   The storm was expected to wear out in Canada.
   Threats of severe flooding were eased because the storm was
moving faster than expected.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>LANDFALL</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The center of the storm made landfall about midnight Thursday
over the Isle of Palms, just east of Charleston. S.C.
   The hurricane passed through Charleston with winds of 135 mph and
gusts even higher. Flooding was worsened since the impact, carrying
a wall of water 12 to 17 feet high, coincided with high tide at 2:13
a.m.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>DAMAGE and FLOODING</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty buildings in downtown Charleston, S.C., were flattened,
houses collapsed all over the city, and several people were trapped
beneath a collapsed condominium complex. Fires erupted from natural
gas leaks.
   Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr. estimated damage at $1 billion.
   Elsewhere along the coast, Garden City Beach, S.C., a small
vacation community south of Myrtle Beach, was largely leveled. At
least 14 houses on Pawleys Island were washed away. Three piers
disappeared in North Myrtle Beach, Cherry Grove, and Garden City
Beach.
   In Charlotte, N.C., 200 miles inland, power was out in 85 percent
of the city, and downed trees blocked roadways and damaged homes.
High winds, clocked at up to 75 mph, felled a 1,000-foot television
transmission tower and broke windows in a 42-story downtown office
building.
   At least 900,000 customers in the Carolinas were without
electrical power Friday.
   As the storm moved northward, coastal areas were largely spared
but inland flooding was reported.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>LAW ENFORCEMENT</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   South Carolina Gov. Carroll Campbell said more than 3,000
National Guardsmen and law enforcement officials were on duty.
   Campbell said there had been looting in the Surfside Beach and
Garden City area, but the National Guard had quickly secured the
area.
   Charleston Mayor Riley ordered a curfew from 6 p.m. until 7 a.m.
every night until the damage is cleaned up.
   About 175 Guardsmen were deployed in North Carolina to assist
local authorities. The state ordered evacuation of 90 prisoners at
Yancey Correctional Center at Burnsville as a precaution because of
rapidly rising waters in the Cana River.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CARIBBEAN</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   On St. Croix, Virgin Islands, officials said patrolling U.S.
troops sent to restore order had curbed rampant looting.
   The Marine Radio Band said Thursday that two looters were shot in
St. Croix, but there was no independent confirmation.
   In Washington, the Interior Department said it will staff phones
24 hours for people concerned about relatives in the Virgin Islands.
The number is 202-343-6816.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890922-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 2114EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Hugo-Chronology 1stLd-Writethru a0714 09-22 0718</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Chronology, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0714,0735</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hugo's Path of Destruction</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with Hugo losing designation, no longer being tracked.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of Hurricane Hugo's destructive path across
the Caribbean into South Carolina:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 11 _ Forecasters monitor new tropical wave forming off West
Africa, southwest of the Cape Verde Islands.
   Sept. 12 _ Storm reaches the 39 mph tropical storm threshold and
is named Hugo.
   Sept. 13 _ Hugo develops into a hurricane as winds reach 74 mph.
Storm is about 1,000 miles east of the Lesser Antilles island chain.
   Sept. 14 _ Winds increase to 115 mph; storm is 650 miles east of
Lesser Antilles.
   Sept. 15 _ Winds reach 150 mph. Storm, designated a Category 4
hurricane, is considered ``extremely dangerous.'' Located 340 east
miles of French territorial island of Guadeloupe.
   Sept. 16 _ Hugo bears down on Guadeloupe and Dominica with winds
reaching 140 mph.
   Sept. 17 _ Eye of Hugo is directly over Guadeloupe. Guadeloupe is
devasted by winds measuring up to 150 mph. Five people are reported
killed, 84 injured and more than 15,000 homeless on the island of
340,000 people. Roofs were torn off, power lines downed and crops
damaged.
   Sept. 17 _ Hugo hits British island of Montserrat. Nine people
are killed and hundreds of buildings are flattened. The British
government says nearly all of the 12,000 island residents are
homeless.
   Sept. 17 _ On Antigua, two people are killed and there is
widespread wind and rain damage. Island hotels report water and wind
damage.
   Sept. 17 _ No casualties are reported on the island of St. Kitts,
but houses are damaged and communications nearly severed.
   Sept. 17 _ On the British Virgin Islands, trees are uprooted and
power and communications knocked out. On the resort island of
Tortola, residents say there are numerous injuries and scores of
homes destroyed.
   In the U.S. Virgin Islands, the popular tourist islands of St.
Croix and St. Thomas are hard hit. At least one person is reported
killed on St. Croix. Early reports say 97 percent of the buildings
were damaged or destroyed on St. Croix, population 53,000. Sailboats
were blown out of the water and thrown up to 150 feet on shore in
St. Thomas. Some waterfront businesses disappeared. On St. Croix,
widespread looting is reported, including raids by machete-wielding
gangs. Some reports say prisoners escaped from jail and were roaming
free and National Guardsman and police were joining in the looting.
   Sept. 18 (daybreak) _ Hugo crosses the northeast corner of Puerto
Rico. Damage is estimated at hundreds of millions of dollars and
homes of at least 50,000 people were destroyed or damaged. At least
three people are killed. National Guardsmen were aiding the cleanup
and trying to stop widespread looting. The Pentagon said some of its
facilities, including U.S. Naval Station at Roosevelts Roads in
Puerto Rico, were heavily damaged.
   Sept. 19 _ On the Bahamas, islanders boarded up homes and stocked
up as Hugo moved westward. The storm brushes past the islands, with
minimal damage, moving on a course parallel to the islands.
   Sept. 20 _ Headed toward the southeast coast of the United
States, Hugo has winds of 105-125 mph.
   Sept. 21 _ Hugo picks up speed and power. Winds reach 135 mph.
Hurricane is again classified as a Category 4 hurricane, capable of
extreme damage.
   Sept. 21 (midnight) _ Hugo crashes into Charleston, S.C., with
winds of 135 mph, leveling buildings and flooding streets. In
addition to flooding, fires from natural gas leaks erupt in
Charleston. Several other coastal communities also suffer heavy
damage. Ten people in the Carolinas are killed.
   Sept. 22 _ The hurricane, with steadily diminishing winds,
continues to move inland and is downgraded to a tropical storm.
Further weakening is expected as it moves north with its load of
heavy rain.
   Sept. 22 _ Hugo was downgraded to a tropical storm at 6 a.m.
Friday. Twelve hours later it had all but lost the characteristics
of a tropical storm and was weakening, although the weather system
featured maximum sustained winds of 40 mph and torrential rains. Its
last location was just west of Pittsburgh, Pa., at latitude 40.5
degrees north and longitude 81 degrees west. Officials said no
further tracking would be done.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890922-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1930EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-USAir-Pilots     09-22 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USAir-Pilots,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA Suspends Flight 5050 Pilots, Union Defends Their Actions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-USAir Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration on Friday
suspended licenses of the pilot and copilot of a USAir jetliner that
skidded into New York's East River, but the pilots' union said the
crew broke no rules.
   FAA Administrator James B. Busey cited the crew's delay in
meeting with investigators and in taking drug and alcohol tests
after the crash that killed two people Wednesday night, calling
their actions ``highly questionable.''
   The Air Line Pilots Association said there was ``nothing unusual
in the crew's performance, no federal rules were broken, and the
crew has cooperated completely with the investigation.''
   In a statement announcing suspension of the crew's pilot
certificates, the FAA did not directly blame the pilots for the
crackup of the 737-400 airliner carrying 61 people but said the
circumstances of the accident are such that the two pilots ``may no
longer be qualified to excercise the privileges of an Airline
Transport Pilot Certificate.''
   National Transportation Safety Board and FAA investigators
interviewed the pilot, Michael Martin, and co-pilot, Constantine
Kleissaf, for the first time on Friday, the FAA said.
   The agency had ordered Martin and Kleissaf to appear at its
regional headquarters in the Jamaica section of New York City's
Queens borough, with their pilot certificates, logbooks and other
relevant documents. It lifted that order after the two were
interviewed, the FAA said.
   Officials have been trying to determine why the plane's
late-night takeoff for Charlotte, N.C., was aborted after it had
started down the LaGuardia Airport runway.
   A pilot's suspension may be appealed to safety board
administrative law judges. Either the pilot or the FAA may appeal
the judges' decision to the five-member board whose actions are
binding unless taken by the pilot to U.S. District Court. The
suspensions remain in effect while under appeal.
   Busey said the failure of the pilots to appear in the hours after
the crash negated the opportunity to get meaningful toxicological
tests, ``thereby denying us factual information as to whether drugs
were or were not a factor.''
   An FAA rule requiring post-accident toxicological tests for
pilots goes into effect later this year.
   ``For these two pilots to have been sequestered for more than 36
hours after an accident that took two lives and to do so with no
explanation is highly quesitionable,'' Busey said.
   The pilots union said that the captain and first officer followed
standard ALPA procedures after the accident and that USAir knew the
pilot's whereabouts at all times.
   The union, in a statement, said the cockpit crew would take drug
tests.
   The union criticized the news media for what it said were
erroneous accounts about the crash.
   It said one report that the first officer told rescue workers the
captain was ``mumbling'' and ``acting irrationally'' are likely
based on the fact that the copilot told rescue workers at the
accident site that he could not hear the captain when he was calling
out a post-accident shutdown checklist.
   Union president Henry A. Duffy said reports concerning drug use,
pending homicide investigatons and improper crew communications
proved to be wrong.
   ``While we understand the new media's need to report events,''
Duffy said, ``such erroneous reporting does not serve the public's
need to know, hinders the accident investigation process, undermines
the public confidence in the safety of the system and slanders the
reputation of hte pilots involved.''
   The union statement included no reaction to the license
suspensions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
