<DOCNO> AP890922-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 2115EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Kenya-Killings     09-22 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kenya-Killings,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kenya Accuses Somalia of Widespread Killing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kenyan officials said Friday that Somali
forces killed ``many people'' in a sweep through southern Somalia
before attacking a Kenyan border town in six armored cars and three
jeeps, killing at least four policemen.
   Some sources suggested the Somali soldiers were chasing members
of a newly formed rebel group.
   ``Our people who visited the site were told by the Somalis
fleeing into Kenya that they were lucky to have escaped and that
those who did not make it across the border were mowed down by
gunfire,'' Foreign Minister Robert Ouko told a news conference
Friday.
   Ouko said he did not know how many Somalis were killed in the
violence Wednesday or if it was continuing. But he said hundreds of
refugees were still pouring into Kenya each day across the eastern
border with Somalia.
   Four Kenyan policemen were killed, four people were wounded, and
one person was missing after Somali forces raced into the border
town of Liboi and started ``shooting wildly'' without provocation,
said Ouko.
   He said a nearby telecommunications station was badly damaged and
looted of firearms and ammunition.
   Ouko gave no reason for the attacks. He said Kenya strongly
protested to the Somali charge d'affaires but received no
explanation.
   ``We received a note yesterday ... that the Somalis were planning
to carry out an investigation ... We have heard nothing since,''
said Ouko.
   Liboi, 155 miles northeast of Nairobi, lies across from the
Somali town of Doble. The Somali army reportedly raided that town
last month, when an estimated 5,000 Somalis fled across the border
into Kenya.
   An insurgency calling itself the Somali Patriotic Front emerged
in opposition to the Somali government after those raids.
   Sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Wednesday's
violence occurred as Somali forces pursued the rebels near Doble.
   It was not immediately possible to get comment from Somali
government officials either in Kenya or Somalia.
   In northern Somalia, far from the Kenyan border, the Somali
government has been waging a 6-year-old battle against rebels. In
recent months reports have surfaced of government opposition in
other parts of the country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
