<FIRST>r i AM-China-Reforms     09-22 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Reforms,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Party Chief Says Reforms to Continue, Within Limits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China will not abandon reform policies adopted in
the past but they should enhance the Communist Party and improve
socialism, party chief Jiang Zemin said Friday.
   Jiang, in an editorial on the front-page of the Communist Party's
People's Daily, also said China will maintain its open-door policy
within the guidelines of party directives.
   The official Xinhua News Agency paraphrased Jiang as saying,
``China will resolutely carry out reforms of both economic and
political structures, but these reforms should enhance and perfect
the party leadership and consolidate and perfect the socialist
system.''
   Xinhua said Jiang made the comments at a meeting of local party
representatitives also attended by government leaders including
Premier Li Peng and President Yang Shangkun.
   The People's Daily editorial acknowledged there was concern both
in China and abroad that the crackdown on dissent could mean an end
to reform and open-door policies.
   The suppression of dissent began with the June 3-4 army attacks
on pro-democracy demonstrators in Beijing in which hundreds, perhaps
thousands, of civilians were killed.
   China's goals are to develop socialism and liberate productive
forces, which can be achieved only through an open-door policy, the
editorial said.
   ``This cannot be done unless the closed-door system is destroyed
and the ossified ways changed. We must never return to the old,
closed system,'' it added.
   But the editorial declared that the party's policies did not mean
China would adopt a capitalist system or Western ideas.
   It said the nation's policies cannot be separated from correct
political ideology and the leadership of the party.
   Xinhua reported Jiang said Friday that the party had made
mistakes but has corrected them. It did not say if Jiang mentioned
any specific mistakes.
   It quoted him as warning of subversion from ``international and
domestic hostile forces'' that seek to destroy the communist system
and overthrow the party leadership.
   Li Peng has said several times this month that martial law,
imposed May 20, cannot be lifted at the present because of the
threat of internal and external subversion.
</TEXT>
