<FIRST>u a AM-ParkerSuit     09-22 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Parker Suit,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>Husband Paroled In Wife's Murder 34 Years Ago Files Suit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By J.L. SCHMIDT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who spent nearly 14 years in prison
for a murder he says he didn't commit and to which another man
confessed said Friday he wants to do more than clear his name.
   Darrel F. Parker filed a $12.5 million lawsuit in federal court
against the city of Lincoln, Lancaster County and a former police
chief, claiming his rights were violated by his imprisonment and
denial of a pardon.
   ``It's probably difficult for people to accept my story,'' said
Parker, 57, who lives in Moline, Ill.
   Parker was convicted in the Dec. 14, 1955, strangulation of Nancy
Parker, his wife of 19 months, in a house the couple shared in
Lincoln's Antelope Park.
   He confessed to the killing after his arrest, but later said
police coerced the statement from him.
   Last year, Parker learned that a murderer on death row told his
lawyers that he had killed Mrs. Parker. The man gave them intimate
details of the killing, but made them promise not to reveal his
confession until after his death. He died of a heart attack in July
1988.
   Parker's civil rights action names former Lincoln Police Chief
Joe Carroll, the city of Lincoln and Lancaster County. It seeks $2.5
million in compensation and $10 million in punitive damages.
   Parker said he initially just wanted to clear his name, but ``the
money is a factor.''
   ``There's lost salary, the inability to have and rear a family
... and who can put a price tag on that,'' he said.
   The lawsuit alleges that police brought in John Reid, a Chicago
criminologist and polygraph expert known for his ability to get
confessions, and accuses Reid of illegally inducing Parker to
confess. Reid has since died.
   ``There had been a murder in Omaha earlier that year and the
people in Lincoln were frightened,'' Parker recalled. ``There was a
mass hysteria, the media seized on that and this was known as the
`no-sex after breakfast murder.'''
   Prosecutors contended that Parker killed his wife after breakfast
because she refused to have sex with him before he left for work.
   ``That's just not true,'' Parker said. ``I was young. The police
were experienced. They wanted a confession, they wanted to solve the
murder.''
   Parker was released in 1969 after an appeals court said his
rights had been violated. The U.S. Supreme Court ordered a new
hearing to determine whether the confession could be used. It also
ordered a new trial.
   The trial never was held. An agreement between defense and
prosecution attorneys called for commuting Parker's life sentence
and granting him parole in exchange for his withdrawal of issues
stemming from his confession.
   He chose parole because ``you have to lay some things aside and
get on with living and hope that some evidence will come along
someday that will straighten things out,'' Parker said.
   When he found out last year about Wesley Peery's death row
confession, he decided to try to clear his name.
   ``The past year has been a roller coaster of emotions for us,''
said Eleanor Parker, Parker's wife of 19 years.
   The Board of Pardons on Dec. 15, 1988, denied Parker a pardon
hearing. Attorney General Robert Spire, a member of the three-person
board, said Parker had other ways to clear his name.
   ``The governor refused to answer my correspondence, the pardon
board didn't want to let me have a hearing, so, 34 years later, here
I am, ready to do battle,'' Parker said.
   Calls to Carroll's Lincoln home went unanswered Friday. Earlier
this year, he told a Lincoln newspaper, ``I don't just think he
(Parker) was guilty; I know he was guilty.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
