<DOCNO> AP890922-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1954EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Students     09-22 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Students,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Legalizes Student Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students sang victory chants Friday when
the Supreme Court issued a ruling legalizing a pro-Solidarity
student union and said the union has the right to strike.
   Students, joined by professors and members of parliament,
celebrated the decision in the hallways of the Warsaw courthouse.
   When the ruling was read in the courtroom crowded with more than
100 people there were chants of ``NZS, NZS'' _ the Polish initials
for the Independent Students Association.
   NZS had been banned after the imposition of martial law in
December 1981. Martial law, subsequently lifted, was used to suspend
and then outlaw Solidarity, the first free union movement in the
Soviet bloc. The union had been chartered by the government in 1980
during nationwide strikes.
   Solidarity was legalized last April following lengthy
negotiations and scored such stunning victories in summer elections
that it and two minor parties were able to form the new coalition
government, ending four decades of communist rule.
   NZS had insisted on the right to strike over political and school
issues, and that demand had blocked legalization of the association
after the Solidarity-government agreement in April.
   NZS is Poland's largest student union with organizations in
universities and high schools.
   It was formed in 1980, along with Solidarity, and became a
popular alternative to the Communist-sanctioned Polish Students
Association.
   NZS was denied legal registration last May when a court declared
that a new labor did not apply to students and they could not claim
the right to strike. The association refused to change its charter,
which claims strike rights.
   Even after it was banned, NZS supported Solidarity demonstrations
and organized its own to protest outdated equipment and the lack of
research and library materials and other shortages.
   ``We've been functioning anyway but it is nice to be legal
again,'' one student in the courtroom said.
   Pressure to legalize NZS increased as the Oct. 2 start of the new
academic year approached. There was concern that failure to register
the association would be met by student protests that could create
instability as the new Solidarity-led government tries to reverse
Poland's economic crisis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890922-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 2004EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Divorce-Embryos     09-22 0855</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Divorce-Embryos,0877</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precedent In Embryo Case Will Await Higher Court Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge's ruling in a divorce battle over
seven frozen human embryos that life begins at conception must
withstand the test of higher courts before it sets a precedent in
the debate over reproductive rights, law specialists said Friday.
   ``It's one decision at this point,'' said Elizabeth Bartholet, an
expert in family and reproductive law at Harvard Law School.
   Neil P. Cohen of the University of Tennessee Law School said the
ultimate decision will be determined by higher appellate courts,
perhaps even the U.S. Supreme Court.
   ``And those are the decisions we'll look to for guidance on this
issue,'' he said.
   Lori Andrews, medical law projects director at the American Bar
Foundation in Chicago, said that even in this formative stage,
Circuit Judge W. Dale Young's decision Thursday in the case of Mary
Sue Davis vs. Junior Lewis Davis will have to be weighed carefully
by judges facing similar issues.
   ``When he started this case he had nothing to look to for
precedent, and so other judges will at least have to turn first to
what he said,'' Ms. Andrews said. ``So it will be very widely read.
It will be very influential.''
   In a 57-page decision, Young plotted out his conclusion that life
begins at conception, relying on the testimony of a French
geneticist and a federal appeals court decision in Florida affirming
the use of DNA fingerprinting in court.
   The judge ruled that seven embryos conceived by the Davises
outside the womb through in vitro fertilization were people, not
property, and he awarded temporary custody to Mrs. Davis to bring
them to term.
   Junior Davis, who had fought to be part of any decision on the
disposition of the embryos and not to be forced to become a father
against his consent, said he would appeal to the Tennessee Court of
Appeals and potentially beyond.
   Young said after issuing the decision that he would welcome
review by a higher court.
   Typically, it takes cases two to three years to travel the
appellate route through the Tennessee appeals court and then the
state Supreme Court, and even longer if the case continues to the
U.S. Supreme Court.
   Janet Mayfield, the attorney handling Davis' appeal, said a state
Supreme Court ruling could come sooner if the courts agree to
expedite the proceedings for medical reasons.
   Davis' attorneys said they will seek a stay of Young's order
preventing Mrs. Davis from implanting the embryos until the appeals
are over. There has been some question about how long the seven
frozen embryos would remain viable.
   However, Dr. I. Ray King, who oversees the Knoxville clinic where
the embryos are stored, said, ``From our standpoint, there would not
be a time restraint that we know of. In other species we can go five
to 10 years easily. I would expect in humans, it is probably going
to be similar to that.''
   There is also a question of whether the Tennessee appellate
courts will address directly the question of when life begins.
``Usually judges want to decide something on its narrowest grounds
and not open up a Pandora's box,'' Mayfield said.
   She said Davis' appeal would focus on the apparent conflict
between Young's decision awarding custody to Mrs. Davis with state
law requiring both parents to consent to donating the organs of
their children and a state policy requiring the reporting of deaths
and miscarriages that doesn't mention embryos.
   Even without appellate review, Ms. Andrews of the Bar Foundation
suggested the decision, though at this point applying strictly to
Young's jurisdiction, could prompt an array of legal cases elsewhere
on the grounds that embryos are persons.
   Some possibilities: Inheritance disputes, doctors unwilling to
perform in vitro procedures for fear of being accused of murder if
all of the implanted embryos fail to come to term _ the success rate
typically is one in five _ and even tax disputes on whether frozen
embryos can be counted as dependents on tax returns.
   If the ruling withstands appellate review, the dimensions could
be even larger, further limiting in vitro fertilization practices
and potentially entering the area of abortion rights.
   The U.S. Supreme Court's 1973 Roe vs. Wade decision giving women
the right to an abortion did not address the issue of when life
begins and failed to find constitutional grounds for considering a
fetus a person.
   ``But the philosophy that would say that life begins at
conception would also say it's appropriate for the state to
intervene in the woman's decision about what to do with that
pregnancy as early as day one,'' Ms. Bartholet of Harvard said.
   ``And the same court that came down with this decision would
presumably say in the context of abortion that it is OK for the
state to prohibit abortion from day one. And Roe vs. Wade clearly
says the opposite of that,'' she said.
   Young said his decision was not concerned with abortion law, but
as Ms. Andrews put it, ``This case has created more potential legal
problems than it has solved.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890922-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 2016EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Hugo-Montserrat     09-22 0800</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Montserrat,0831</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tiny British Island Wrecked By Storm, 10 Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PLYMOUTH, Montserrat (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Hugo killed 10 people in
Montserrat and turned this peaceful, hilly island into a junkyard of
smashed houses and snapped trees. Residents were repairing their
homes Friday with relief supplies that have been arriving all week.
   Heavily damaged buildings included the hospital, two hotels and
the American University of the Caribbean, a medical school.
   ``It's disastrous. It will never be the same,'' said Nancy Flynn,
a nurse who was studying at the university.
   Montserrat was one of the islands hardest hit when Hugo ripped
through the Caribbean on Sunday, and the appointed governor of the
British colony said he had feared a death toll perhaps 10 times as
high.
   ``It's miraculous the casualties were so low,'' remarked Gov.
Christopher Turner, who said he survived four hurricanes in previous
assignments. ``This one was so bad I thought 50 to 100 deaths would
be more reasonable.''
   Many victims were elderly, unable to escape their collapsing
homes, he said.
   Ms. Flynn said that despite severe damage to the hospital, about
40 people were treated there for cuts, broken legs and other
injuries.
   ``People were lying in the beds with water dripping on them,''
she said. ``There was no hospital left.''
   Doctors had to suture cuts without anesthetic and beds lacked
sheets, she said.
   Turner estimated damage at about $100 million. He said 30 percent
of the homes will have to be rebuilt and another 30 percent will
need extensive repairs.
   The governor said that about 3,000 of the island's 12,500
residents were left homeless and about 1,200 remained in shelters
Friday.
   The 39-square-mile island lacked power, but some water and phone
service was being restored, he said, adding, ``The entire island
will need rewiring.'' Ships cannot dock here. The storm wiped out
the wharf in downtown Plymouth. Supplies were being flown in by
British and Canadian C-130 military planes that landed on a
3,500-foot runway rated for 40,000 pounds. A loaded C-130 carries
100,000 pounds.
   The British warship HMS Alacrity, which had been in the area for
a port call, flew a helicopter to the island Monday, Turner said.
The ship and a ham radio operator called for help, he reported.
   The airport re-opened Monday afternoon. By Tuesday, food,
building supplies and emergency generators were arriving from
Caribbean neighbors, the United States, Canada and Britain. Roads
and bridges between Blackburne Airport and Plymouth remained intact.
   Mona Ponde swept up the two remaining rooms of her frame house,
which was surrounded by piles of debris from the demolished homes of
neighbors.
   During the hurricane, she and her six children and grandchildren
huddled in the house until the two bedrooms broke away. They stayed
in a neighbor's house until the roof flew off. The rest of the storm
they rode out in the police station.
   ``It was terrible,'' said Ms. Ponde, who survived Hurricane David
on neighboring Dominica island 10 years ago. ``This one, like it,
didn't want to stop at all.''
   At the medical school, the 200 students hid under mattresses in
the dormitory as the hurricane ripped away the school's buildings.
   ``We watched and said `Oh, my God' for hours,'' Ms. Flynn said.
   The Rev. Jeff Hamblin, an Episcopal priest who attended the
school, said he crouched against a stone and concrete wall in his
dormitory.
   ``You could feel it move like you were in a car on a bumpy
ride,'' he said.
   Nearly all the trees were broken or uprooted. One water tank blew
off its platform and tumbled down a hillside.
   Turner said there was some damage at Air Studio, where Paul
McCartney, Elton John and other rock artists have recorded albums.
   The governor said he heard that studio owner George Martin would
like to have all the artists who recorded there put together an
album to benefit island residents.
   Some residents went into damaged supermarkets to salvage food
shortly after the storm, but residents said no widespread looting
occurred. Merchandise remained on some store shelves Friday.
   Police reported seven arrests for petty theft on Thursday.
   The island went through little of the chaos experienced in St.
Croix in the U.S. Virgin Islands, where residents ransacked stores
and prisoners reportedly were released from the damaged jail to roam
the streets. President Bush ordered 1,200 troops, mostly military
police, to St. Croix Wednesday.
   ``My prisoners are out of prison, too, but they're rebuilding the
hospital,'' Turner said.
   A relief headquarters _ called by the British ``a major incident
center'' _was operating downtown.
   The sounds of hammering were heard throughout the island on
Friday as residents fixed roofs and started rebuilding homes.
   ``Montserratians are the salt of the earth,'' Turner said. ``It's
a community which has got it together.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
