<FIRST>r i AM-Duarte     09-22 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Duarte,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Duarte Making `Incredible' Recovery from Near Fatal Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The condition of Jose Napoleon
Duarte, who was in a coma and nearly died this week, improved so
much Friday that his doctor said the former president appeared to be
out of imminent danger.
   ``It is incredible. I can't explain it,'' declared Dr. Jose Luis
Saca, saying Duarte's improvement was ``like night and day. ... From
a moribund state, an agonizing state, he has progressed to a stable
state.''
   A devout Roman Catholic, Duarte received last rites early
Thursday. That night, Saca said ``only a miracle'' would prevent
Duarte's imminent death. Saca made his statements outside Duarte's
home in San Salvador.
   Duarte, 63, has incurable liver cancer that was diagnosed 15
months ago and treated with chemotherapy.
   Duarte, who worked in his earlier years as an engineer, was
president from 1984 until last June. In that post, he was a staunch
U.S. ally.
   He handed over power to Alfredo Cristiani, whose rightist
Republican Nationalist Alliance trounced Duarte's Christian
Democrats in a March election. This week's crisis began Monday,
while the ex-president was visiting Guatemala. Saca said Duarte was
near death Tuesday and Wednesday from asphyxiation due to difficulty
breathing.
   Saca cautioned Friday that Duarte's condition ``is still
serious.'' He said it was impossible to say how much longer Duarte
has to live.
   When the cancer was diagnosed in June 1988, Duarte's doctors gave
him between six and 18 months to live.
   Saca and the medical team attending Duarte at his home took chest
X-rays on Friday. The physician said they diagnosed a spot of
pneumonia in the right lung.
   ``The crisis was the result of that infection,'' said Saca. He
said antibiotics had countered the infection.
</TEXT>
