<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Drugs     09-22 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Drugs,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Assembly to Hold Special Anti-drug Session</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Assembly will hold a special
session on the international battle against drug trafficking next
month, the president of the Security Council said Friday.
   President Bush is expected to urge international action to fight
the illegal drug trade when he addresses the General Assembly Monday
   The drug problem has become so widespread it has even affected
U.N. headquarters.
   U.N. security guards were ordered this summer to clean up a
playground at the northern end of the U.N. complex where cocaine
vials were found virtually every morning.
   Brazilian Ambassador Paulo Nogueira-Batista, the current Security
Council president, said after a council meeting that the the General
Assembly will take up the issue of drug trafficking.
   ``It's clear now among all the members of the council, and it is
also the view outside the council, that the General Assembly must
deal with the question as a matter of great priority,'' he said.
   He was asked when the assembly would consider the issue and
replied ``sometime in October.''
   The Security Council is considering an anti-drug resolution.
   Britain wants drug-trafficking defined as a threat to
international peace and security, which would enable the Security
Council to direct U.N. members to act against drug dealers.
   Nogueira-Batista predicted a resolution will be adopted next week.
   The United States, Soviet Union, Britain, France, and China are
the permanent members of the council and the other members are
Algeria, Brazil, Canada, Colombia, Ethiopia, Finland, Malaysia,
Nepal, Senegal and Yugoslavia.
</TEXT>
