<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 2111EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Scova-DNAEvidence     09-22 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scova-DNA Evidence,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Virginia Court Upholds DNA Fingerprinting Evidence in Murder Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's first murder conviction based on the
use of so-called DNA fingerprinting evidence was upheld Friday by
the state Supreme Court.
   In a pair of unanimous rulings, the court concluded that DNA
tests which linked Timothy Wilson Spencer to the rape-slayings of
two women were scientifically reliable.
   DNA, deoxyribonucleic acid, is the basic genetic material in
human cells. Scientists believe that everyone, except for identical
twins, has a unique DNA pattern.
   Spencer, 26, a former resident of a Richmond halfway house, was
convicted of murder and sentenced to death in separate trials last
year for the slayings of Susan M. Tucker, 44, of Arlington and
Debbie Dudley Davis, 35, of Richmond.
   The women were bound and strangled by an assailant who broke into
their homes through a window. At both trials, evidence was offered
that semen samples from the crime scenes and blood samples from
Spencer had matching DNA patterns.
   In DNA analysis, microscopic fragments of thread-like genetic
material are treated so that they arrange themselves into
characteristic patterns which look much like the bar codes used by
supermarket scanners.
   If pattern samples from crime scene match the suspect's, the
blood or semen is considered to have come from the suspect, since
the likelihood of matching patterns from different people is
reckoned at 1 in many millions.
   The state Supreme Court said Spencer's challenge to the DNA
evidence amounted to saying ``that we should hold off until another
day'' any decision on the reliability of such tests.
   But a number of expert witnesses testified that the technique is
generally accepted in the scientific community.
   ``Indeed, Spencer acknowledges that the evidence establishes that
the DNA tests are accepted `as reliable within the scientific
community' and that he `was unable to find or produce one qualified
expert to debunk either the theory of DNA printing or the statistics
generated therefrom,''' the court said.
   Earlier this year, Spencer was convicted and sentenced to death
in two other cases, the rapes and murders of Dr. Susan Elizabeth
Hellams, 32, of Richmond, and Diane Cho, 15, of Chesterfield County.
   Both those cases are still on appeal.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890922-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 2158EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-OldGrowth-Owls     09-22 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Old Growth-Owls,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Critics Vow Floor Fight If Legislation Isn't Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 members of the House on Friday
asked a conference committee to reject a Senate provision limiting
the power of federal courts to protect the northern spotted owl from
the timber industry of the Pacific Northwest.
   Some critics of the provision said they would mount a floor fight
if they had to.
   Lawmakers from the area, meanwhile, stepped up efforts to reach a
compromise that would be acceptable to environmentalists, the timber
industry and their colleagues.
   The conference committee of members from the House and Senate
next week will try to work out differences between the two versions
of the Interior Department appropriations bill, to which the Senate
provision is attached.
   The critics signed a letter delivered Friday to Rep. Sidney
Yates, D-Ill., the House chairman of the conference committee urging
that the conference drop a Senate-approved amendment that would bar
federal courts during the next year from enjoining any timber sales
in federal forests known to contain the northern spotted owl.
   The owl lives only in old-growth forests of the Northwest. The
Fish and Wildlife Service is considering whether to declare it a
threatened species, which would require federal agencies to protect
its habitat.
   ``What is proposed by the Senate is unprecedented and unwise,''
Minnesota Democratic Rep. Bruce Vento, one of the signers of the
letter, said at a news conference.
   When asked whether he would be willing to lead a floor fight if
changes weren't made, Vento said ``absolutely. This is not just a
policy question for the Northwest. We are willing to look at some
form of relief (for the timber industry), but this is not the path.''
</TEXT>
