<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 2205EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r n AM-Cliff'sNotes-Spy     09-22 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cliff's Notes-Spy,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Allows Parody Because of Free Expression</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge erred in barring distribution of
Spy magazine's parody of Cliff's Notes because the public's right to
free expression outweighs any possible confusion among consumers, an
appeals court said Friday.
   In a 17-page ruling, three judges of the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals explained their Sept. 5 decision to lift the lower
court's injunction.
   Spy Notes, published by Bantam Doubleday Dell Publishing Group
Inc., uses the format of Cliff's Notes, the long-established study
guide to the classics, to poke fun at what Spy Co-Editor Kurt
Andersen called the ``hip urban novel.''
   ``The district court's ruling unjustifiably imposes the drastic
remedy of a prepublication injunction upon the cover of a literary
parody,'' the judges wrote.
   Cliff's Notes Inc. sued the Doubleday group because it claimed
the parody looked too much like the real thing and would confuse
consumers.
   U.S. District Judge Shirley Wohl Kram granted Cliff's Notes a
preliminary injunction on Aug. 2 and Doubleday immediately appealed.
The appeals court lifted the ban on Sept. 5 and said a full opinion
would follow.
   ``We conclude that the parody cover of Spy Notes, although it
surely conjures up the original and goes to great lengths to use
some of the identical colors and aspects of the cover design of
Cliff's Notes, raises only a slight risk of consumer confusion that
is outweighed by the public interest in free expression,'' the
judges said.
   They noted that the cover of Spy Notes prominently states ``a
satire'' five times in bright red letters on the front and four
times on the back. The judges also said that a substantial portion
of Spy Notes' potential audience, college students or
college-educated adults, overlaps with Cliff's Notes' audience.
   ``As a result, the name `Spy' in the title, the notation, `A Spy
Book' emblazoned on the cover of Spy Notes and the use of a prepack
marketing device prominently displaying the `Spy' name should alert
the buyer that Spy Notes is a parody of some sorts, or at least,
that it is not the same product as Cliff's Notes,'' the judges said.
   When the injunction was lifted, Doubleday spokeswoman Jacqueline
Deval said Spy Notes was expected to be on sale at bookstores around
the country by the week of Sept. 18.
   Spy Notes gives humorous plot summaries, commentary and questions
for review on contemporary novels like ``Bright Lights, Big City''
by Jay McInerney and ``Slaves of New York'' by Tama Janowitz.
   It also includes the Novel-O-Matic, a slide rule-like device that
Andersen says allows readers to create their own 1980s novel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890922-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 2205EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Hugo-Charleston 1stLd-Writethru a0802 09-22 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Charleston, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0802,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hurricane Damages Dozens of Square Blocks in City's Historic District</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Most of ..., with 4 grafs to UPDATE with quotes
and color from mansion district; picks up 6th graf pvs: `Across the ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hugo, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mansions of Charleston, which
survived the Civil War, withstood the onslaught of Hurricane Hugo's
135 mph-winds on Friday, but the rest of the city bore fresh scars
from the region's worst storm in 30 years.
   The city where the first shots of the War Between the States were
fired in 1861 looked much like a battlefield Friday, with
rifle-toting National Guards troops men posted to prevent looting in
stores and buildings gutted by the wind and a tidal surge of 12 to
17 feet.
   ``It looked like just devastation all over the city,'' said
resident Milton Demetre. One of the chimneys and half the roof were
gone from his 200-year-old house.
   The streets were littered with bricks, awnings, broken glass and
other debris. The storm, packing 135 mph winds, toppled chimneys,
tore up roofs, shattered windows and collapsed houses over dozens of
square blocks.
   Most of the storied antebellum mansions that line the Battery
facing Charleston Harbor appeared to have weathered the storm with
little damage. The roofs of a few homes looked beaten by the
hurricane-force winds. The biggest threat appeared to be flood
waters, which could be seen as high as the porches.
   ``You come to respect the hurricane. You can see it on the radar,
but it doesn't do anything for you. You see it's really big,'' said
resident Elizabeth Lee.
   Pointing to a house in the city's historic district, she said,
``That house has been through hurricanes, civil wars and all. You
don't understand until you've been there.
   ``There were times we didn't know we would be alive today. We all
woke up and we hugged each other,'' she said.
   Across the street, people had to side-step broken tree limbs
tangled in Spanish moss.
   At St. Michael's Episcopal Church, a piece of wood was lodged in
the side of the roof like a spear and stones from the facade of the
Charleston County Courthouse littered the ground.
   Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr. placed the damage estimate as high as
$1 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
