<FIRST>r a AM-Bush-Trip 3rdLd-Writethru a0768 09-22 0785</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Trip, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0768,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Campaigning Bush Blasts `Failed Policies' of Democrats</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Budget-Taxes, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: INSERTS 12th graf: ``After nine,'' with Bush fishing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, trying to help
Republicans score a come-from-behind victory in the New Jersey
governor's race, portrayed Democrats on Friday as soft on crime,
eager to raise taxes and champions of ``the failed policies'' of the
1970s.
   In a sharply partisan speech, Bush said there was a lot at stake
in the Nov. 7 election: ``The future versus the past. Policies that
work versus policies that don't. A better future for our children,
or one of lost opportunity.''
   The race, one of two governor's contests this year, pits
Republican Rep. Jim Courter against Democrat James Florio to succeed
GOP Gov. Thomas Kean. The other gubernatorial contest is in Virginia.
   ``I am the underdog in this race,'' Courter said, acknowleging he
trails Florio in public opinion polls.
   Florio, a liberal Democrat, ran a close race against Kean in
1981. The governor is not seeking re-election.
   ``The failed policies ... of the 1970s just aren't good enough,''
Bush said. ``Not for New Jersey, not for the United States of
America. They're not good enough to tackle drugs or crime. Or to
protect the environment or do better as a nation in education.
They're not good enough for our kids.''
   Bush campaigned for Courter at a state Republican fund-raising
luncheon before flying to Maine for a weekend at his seaside
compound in Kennebunkport.
   Before settling in at his vacation home, Bush made a brief stop
at a remote tree farm in nearby Wells to underscore his call for a
reduction in capital gains taxes, which are imposed on profits from
sales of real estate, stocks and other assets.
   Farm owner Martin Morse, owner of the 700-acre spread, told Bush
that tree farmers face substantial costs before there is any income
and said that they have to face substantial risk.
   The farmer said the 1986 changes in the capital gains tax law had
cost him more than $4,000 in one year.
   Bush rode to the farm in a van that became stuck in the farm's
dusty driveway as he was leaving. He was pushed out and drove to the
golf course for a round with Brent Scowcroft, his national security
adviser.
   After nine holes, the president went fishing in the dark for 15
minutes in the ocean off his home. As far as anybody could see, he
caught nothing.
   Bush used a tree farm to advance his campaign for a capital gains
tax cut because tree farmers must pay capital gains tax on profits
from their sales.
   That's because trees are considered tangible assets rather than
merchandise.
   The administration contends that many tree farms are small,
marginal operations. Before the 1986 tax reform act, tree farmers
could pay the then-lower rate on capital gains and make ago of it,
officials contend. Now, with the higher rates, many are going
bankrupt, the administration contends.
   Bush told the GOP fund-raiser that he rejected Democrats' charges
that his plan was a tax break for the rich. ``It is a tax adjustment
that is going to create jobs in America and that is why I am going
to continue to fight for it.''
   Bush will make a three-hour excursion Saturday to speak a
luncheon of the Archdiocese of Boston Catholic Lawyers Guild.
   On Monday, he will travel to New York for his first speech as
president to the United Nations General Assembly. He will return to
Washington late that night after hosting a reception and dinner for
U.N. dignataries.
   Sponsors said the New Jersey luncheon raised $700,000 for the
GOP, Bush told the audience.
   In New Jersey, Bush told Republicans, ``This election will decide
whether New Jersey builds on what you began eight years ago or
whether it risks everything by returning to the past, whether New
Jersey has the inspired leadership it needs to win the war on drugs
and crime, or whether it reverts to failed social policies that
blame everyone but the criminal.
   ``This election will decide whether New Jersey continues to have
the kind of leadership which balances a sound economy and a sound
ecology ... or whether its leadership says `No' to higher taxes and
`Yes' to extending the prosperity of the last eight years,'' Bush
said.
   He said Republican leadership would champion the environment,
education, jobs and the war on drugs, and that New Jersey's
residents should ``oppose those liberal Democrats who cherish new
taxes like moths drawn to some kind of a candle.''
   ``The old New Jersey's attitude was: If one tax didn't work, try
another one,'' he said.
</TEXT>
