<FIRST>r a AM-VoodooBrothers     09-22 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Voodoo Brothers,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brothers Convicted of Plotting to Kill Judge With Voodoo Ritual</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUPELO, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two brothers accused of plotting to kill a
judge by using a bizarre voodoo ritual pleaded guilty Friday to
conspiracy to commit murder.
   LeRoy Ivy, 33, and John Henry Ivy, 26, both of Oxford, pleaded
guilty in Lee County Circuit Court with attempting to direct the
voodo spell against the circuit's Judge Thomas Gardner.
   Under the plea, John Henry Ivy will receive a 10-year prison
sentence, with two years to run concurrent with a 40-year prison
term he is already serving for armed robbery. Gardner had sentenced
him on the armed robbery charge, and the voodoo plot allegedly was
concocted as revenge.
   LeRoy Ivy was given a five-year prison sentence with credit for
the time he already has served.
   The Ivy brothers' trial had been scheduled to start Monday in
Tupelo.
   The case against the Ivys has drawn national attention since
LeRoy Ivy was arrested last Oct. 14 and charged with his borther,
who is incarcerated at the Mississippi State Penitentiary at
Parchman.
   The indictment said the Ivys tried to get Gardner's housekeeper
to take a lock of Gardner's hair and a picture of the judge from the
home. She was then to give the items to the Ivys, who were going to
give them to a voodoo witchdoctor in Jamaica to put a death curse on
the judge.
   The brothers offered to pay the housekeeper $400 for the items to
be used in the ritual, the indictment said.
   The brothers previously admitted to believing in voodooism, but
had denied plotting to use it to kill the judge.
</TEXT>
