<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 2319EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RacialPrank     09-22 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Racial Prank,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ole Miss Panel Recommends Banning Prank Frat for Three Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Mississippi should ban a
fraternity from campus for three years for dumping two white pledges
with racial slurs painted on their naked bodies at a
predominantly-black college, a campus committee recommended Friday
evening.
   Members of Beta Theta Pi's pledge class ``kidnapped'' two
fraternity pledges in a traditional prank Monday night, but left the
two students on the campus of Rust College, about 25 miles north of
the Oxford school.
   Rust officials and Holly Springs police said the two pledges were
naked and their hands and feet were bound with duct tape. Witnesses
said the students had ``KKK'' and ``we hate niggers'' painted on
their chests.
   The committee's recommendation followed an almost five-hour
closed hearing.
   ``They found them in violation of three sections of the
Associated Student Body code. The three sections were disorderly
conduct, personal assault and hazing,'' said Jan Robertson,
coordinator of university news.
   The committee of two students, two faculty members and two staff
members made its recommendation to Ole Miss Chancellor Gerald
Turner, who will have the final say in the matter.
   The incident had drawn calls for severe punishment for the
fraternity from the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People and the Ole Miss faculty senate.
   ``The recommendation of the administrative hearing committee is
that the fraternity be dissolved for three years with no activities
whatsoever. All activities will cease immediately, except for
transitional meetings with national fraternity representives,''
Robertson said.
   ``They can serve meals in the house until Friday,'' she said.
``Those living in the fraternity house have been given 30 days from
today to find another place to live, at which time the house will be
closed and secured.
   ``And during those 30 days, there will be a representative of the
national fraternity there at all times.
   ``They further recommended that as far as the individuals
involved in the incident, that normal judicial hearings be held for
all of those with the full range of penalties to be considered from
reprimand to expulsion,'' she said.
   She said the fraternity will have 72 hours to appeal the
committe's recommendation. If they do appeal, she said the
chancellor would announce his decision on the matter at 6 p.m.
Wednesday.
   If there was no appeal, she said the chancellor's announcement
would come after the 72-hour period.
   A man answering the telephone Friday night at the Beta Theta Pi
fraternity house was asked if fraternity representatives were
available to comment. ``I don't think nobody's going to comment on
anything,'' he said. He refused to give his name and hung up.
   Robertson said school officials don't know how many fraternity
members were involved in the incident.
   ``We don't have any names,'' she said. ``I think the next step is
to determine who the individuals were involved. ... We think around
a dozen students were involved, but we don't know for certain.''
   Ishmell Edwards, dean of students at Rust, said officials at the
925-student school had decided to let Ole Miss handle the incident.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
