<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 2332EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ChineseStudents 1stLd-Writethru a0800 09-22 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chinese Students, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0800,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Students Argue For Asylum</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with later testimony, details. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese student wept during an immigration
hearing Friday as she described her father's imprisonment during her
country's Cultural Revolution and said she ``would rather die'' than
return to her homeland.
   ``If we return it's like a death row. My life will be like my
father's and many others,'' said Hoy Yu Li, 27, who along with her
fiance Luo Jian Guang, 32, fled China through Hong Kong and is
seeking political asylum.
   The two students, who were led into court in handcuffs, sought
asylum after leading a protest in Tokyo on June 4 against the
Chinese army's bloody repression of unarmed demonstrators in
Beijing's Tiananmen Square.
   Immigration Judge Bernard Hornbach continued the hearing until
Friday and advised an attorney for the students to seek Hoy's
release from custody through immigration officials so she could seek
medical treatment for ulcer-like symptoms.
   During two hours of dramatic testimony, Hoy described how her
father, a poet, deteriorated mentally during his incarceration and
how her brother tried twice to swim the river between China and Hong
Kong before succeeding in 1976.
   Asked whether she would be willing to return to China, Hoy grew
somber and said, ``I'd rather die.''
   Luo had been studying business and Hoy linguistics at a
university in Tokyo for more than two years before the June 4
protest in front of the Chinese embassy in Tokyo.
   After the protest, the couple received anonymous threats at their
home in Tokyo, they said. Using Argentine passports and helped by
students in Hong Kong, they fled to San Francisco on August 7 to
seek asylum.
   Their attorney, Eugene Wong, said the two students have
legitimate fears of persecution if they are returned to China.
   He also said the case could be the model for other Chinese
residents in the United States who have spoken out against the
current regime in Beijing. There has been only one other case in
which a Chinese came into the United States after Tiananmen to seek
asylum, Wong said.
   The U.S. government estimates there are 73,000 Chinese students
in the country. President Bush decided in June to allow students who
were in the country at the time of the Beijing crackdown to remain
here.
   ``We ... seek to prove that being a pro-democracy student
constitutes membership in a particular social group under the 1980
Refugee Act,'' Wong said. ``If we succeed, this will set a very
important precedent that may enable other pro-democracy students to
be granted asylum in the U.S.''
   A decision could come immediately after Friday's hearing, or
within the next few weeks, he said.
   Immigration and Naturalization Service attorney Beverly Phillips
said the INS had no particular position on the asylum issue, but
filed a brief containing a State Department recommendation that it
not be granted because the students hadn't proven they face
persecution if they return to China.
   Since turning themselves over to immigration authorities, Luo has
been held in a Laredo, Texas, city jail, while Hoy has been at a
detention center in San Diego.
   Luo testified that his father was jailed for nine years during
the Cultural Revolution because because of developing a plan to make
his city government ``in sort of a capitalist way.'' His mother and
a paternal brother were also jailed, he said.
   When his father died in July, Luo said he was afraid to return
for the funeral.
   ``I would never return to China,'' he said, ``They know my name,
they will imprison me.''
   Both students said their Japan visas were due to expire soon, and
they feared applying for extensions because the Japanese government
would ask the Chinese government for comment and force them to
return home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
