<FIRST>a i PM-Europe'92-Japan Adv28   09-22 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Europe '92-Japan, Adv 28,0774</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thurs PMs Sept. 28 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Looking Ahead to 1992, Japan Turns on Charm in Europe</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports
looking ahead to Western Europe in 1992, when the 12 nations of the
European Economic Community remove their trade barriers and
interlock their policies and goals.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>By RAF CASERT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After years of focusing its efforts on
economic and technological progress, Japan is trying to show West
Europeans it has more to offer than Walkmans, Nikons and Hondas.
   It is doing so in ``Europalia 89 Japan,'' a three-month art
extravaganza, in hopes of enhancing its reputation within the
12-nation European Economic Community, which will take down internal
trade barriers and interlock economic policies and goals by the end
of 1992.
   The exhibition is intended to show the depth of Japanese culture
and to offset charges often leveled against Japan that it dumps
goods on the market at unfair prices and follows a course of
protectionism and economic imperialism in trade policy.
   With 1992 closing in, the Japanese decided to make their move
into a market which will have 320 million potential customers.
   ``The Japanese prime minister told me it was important to
reinforce the bonds with Europe in view of 1992, which worries
Japan,'' said Jacques Groothaert, Europalia's organizer.
   Japan is going to great lengths now to give Europeans a better
and different view of its society.
   Europalia is costing $25 million and shows priceless pieces of
Japan's cultural heritage for the first time ever overseas.
   ``It is clear they want to spread a different image,'' said Gretl
Van Ourti of the Europalia Japanese Committee.
   It all contrasts greatly with the past when ``the Japanese used
to make a bad marketing effort whenever it concerned their own
image,'' said Jean-Pierre Debever, Japan specialist at Belgium's
Foreign Trade Ministry.
   ``Now, they want to put Japan in a more positive, a softer
light.''
   In all, more than 500 events _ from blockbuster art exhibits,
plays, ballets to literature and philosophy sessions _ are expected
to attract an estimated 1.7 million people in cities across Belgium.
In addition, there will be a smattering of events in six other
European nations.
   Although Europalia is by far the most spectacular effort, Japan
has also been using other means to make itself better known.
   These range from an increase in trade missions, symposia and
corporate conventions on Japan to cocktail parties, dinners and golf
competitions, said Etsuro Yoneyama, President of the Japanese
Association in Belgium.
   ``There is widespread agreement among the Japanese here that we
have to increase such happenings,'' he said.
   At the same time, trade relations with the EEC are slowly
improving, despite a staggering $25 billion trade imbalance in
Japan's favor and the barriers Europeans face to get a stake in
Asia's richest market.
   ``There are still major (trade) problems expected and many things
still have to be solved. But we are on the right track,'' said EEC
spokesman Nico Wegter, who lauded Japan's recent initiatives to
market itself better.
   Europalia organizers faced many problems to lure Japan as the
first non-European nation to their 20-year-old festival. Since its
inception, Europalia has highlighted art from a European nation once
every two years.
   At first few Japanese companies seemed willing to sponsor the
event.
   ``They were slow to catch on but changed when they realized what
a great base it would be for 1992,'' said Debever.
   As Europalia's headquarters are in Brussels, which also is the
home base of the EEC, the festival's marketing effort gained an
extra dimension. And when Japan's Emperor Akihito formally endorsed
Europalia as a showcase for Japanese art and culture, money began to
stream in.
   Japanese corporations are financing half of Europalia's budget,
with the remainder coming from the Japanese government and European
sources.
   Despite all the good will, a cultural divide remains.
   While European companies traditionally support the arts in a
discreet manner, Japanese firms look for a maximum return on
investment.
   Toyota, for instance, has been elevated to Europalia's ``Official
Car'' and chopsticks and sushi at official receptions ``are brought
to you by La Porte of Japan,'' a Brussels restaurant.
   And, ironically, Japan, a nation keen on uniforms in the
workplace, went against European tradition to insist Europalia
hostesses wear no official outfits for fear these would cheapen the
cultural aspect of the happening.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs Sept. 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
