<DOCNO> AP890922-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1013EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:James Adv25   09-22 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: James, Adv 25,0740</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs, Sept 25 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Kind of Cooperative Victorian Women Could Have Used</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the J-K volume of a recent
Encyclopedia Brittanica, the writer Henry James has a six-column
entry. His sister, Alice, is given no mention at all.
   The 19th-century diarist never succeeded in establishing herself
as a talent, which seemed a literary crime to the small group of men
and women who founded a writers' collective in her name.
   Alice James Books, an independent press that emphasizes women's
work, was conceived in 1972 as a strike against not only Victorian
mores, but also against the male-dominated reading lists most
college freshmen were studying in the 1970s.
   ``At the time, the people who sat in the important chairs at the
publishing houses were men,'' said Marjorie Fletcher, a poet and
co-founder. ``It was far easier to get a book on baseball into print
than one by a woman or about women's issues.''
   The collective publishes about 2,100 copies each of two books of
poetry every summer and spring. Its authors vary in age, race and
lifestyle, but they all share in the ideals from which the
non-profit enterprise grew.
   When Alice James writers agree to join the cooperative, they
agree to nurture their colleagues as well as their own work.
   So far about 70 authors have made the two-year commitment, during
which they guide their own book into print. Three have received
Beatrice Hawley Awards, a grant named after the poet that allows
poets outside of New England to publish.
   Rosamond Rosenmeier is just wrapping up work on her first
collection, ``Lines Out,'' which appears this fall.
   ``The experience is extraordinary,'' says Rosenmeier, a writing
professor at the University of Massachusetts in Boston.
   With the help of a ``buddy,'' a veteran collective member who's
already been through the process, she has taken her book from pen
and paper to its final production stages.
   ``It's definitely my book,'' Rosenmeier said. ``I've had a hand
in everything: choosing the print, negotiating with the typesetter,
picking the cover design. We even did the paste-up.''
   That participation and the support collective members lend one
another are part of the philosophy inspired by Alice James, who
struggled in the shadow of her five brothers, including Henry and
William, a prominent psychologist.
   Henry James, the author of such works as ``Portrait of a Lady''
and ``The Ambassadors,'' was so unsettled by his sister's diaries,
which he considered an invasion of privacy, that he burned his copy,
according to biographers..
   ``She was a talented woman who never had a chance to develop,''
Fletcher said of Alice James, who died at the age of 43.
   Today, Fletcher says, it's a whole new ballgame. Women have
gained widespread acceptance, so much so that the collective has
begun casting its net wider and more actively soliciting minority
writers.
   Inclusion is the idea.
   Rosenmeier chuckles to think of the group's regular Sunday
afternoon meetings. ``We're all so different,'' she says. About a
dozen writers from all walks of life gather at one member's home,
bringing with them plenty of pasta salad, fruit, cheese and wine.
   Fletcher says it's funny to watch everyone file in when the
meeting convenes.
   ``Everybody finds a chair that somehow issues from her
personality. Some sit on the floor, the clubby people sit on the
couch. I sit on a chair,'' she says.
   The business of running and promoting Alice James is always high
on the meeting's agenda. The authors take no salary, but revenue
from limited sales through catalogs, book fairs and a few stores is
far from enough to sustain the collective's budget.
   The press relies in large part on state, federal and private
grants, which Fletcher said have dwindled steadily, particularly
under the strain of Massachusetts' current fiscal crisis.
   But Jenney Milner, a part-time office manager and the only paid
employee, said the gatherings inevitably swerve from the pragmatic
to a free-for-all.
   ``That's when they get interesting,'' she said, ``when we talk
about the philosophy of the press.''
   And, adds Fletcher, ``The vagaries of the commercial world or
damned luck can't change our commitment to empowerment, to fairness,
to our philosophy.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Mon Sept. 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
