<DOCNO> AP890922-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0930EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a w PM-Education-Cavazos Adv25   09-22 0932</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Education-Cavazos, Adv 25,0955</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday PMs, Sept. 25</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Nation's Top Educator Prepares for the Education Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The aggressiveness of his answer stunned the
audience.
   Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos, normally one of the most
easy-going members of President Bush's Cabinet, had just been asked
if letting parents pick their child's school would lead to
half-empty ``dumb, dumb'' schools.
   ``Well, then, why don't we just close those dumb, dumb schools,''
Cavazos told reporters gathered for a breakfast briefing. Shaking in
anger, he jabbed the air with his finger over the ``choice''
question he'd been asked.
   Such emotion is something educators hope to see more of from
Cavazos at the education summit meeting Wednesday and Thursday in
Charlottesville, Va. One reason: Cavazos, a college president before
becoming education secreatry last year, will be the only educator
sure to attend the meeting of Bush and the nation's governors.
   Does Cavazos see his role as a burden?
   ``I don't think of it as pressure,'' the 62-year-old former
professor said in an interview.
   ``There certainly have been certain amounts of pressure'' in his
role preparing for the summit, he said, adding, ``This is really the
president's summit. ... I'm just simply a supporter of the president
and trying to move ahead his program.''
   Cavazos pointed out that other educators may, indeed, attend the
summit. Each governor can bring one aide to the table and, the
secretary conjectured, many may bring the heads of their education
departments.
   The summit, Cavazos said, should ``create the kind of climate
that will permit education to be examined. The only problem all of
us have is solving that education deficit.''
   Although highly praised for his understanding of education, some
educational leaders are concerned that Cavazos' conciliatory style _
which won their support after being battered by the abrasive,
outspoken William Bennett _ may hinder Cavazos from aggressively
pushing with the president substantive educational programs and the
money needed to make them work.
   ``I see this as a beginning,'' Cavazos said of the two-day
gathering. ``People look at this as the end. We're not going to come
out of there with a lot of ideas and direction. We have a long way
to go to solve this education deficit.''
   Cavazos chuckled at the mention of money, a subject that has been
avoided like the plague by virtually all those expected to have a
role at the summit. Repeating a statement often used by
administration officials, he said, ``I don't think we need more
money for education.''
   ``The education deficit is not a fiscal deficit. I see it as a
deficiency deficit,'' he said, pointing to the $330.5 billion
expected to be spent on education by all levels of government this
year and the $353 billion projected for next year.
   ``When you look at that amount of money ..., that means that
people out there are investing a tremendous amount of money in
education and yet when you look at our performance educationally, it
is not an issue of dollars. To me it is an issue of changing the way
we are doing things now.''
   As the nation's top educator, Cavazos has been working
``extremely close'' with the White House in planning the summit,
attending ``extensive meetings'' and providing background
information and suggestions that are helping to shape the agenda.
   The secretary has been lauded by educators who credit him with
persuading Bush to hold a series of private meetings with various
groups prior to the summit.
   ``I certainly have pushed the idea because I very much wanted to
have this happen ...,'' said Cavazos. ``What we're trying to do is
bring in a broad consensus and gather ideas from that.
   ``I want to make it very clear that I'm optimistic. The very fact
that the president has called this summit is a tremendous historic
occasion.''
   Cavazos, the first Hispanic named to a Cabinet post, has been a
loyal promoter of Bush's education initiatives, quietly circulating
through Capitol Hill and around the country to spread the Bush's
rhetoric.
   Key among Cavazos' own pet projects is bilingual education. But
he has won the most praise for his student loan default regulations,
which educators say have shown the right combination of toughness
and understanding of the soaring, multibillion-dollar default
problem.
   Initially lukewarm to the idea of parental choice when it comes
to their child's school, Cavazos has since enthusiastically embaced
what has become the centerpiece of Bush's education initiative.
   Without a doubt ``choice'' will be discussed at the summit along
with five other topics that Bush and the governors hope will lead to
national goals on what children should learn.
   Cavazos has described himself as the system's first beneficiary
of ``choice'' because his father, then the foreman of the huge King
Ranch near Kingsville, Texas, managed to send his five children to
the local Anglo school and not an inferior one for Hispanics.
   Cavazos grew up on the ranch, served in the Army for two years,
attended college in Texas on the GI Bill and earned a doctorate in
physiology from Iowa State University. He taught anatomy at the
Medical College of Virginia and Tufts University Medical School,
becoming dean of the latter in 1975.
   In 1980, Cavazos moved to Lubbock to become president of Texas
Tech University and in September 1988, then-President Reagan tapped
him to succeed Bennett as education secretary. Bush, who had pledged
not only to be the education president but to put at least one
Hispanic in his Cabinet, kept Cavazos on.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday PMs, Sept. 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
