<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0732EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Garcia Adv25   09-22 0828</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Garcia, Adv 25,0847</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday AMs, Sept. 25, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Andy Garcia's Spontaneous Characters</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING to fix garble.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Black Rain'' opened Sept. 22.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andy Garcia doesn't like to talk about acting.
There are methods, he insists, that must be kept from the public,
intricate preparation that, if revealed, would spoil his character's
aura of spontaneity.
   On screen, he is equally mysterious, preferring to play cops who
let a slight turn of the head or an eye that gleams like an
officer's badge take the place of words.
   That's one reason why he was drawn to the character of Charlie
Vincent, the quiet, faithful sidekick of Michael Douglas'
swaggering, hard-headed detective in ``Black Rain.''
   ``If your thought is clear, there's nothing else you have to
do,'' said the Cuban-born actor, whose big breakthrough came last
year as Kevin Costner's eagle-eyed sideman in ``The Untouchables.''
   ``That's the task. Now how do you go about doing it, to convey
the beautiful thought? Once you do all the preparation, it's really
spontaneous, the character behaving. Once all the
intellectualization is done, you just do it.''
   The homework _ tracing the character's history, internalizing his
conflicts _ are for the actor's eyes only. What Garcia cares about
is how audiences feel about Charlie, who helps Nick Conklin track
down a Japanese hitman in Osaka and gets killed in the process.
   ``When people are in times of need, certain individuals come into
your life that act as a foil or help you come out of that,'' Garcia
said. ``I look at Charlie as that angel who came down and provided
that, and when his time was done, and the door opened, he goes.
   ``He's usually pretty upbeat. When you're down he keeps your
spirits up. He always seems to be easygoing and yet is usually the
most spiritual and painful character.''
   Garcia, who emigrated to Miami Beach with his parents when he was
5 years old, liked movies as a child but felt no special desire to
act until he went to Florida International University.
   ``I don't know. It was really a virus situation that just invaded
me and was brewing bigger and bigger,'' he said. ``I was in my share
of plays as a kid, but so was everyone else in the world.
   ``I do think there is a correlation between the spontaniety and
spirit of athletic competition and the moment-to-moment rush of
acting.''
   After college, he went to Los Angeles, hoping to break into
movies. First came a spot in the TV pilot for ``Hill Street Blues.''
Theater work followed, with appearances in ``Anastasia,'' ``The
Cherry Orchard,'' ``Don't Trust Life'' and other works.
   Movies began in 1985 with ``The Mean Season,'' starring Kurt
Russell.
   ``It was tough but very rewarding, and afforded me the luxury not
to have another job,'' Garcia said. ``It was a fresh learning
experience, but it's still a stage. The stage becomes a street, and
the onlookers are your audience. ``You pay dues and you have the
learning process that no one can take away from you.''
   Garcia's penchant for simplicity colors his approach to choosing
films. Rather than agonizing over image and storyline, he takes a
look at who else is involved. For ``The Untouchables,'' that meant
Sean Connery.
   ``When I heard he was in it I said, `Oh great, let's go.' He was
a hero ... when he played James Bond.
   ``I admired his work ethic, his preparation. He was ready to go.
If you weren't ready, he'd blow right by you. Eight in the morning,
ready to go. All great actors are like that. The people you're with
are the spark that opens the door to all that work.''
   ``Black Rain'' offered several temptations: Douglas, director
Ridley Scott (``Blade Runner,'' ``Alien''), and producers Stanley
Jaffe and Sherry Lansing (``The Accused,'' ``Fatal Attraction'').
   He credited Scott with allowing him to pursue his character to
the fullest.
   ``Ridley said an interesting thing to me for one scene,'' Garcia
recalled. ``He said, `I think you should go for whatever you want to
do, because you need to get all the way to the end.' It comes out
from using all your energy and within that state of exhaustion,
finding that precious moment.''
   But Garcia's tribute to the late Hal Ashby, who directed him in
``8 Million Ways to Die,'' is most in line with the actor's taste,
what he likes to accomplish on film and can't resist doing in person.
   ``I liked the fact he never said anything. He did say everything,
but without imposing anything.
   ``I'm an observer, to the detriment of many people around me,''
Garcia said. ``The great danger of being in the public eye is losing
that perspective and becoming the one being watched instead of the
one watching. But you have to cope. You have no choice.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday AMs, Sept. 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
