<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0729EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:SongSamples Adv28   09-22 0965</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Song Samples, Adv 28,0989</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thursday AMs, Sept. 28, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>New Service Lets Listeners Sample Records by Phone</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Music fans no longer have to judge a record
by its cover.
   A new company is offering consumers the chance to sample portions
of albums using their touch-tone telephones. At 89 cents a minute, a
nimble-fingered fan can form musical opinions for less than the cost
of a single.
   ``With the cost of compact discs and the large market out there,
this gives a listener a chance to hear an album before he buys it,''
said Mark Munson, marketing director for Music Systems Inc.
   The Fort Lauderdale, Fla., company has been operating its special
charge 900 telephone line since the beginning of August. About 5,000
people a week are calling to hear a little music, Munson said.
   Music Line is the little brother of the party lines and rock
hotlines that have boomed in popularity during the past few years
with advancing telephone technology.
   Callers who hook into the system are asked to choose from among
more than 100 albums in categories such as rock, heavy metal, rap,
progressive and so-called black music.
   Once the selection is made, a 10- to 15-second snippet of each
song on the album is played. Callers can move on to another song or
album with the press of a button. The average caller stays on the
line for about four minutes.
   ``We sampled the 15 seconds that hopefully are the most
indicative of the song,'' Munson said. ``We don't just start at the
beginning.''
   Albums on the playlist range from such hit artists as Fine Young
Cannibals, the Traveling Wilburys and Madonna, to more obscure
newcomers such as rappers Three Times Dope and independent label
rockers Nirvana.
   A group of Harvard Business School students were the brains
behind the idea. They started a telephone line in the early 1980s,
but it folded due to high costs. A 900 telephone line is considered
easier and cheaper to run.
   With radio stations increasingly reluctant to play more than one
or two songs from an album, Music Line performs an important
service, Munson said.
   One act that's generated a lot of calls, he said, is Elektra
Records recording artists 10,000 Maniacs. Curious fans can easily
find out through Music Line that despite the name, 10,000 Maniacs is
actually a literate folk-rock band, he said.
   ``Elektra is intrigued by the idea that they are on the system,''
Munson said. ``That kind of a response is good. They see it as a
valuable service.''
   But the group's manager, Peter Leak, said he's not certain he
likes the idea of someone outside the group boiling down 10,000
Maniacs songs into the 15 seconds they consider most important.
   ``Hearing 15 seconds of each song on each album isn't hearing the
whole album,'' said Leak, whose New York End Ltd. also manages the
Cowboy Junkies, another band featured on Music Line. ``To imagine
that it does is not being realistic.''
   It's much preferable, he said, for a fan to slip on a pair of
headphones in a record store and hear as much of the album as
possible. Many record stores used to have ``listening booths'' where
customers could do this.
   Music Line has no formal relationship with record companies, but
marketing departments in several companies are eagerly providing the
phone service with compact discs and promotional materials, Munson
said.
   That's obviously in their best interests, he said, because
listeners who like the 15-second snippets will go out and buy the
records.
   Record company reaction has been more cautious.
   ``We've been approached, but we have absolutely no idea what the
potential of this thing is,'' said Robert Altshuler, spokesman for
CBS Records, whose records are being used on Music Line. ``It's too
early. This is a brand new thing.''
   The service helps record companies in the same way radio play
does, said Louis Dennis, national sales director for Warner Bros.
Records, whose LPs are also being used.
   ``Obviously the more exposure we get, the better we are,'' Dennis
said. ``Whether this is a revolutionary thing, I don't know.''
   But Dennis said when he first saw advertisements for Music Line,
he alerted Warner Bros.' legal department. Munson said that's been
the initial reaction of several record companies, whose persnickety
attitude toward unauthorized use of their product has been seen in
the controversy over home taping.
   ``I'm not saying they don't have the rights to do it,'' Leak said
of the service. ``I'm sure they do. I'd like to make sure that there
are some provisions that people get taken care of. It seems a little
unfair that all the money flows into one pocket.''
   Music Line pays a small fee to music publishing firms for use of
the songs, Munson said. The company is relying on a legal opinion
that says it owes record companies nothing, he said.
   ``If any record company feels they don't want the album on the
system, we'll take it off the system,'' he said. ``Of course, it's
in their best interests to be on the system. It's a new thing, and
of course people always have questions about new things.''
   The company also wants to assuage the fears of parents who worry
about teen-agers rolling up exorbitant phone bills. At a parent's
request, the company can block calls coming in from a particular
phone line, Munson said. The company also offers a money-back
guarantee to dissatisfied customers, although the process would take
a few months, he added.
   The phone service, which drew more than 12,500 calls in its first
month, has an eventual goal of 2,500 calls a day, Munson said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thursday AMs, Sept. 28</NOTE>
