<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0738EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-Education-MoneyTrail Adv26   09-22 1022</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Education-Money Trail, Adv 26,1049</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tuesday AMs, Sept. 26, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>From Lunch to Lessons, Feds Pay Small _ But Needed _ Part of School
Tab</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON COHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WAUKEGAN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At Greenwood Elementary School, scores of
pupils can count on a free hot meal every day. They also can expect
regular lectures on the evils of drugs. Both come courtesy of Uncle
Sam.
   The federal government writes billions of dollars in checks each
year to educate tens of millions of children across America. As is
the case with most schools, Greenwood's share goes for everything
fom lunches to lessons.
   ``The work of the federal government in terms of how it helps
urban centers is critical,'' said Jack Taylor, superintendent of
Waukegan Community Unit School District 60. ``We just simply
couldn't handle the youngsters' needs without this type of funding.
... It makes the schools decidedly better.''
   At the start of the 1980s, nine cents out of every dollar spent
by the public schools came from Washington. Today, it is barely six
cents.
   The federal share slipped even while the Department of Education
budget grew from $14.8 billion in fiscal 1981 to almost $22 billion
for fiscal 1989.
   While the federal share dwindled, state and local expenditures
have spurted, and overall education spending has jumped 29 percent
in real dollars _ after inflation _ since 1981. Expenditures per
pupil in the public schools have risen from $2,762 in 1980-81 to an
estimated $5,246 in the current school year.
   President Bush told lawmakers in Helena, Mont., last week: ``The
plain truth is that our educational system is not making the grade.
... Spending more money on education than most other countries,
we're getting less return on the investment. It is time for change,
perhaps radical change.''
   Just what kind of change will be discussed Wednesday and Thursday
in talks between Bush and the nation's governors.
   Although Washington will provide a seemingly substantial $11.6
billion for elementary and secondary education in 1989, including
the Agriculture Department's free lunch and breakfast plan, the
federal government often is the smallest _ and most limited _
partner in the school financing formula.
   It accounts nationally for about 6 percent of elementary and
secondary school spending; poor areas generally get more because of
programs designed for the needy.
   In Illinois, for example, the state in recent years has provided
five to six times as many education dollars as the federal
government.
   The ratio is about the same in District 60, which has 11,500
students in 21 schools in this blue-collar lakefront community about
10 miles from the Wisconsin border. The enrollment is equally
divided among blacks, whites and Hispanics.
   In the 1987-88 school year, the district spent an average $4,102
per pupil. The national average that year was $3,522.
   The district's projected budget for 1989-90 is $40.3 million.
More than 92 percent will come from local and state sources, while
federal aid will make up only 7.29 percent _ about $2.9 million.
   It seems a small contribution, but it's an essential one.
   ``When you're talking to a district in the red, every dollar is
very valuable,'' said Lawrence Pekoe, associate superintendent for
administration. ``It's not a matter of getting it from the state
government or the local taxpayer. We just don't have the property to
tax.''
   But Pekoe also noted educators have few options with Washington
dollars because, unlike general state funds, they are specifically
targeted. Two of the largest federal programs are for poor and
special education students.
   This strings-attached approach ``is good on one hand because it
earmarks money for special needs,'' Pekoe said. ``You put energy
into that area you might not if you didn't have the money. (But) it
also prevents a district from using that money in other ways that
might be of greater need.''
   In District 60, free and reduced-price breakfasts and lunches
last year consumed more than a third of the available federal
dollars.
   The two other biggest chunks of aid went to special education and
Chapter I, a remedial program for low-income students that is used
in Waukegan to boost reading skills. About 85 percent of the money
goes for salaries and benefits.
   Federal funds for District 60, usually channeled through the
state, also pay for vocational education; high school ROTC; staff
training in math and science; Follow Through, an extension of Head
Start; library equipment; aid to Hispanic students; and a drug and
alcohol education program coordinated with the county and featuring
local police lectures.
   Local school officials rely on these programs.
   Consider Judith Lafferty, principal at Greenwood, where more than
a third of the 328 pupils are from poor families.
   ``Initially I was never really enamored with the free lunch
program or the breakfast program,'' she said. ``It can be an
administrative headache.''
   But for some children, ``these are only the two times during the
day they know they can get something to eat,'' she added. ``You
can't teach a kid who's not properly nourished. You can wish a
situation away and try to blame it on their parents. That's not
going to change the fact some of these kids are sent to school with
nothing to eat.''
   At Greenwood, 183 children receive free or reduced-price lunches
at a federal price tag of more than $44,000 each school year. Each
free lunch costs about $1.40, Pekoe said.
   As for the 48 students who benefit from Chapter I reading money,
Mrs. Lafferty said: ``It gives them an opportunity for small group
instruction and for individual attention, which some of these kids
lack at home. They don't have someone read to them; they haven't
been exposed to books. It helps to build these kids' confidence. In
some cases, I've seen them improve by leaps and bounds.''
   The projected cost for the 1989-90 school year: about $76,700, or
nearly $1,600 a child.
   Like so many other educators, Mrs. Lafferty would appreciate more
federal aid.
   ``But what they do, I'm glad I've got that,'' she said. ``It does
make a difference _ really.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues AMs, Sept. 26</NOTE>
