<FIRST>a i AM-Lebanon-DeadFish Adv29   09-22 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Dead Fish, Adv 29,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday AMs, Sept. 29, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Syrian Shelling Killing Fish Off Lebanon Near Beirut</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOUNIEH, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian shelling is killing fish in the
Mediterranean off this Christian enclave near Beirut and threatening
one of Lebanon's few natural resources, a government ecologist says.
   It also has cut sharply into the livelihoods of the enclave's 500
fishermen, but some are venturing out after dark to gather the
thousands of fish that float dead on the surface after each shelling.
   ``Our sea is dying,'' ecologist Pierre Malichev of the Health
Ministry said in an interview. ``It's become rotten and polluted.
Our marine life is nearing its end and we have no fish for next
year.''
   He estimated that millions of fish have been killed, along with
billions of their eggs.
   Malichev said fish that are not killed by the hundreds of
exploding 130mm howitzer shells and salvoes of rockets are being
poisoned by tetryl, one of the explosive elements in the shells that
is released into the water.
   All that remains for the fishermen are the dead fish.
   ``After a heavy round of shelling, the dead fish float like a
carpet on the surface,'' said Sirop Ornakian, one of about 75
fisherman who still go out.
   ``We usually wait a bit and then head for the carpet. Most times
I collect about 25 kilograms (55 pounds) of fish every trip.''
   The Syrians have been pounding the 28-mile coastal enclave and
its waters for six months to keep cargo ships and tankers from
running a blockade with supplies for the Christian forces of Gen.
Michel Aoun in the battle of Beirut.
   ``The shelling has killed our season,'' said Kivork Manoukian, a
fisherman for more than 40 years. ``Usually this time of the year is
the best for us, when we make some money. But this year's been
catastrophic.''
   He and other fishermen sat around the shady courtyard of his
house in Jounieh, 12{ miles north of Beirut, smoking an Arabic water
pipe.
   ``This is what our life is now,'' he said.
   His friend, Arten Khishkhishian, said he does not go out any more
because his nets were torn by twisted rocket casings and lumps of
shrapnel littering the shallow waters off Jounieh and the ancient
port of Byblos a few miles north.
   ``I've had to repair my net three times and that cost more than
100,000 pounds ($200),'' he said. ``I decided to stop this `shrapnel
fishing' until there's lasting peace.''
   But the others risk their lives and their boats, 15-foot craft
powered by outboard motors, to haul in the dead fish. Sometimes a
Syrian barrage will come unexpectedly. Police said several fishermen
have been wounded.
   Kevork Manoukian said that on one recent night ``it looked quiet
so I dropped my net.''
   ``Then the next minute a shell hit about 100 meters away from my
boat,'' he said. ``I ditched my net and made it for the shore in
panic as more shells exploded around me.''
   Ornakian and other fishermen regularly go out for catches not
much bigger than those they were netting before the fighting.
   With fish in short supply in the enclave, the price has doubled
to the equivalent of about $4.50 a pound.
   Ornakian and the others reckon that the money they make from each
trip _ the equivalent in Lebanese pounds of about $250 _ is worth
the chance.
   Moslem fishermen are banned from the waters off Beirut, where the
Syrians have deployed batteries of long-range artillery along the
waterfront to shell the Christian coastline.
   But the Moslems are able to fish south of Beirut for 50 miles
down the coast to the ancient port of Tyre, where the biggest danger
they face is an occasional Israeli gunboat.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Sept. 29</NOTE>
