<SECOND>BC-Education-Statistics, 1st Ld-Writethru, Adv 24,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv24</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to reflect that cost is on annual basis.</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 24, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>American Education by the Numbers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Education-Bush, b0664.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Statistics say 37.2 million students are in
America's public school classrooms on a typical day. At an average
annual cost of $4,500 each.
   Statistics say many things about education in the United States.
   For instance, 46.1 million students attended public and private
schools in the 1987-88 term. Of that, 32.4 million were in
kindergarten through the eighth grade; 13.7 million were in grades
9-12.
   Teaching the public school students were 2,308,900 teachers _
1,332,487 in elementary schools and junior highs and 976,413 in high
schools. Their average pay: $29,567, up 5.6 percent from a year
earlier.
   Total public school spending in the 1988-89 school year was an
estimated $185.9 billion, or an average of $4,500 a student, up 5.8
percent over a year earlier.
   And those numbers just touch the landscape of education
statistics. Among others:
   _As of the 1987-88 year, total grade school and junior high
enrollment had risen 2.5 percent since 1980, when 31.6 million
students were enrolled in public and private schools. High school
enrollment had risen 3.0 percent, from 13.3 million, in the same
period.
   _As of 1986, boys outnumbered girls 16.1 million to 15.0 million
in elementary school and junior high and 7.1 million to 6.9 milion
in high school.
   _Of the 40.3 million full-time public school students, average
daily attendance was estimated at 37.2 million.
   _There were 15,309 operating public school districts in the
1987-88 year.
   _Public schools employed 1,332,487 elementary school teachers and
976,413 high school instructors.
   _Total 1988-89 public school spending was estimated at $185.9
billion, including current expenses, capital outlays and interest
expenses.
   _Current expenses were $167.9 billion, up from $157.6 billion a
year earlier.
   Statistics also show the value of education.
   A 1984 Census Bureau study said the average college graduate
makes 83 percent more than someone who graduated only from high
school. The average holder of a professional degree, such as a
lawyer or doctor, made twice the income of someone with an
undergraduate degree and five times the income of someone who never
finished high school.
   How long do most people stay in school?
   Americans average 12.7 years of education. The averages for
various groups are: white males, 12.8; white females, 12.6; black
males, 12.4; black females, 12.4; Hispanic males, 12.1; and Hispanic
females, 12.0.
   Among those aged 25 and over, 2.4 percent had completed less than
five years of schooling. For whites that figure was 2 percent, while
5 percent of blacks and nearly 12 percent of Hispanics had 5 years
or less of school.
   Some 35.5 percent of Americans 18 and older ended their education
with a high school diploma; 26 percent never finished high school.
   Beyond that, 3.4 percent added an associate degree, 10.6 percent
went on to get a bachelor's degree, 3.4 percent added a master's
degree and 1.5 percent earned a doctorate or professional degree.
Nearly 18 percent attended college but did not graduate.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 24</NOTE>
</DOC>
