<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0841</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The economy grew at a moderate 2.5 percent pace
in the second quarter, the government said, down from the first
quarter but strong enough to stop any new predictions of an imminent
recession.
   The Commerce Department reported Thursday that April-June growth
in the gross national product compared with a 3.7 percent gain in
the first three months.
   Nearly two-thirds of the January-March strength came from an
anticipated rebound in farm output.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.P. Morgan &amp; Co. Inc. moved ahead of other major
banking companies by adding $2 billion to its cushion of reserves
for loan losses, indicating deeper pessimism about the chances of
repayment by developing countries.
   Morgan's action, announced Thursday, was far more severe than
those taken earlier this week by Chase Manhattan Corp. and
Manufacturers Hanover Corp.
   Morgan's reserves now equal 100 percent of its medium- and
long-term loans to developing countries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New doubts were raised over prospects for the
Bush administration's strategy to reduce the $1.3 trillion Thirld
World debt as delegates from 152 nations arrived for talks on global
economic issues.
   World pollution, political upheavals in Eastern Europe and China,
and the roller coaster ride of the dollar all were expected to be
addressed during the annual meetings of the International Monetary
Fund and the World Bank.
   But the U.S. debt plan, unveiled last March by Treasury Secretary
Nicholas Brady, was the major topic on the agenda because resources
of the IMF and World Bank are crucial the effort's success.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hoylake Investments Ltd. won an important second
round in its takeover battle for BAT Industries PLC when the British
government cleared the group's $21 billion hostile bid for the
conglomerate.
   Trade Secretary Nicholas Ridley said Thursday he would not refer
Hoylake's offer to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission, upholding
the Conservative government's free-market policies and sweeping
aside concerns about the advent of giant, highly leveraged, junk
bond-financed buyouts in Britain.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Koito Manufacturing Co. said it will not give T.
Boone Pickens Jr. more power just because the U.S. investor is
increasing his stake in the Japanese auto parts supplier to 26
percent.
   But the company, which Pickens has railed against for repeatedly
refusing him a spot on its board of directors, said Thursday his
larger ownership could threaten its position on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several major airlines matched an American
Airlines initiative that will increase some discount fares by more
than 15 percent and double cancellation penalties.
   Under the proposal matched Thursday, the popular ``MaxSaver''
cut-rate fare often used by vacationers, which must be purchased 14
days in advance, will be increased by $10 to $20 round trip. The
``MaxSaver'' tickets will remain non-refundable.
   In addition, fares will be raised on seven-day advance tickets by
$30 to $60 round trip. The penalty for changing or canceling a
reservation will double to 50 percent of the ticket price.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp., strapped for cash because of the
strike and bankruptcy of its Eastern Airlines subsidiary, is
discussing the sale of a stake in its computer reservation system to
a General Motors Corp. unit, sources said.
   Sources close to the situation said Thursday the airline company
was looking for a partner for the reservation subsidiary, called
System One.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The total cost of the UAL Corp. buyout could reach
$9.45 billion, according to Securities and Exchange Commission
filings by the employee-managment group seeking to take over United
Airlines' parent.
   The group, composed of United pilots, UAL's top management and
British Airways PLC, also announced in newspaper ads Thursday the
commencement of their tender offer for all outstanding shares of
UAL's common stock for $300 a share.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the U.S. meatpacking industry said they
are exploring new ways to reduce repetitive-motion injuries that
strike their workers more than those in any other business.
   The American Meat Institute, an industry group, is funding
research aimed at detecting the early warning signs of carpal tunnel
syndrome, the most severe of the disorders, the organization's
president said Thursday.
   The Occupational Safety and Health Administration levied heavy
fines against several meatpackers in recent years for violating laws
aimed at preventing repetitive-motion injuries.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market posted a small loss for the second straight
session Thursday. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials closed
with a 3.61 point loss at 2,680.28.
   The dollar gained ground against the major currencies in quiet
dealings. Gold prices were unchanged to slightly higher.
   Bond prices fell slightly.
   Grain and soybean futures prices rallied strongly; silver futures
were sharply higher; oil futures were mixed; and livestock and meat
futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
