<FIRST>r f PM-Griffin-Campeau Bjt   09-22 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Griffin-Campeau, Bjt,0792</SECOND>
<HEAD>Griffin and Campeau: A Tale of Takeovers Gone Wrong</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At first glance they appear vastly different: A
singer and television star turned successful businessman, and a high
school dropout who built his way up to become a millionaire
developer.
   But Merv Griffin and Robert Campeau, to their chagrin, have much
in common. Both men find their companies struggling because they
can't handle debts run up in notorious takeover battles.
   Griffin's Resorts International Inc. is trying to restructure a
$900 million debt after failing to meet interest payments to
bondholders. Resorts, which operates hotels and casinos, is not
generating enough cash to pay bills.
   Campeau, meanwhile, was forced to cede control of his retailing
empire to Olympia &amp; York Developments Ltd. in exchange for a $250
million loan.
   His company, Campeau Corp., also could not meet interest payments
on some of its $11.5 billion debt, and the developer has had to put
his prize Bloomingdale's department store chain up for sale.
   Resorts has attributed some of its problems to competition from
newer casinos in Atlantic City, poor management and deteriorating
physical facilities.
   Campeau's Federated Department Stores Inc. and Allied Stores
Corp. have suffered from the same lackluster sales that have
afflicted other retailers.
   But the real problem is that Merv Griffin and Robert Campeau paid
too much for their companies, went too deeply into debt and did not
anticipate that their cash flow would be inadequate to handle their
interest payments.
   Griffin battled with developer Donald Trump over Resorts for
months last year with on-again, off-again agreements before finally
buying the company for $364 million and the assumption of $600
million in debt. Griffin issued $325 million in notes to help
finance the deal.
   Campeau waged a bidding war with R.H. Macy &amp; Co. Inc. early in
1988 before winning Federated for a total price tag of $8.8 billion.
He went deeply into debt, increasing the liabilities he incurred
over a year earlier when he triumped in a $3.4 billion battle for
Allied.
   Griffin and Campeau were all smiles on winning these fights. Both
were on top of the world, each believing he had cut a great deal and
achieved glory after years of hard work.
   They came by their money in very different ways.
   Griffin is one of the best-known entertainers in the United
States. He began his career as a singer and film actor and then
moved to television, where he hosted game shows including ``Play
Your Hunch'' and for 23 years had his own talk show.
   But behind the affable exterior Griffin presented to television
audiences was a shrewd businessman. He founded his own production
company, Merv Griffin Enterprises, which turned out programs
including the ``Merv Griffin Show'' ``Wheel of Fortune'' and
``Jeopardy.''
   He also bought radio stations and assembled an extensive real
estate portfolio, with holdings in Beverly Hills and Northern
California.
   In 1986, Griffin sold his production company in 1986 to Coca-Cola
Co. for a reported $250 million, but kept his role as chairman.
   Campeau's background is less spectacular.
   He was born into a poor Ontario family and left school at 14 to
help support his brothers and sisters. Campeau was a factory foreman
in Ottawa in 1949, building a home for his family in his spare time,
when he got the idea to sell the house instead and make a profit.
   Campeau continued building houses and was on his way to becoming
a prominent builder. Over the years, he developed part of the
lakefront area of Toronto, now a fashionable area, put up office and
government buildings and became increasingly wealthy in the process.
   He tried his hand at takeovers in Canada, and failing there,
turned his sights toward the United States and Allied.
   Neither Campeau nor Griffin is exactly going about with hat in
hand now, but they are taking some lumps to try to keep their
companies going.
   In exchange for the loan from Olympia &amp; York, Campeau gave up
control of his company, and Bloomingdale's may not be the only
assets he will be forced to sell.
   This is not the first time Campeau has surrendered control of his
company. In 1969 he sold a majority share in return for cash for
expansion, a move he regretted, but later bought back the stake at a
premium.
   Griffin has had to ask his company's bondholders to back a debt
restructuring. He could have a hard time getting their approval:
Ninety percent of each class of bonds must approve the restructuring
for it to take effect.
</TEXT>
