<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0233EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-OilPrices Bjt   09-22 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Prices, Bjt,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gasoline Futures Move Higher Due to Refinery Damaged by Hugo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy analysts say Amerada Hess Corp. should not
have problems meeting its commitments to U.S. customers despite
severe damage from Hurricane Hugo to a major refinery at St. Croix,
Virgin Islands, which sent gasoline futures prices surging.
   The 545,000-barrel-a-day facility, which was wrecked when the
storm smashed into the Virgin Islands earlier this week, supplies
markets in the eastern United States.
   By drawing on inventories or buying on the cash market, Hess
should be able to supply its customers, analysts said. The company
has refused to comment on how it will meet its obligations, but a
company spokesman stressed there would be no disruption in supplies.
   News that hurricane damage would shut down the huge refinery for
about 60 days sent gasoline futures prices soaring for the second
day Thursday.
   The October contract for unleaded gasoline closed 2.12 cents
higher at 61.86 cents a gallon on the New York Mercantile Exchange,
for a two-day increase of 4.19 cents. Heating oil for October
delivery rose 1.03 cents to 57.58 cents a gallon after rising 1.60
cents in the previous session.
   Contracts for delivery later in the year posted much smaller
gains.
   Analysts said gasoline prices on the futures market could go even
higher in the short-term. Hess has said the refinery would resume
partial operations in about 30 days.
   ``We've gotten to the point where refined product markets are in
such basis equilibrium that when they lose any production it does
cause tightness,'' said Peter Beutel, assistant director of the
energy group at Elders Futures Inc. ``So probably we will see prices
move up.''
   Sustained higher prices could be passed on to retail customers in
another 30 days or so, analysts said, but if they erode fairly
quickly as some anticipate, there could be little effect at the
gasoline pump.
   ``We believe the excess capacity will be made up by refineries
abroad,'' said James Steel, energy analyst at Refco Inc. ``It also
will probably push U.S. refineries back above the 90 percent level.''
   U.S. refiners recently slowed to about 89.8 percent capacity
after pumping at a strong 92 percent during the peak summer months,
Steel said.
   Hess also announced Thursday that it would not be able to provide
petroleum products for ships loading at its refinery in St. Croix.
   ``We're talking about other ships, not ours, that buy an
occasional load from us,'' said a Hess spokesman who did not want to
be identified. ``We stand by our original statement that we will
meet all our commitments to U.S. customers.''
   Crude oil futures traded on the New York exchange were mixed,
with the contract for November delivery falling 6 cents to $19.62 a
barrel. Contracts for later delivery rose slightly.
   Amerada's refinery was shut down Saturday in preparation for
Hugo. The refinery had been producing about 400,000 barrels a day of
gasoline, distillates and other products, most of which are used in
the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
