<DOCNO> AP890922-0253 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0231EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Morgan-DebtTalks Bjt   09-22 0721</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Morgan-Debt Talks, Bjt,0744</SECOND>
<HEAD>J.P. Morgan Loan-Loss Decision is Bad News for Debtor Nations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.P. Morgan &amp; Co. Inc.'s painful decision to add
$2 billion to its reserve cushion against loan losses is bad news
for Third World nations in debt, analysts say.
   Morgan, the nation's third-largest banking company, cited
intensifying political and economic problems in debtor nations
Thursday as it announced that the addition to its reserves would
result in a $1.8 billion loss in its current quarter.
   Chase Manhattan Corp. and Manufacturers Hanover Corp. announced
similar steps earlier in the week, but Morgan's was the most
drastic. It boosted its reserves to 100 percent of its medium- and
long-term loans to developing countries, more than double the
reserve fraction established by the others.
   Morgan's action could complicate talks on debt-reduction plans
that are part of the annual meetings in Washington of the World Bank
and International Monetary Fund. Delegates from 152 nations began
arriving for those talks Thursday.
   Morgan and other big banks that have begun facing up to the
likelihood of huge losses on loans to developing countries are
unlikely to resume large-scale lending to those nations for many
years, analysts said.
   ``Bankers do have short memories. But once a bank loses a billion
dollars on any sort of a loan, they don't come back very quickly.
Maybe 20 years from now,'' said Stephen Berman, an analyst at County
Securities USA in New York.
   Morgan, the parent of Morgan Guaranty Trust Co., said it would
continue doing business in developing countries but would focus on
merchant banking rather than general lending. Merchant banking
involves providing advice, trading and investing, and finance.
   ``We will continue to consider lending in appropriate specific
transactions. We intend to continue to play a constructive role in
developing countries,'' Morgan spokeswoman Kathleen Baum said.
   The talks in Washington will concern Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady's plan to relieve the $1.3 trillion Third World debt through
debt forgiveness rather than new lending.
   Some banks are concerned that the Brady plan may have caused
debtor nations to lose their sense of urgency about keeping up on
their loan payments. Morgan said debtor nations seem to have
overestimated how much help is forthcoming from the industrial
nations.
   ``We are very concerned about debtor countries' rising
expectations of the magnitude of debt reduction possible under the
Brady initiative,'' Lewis T. Preston, Morgan's chairman, said in a
statement.
   The Treasury Department said Morgan's increase in reserves was
not a direct result of the Brady plan. It said banks would actually
need lower reserves under the plan, since they would be scratching
some shaky loans off their books.
   But analysts said the Brady plan is forcing bankers to
acknowledge the depth of their troubles in developing countries.
They are responding by doing everything possible to extricate
themselves.
   Morgan's financial strength allowed it to cleanse its books more
completely than Chase or Manufacturers Hanover. It means the company
will not suffer any further losses even if developing countries
don't pay another cent on their medium- and long-term loans.
   ``Some banks just want out,'' Berman said. ``Early on in this
process everybody sort of pulled together, followed the lead of
Citibank. Everybody is sort of cutting and running now and pursuing
their own interest.''
   Morgan now has a total of $3 billion in loan-loss reserves, with
$2.8 billion of that unofficially allocated to loans to developing
countries. That $2.8 billion is equal to 70 percent of Morgan's
total loans to developing countries, and 100 percent of the
medium-and long-term loans to those nations. In an indication of
Morgan's strong finances, Moody's Investors Service Inc. and
Standards and Poor's Corp. on Thursday both confirmed their
investment-grade ratings on Morgan senior debt.
   The last big round of additions to loan-loss reserves came in
late 1987, and many banking companies have not taken any action
since then.
   For example, Chemical Banking Corp.'s loan-loss reserves equal
just 28 percent of its medium- and long-term loans to developing
countries.
   At Chase and Manufacturers Hanover, the corresponding reserves
are 46 percent and 36 percent, respectively.
   Before the formal sessions of the IMF and World Bank in
Washington, finance officials of the world's seven richest countries
were scheduled to hold talks all day Saturday to review global
economic issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
