<DOCNO> AP890922-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0231EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TexasAir-GM Bjt   09-22 0737</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texas Air-GM, Bjt,0757</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Air Discussing Sale of Stake in Reservation System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prized part of Texas Air Corp., its
computerized reservation system, is now on a list of possible items
for sale by the nation's biggest airline company because of a cash
crunch.
   Sources said Thursday that Texas Air is discussing the sale of a
stake in its reservation system to a General Motors Corp. unit,
Electronic Data Systems Corp., partly to ease the pressure caused by
the strike and bankruptcy proceeding at Texas Air's Eastern Airlines.
   Texas Air spokesman Art Kent in Houston and Roger Still, a
spokesman for Electronic Data Systems in Dallas, both declined to
comment on the matter Thursday. But sources close to the situation
said the airline company was looking for a partner for the
reservation subsidiary, called System One.
   The Wall Street Journal reported in its Thursday editions that
talks between Texas Air and Electronic Data Systems were advanced
and that barring a snag, an agreement could be reached soon.
   The Journal indicated the companies were discussing the sale of
System One in its entirety, but sources told The Associated Press it
would likely be a partial sale.
   Analysts estimate the value of System One, the nation's
third-largest airline reservation system, at $300 million to $400
million.
   The participation of GM in System One would mark the first
non-airline owner of a computer reservation system, which might be
more acceptable to government regulators, who have expressed worries
about consolidation in the field.
   In addition to the work it performs for GM, EDS is involved in
health insurance, government and financial institution data
processing and is looking for sources of revenue that will make it
less dependent on its parent.
   Selling System One would be a radical move for Texas Air Chairman
Frank Lorenzo, who has underlined the importance of computer
reservation systems to airlines' competitiveness. Those systems have
been undergoing rapid changes and consolidations recently.
   Earlier this week, Delta Air Lines disclosed it was discussing
merging its reservation system with PARS, an operation jointly owned
by Trans World Airlines Inc. and Northwest Airlines. And American
Airlines' Sabre reservation system has been seeking a partner after
the Justice Department quashed its plans to link up with Delta's
system.
   System One was transferred from Eastern to Texas Air in April
1987 for about $100 million. A member of the Air Line Pilots
Association, one of the three unions on strike against Miami-based
Eastern since March 4, has a lawsuit pending in New York state
Supreme Court challenging the transfer and claiming that Texas Air
paid too little for System One.
   Court-appointed bankruptcy examiner David I. Shapiro is studying
the transfer as part of his investigation of transactions between
Texas Air, Eastern and sister carrier Continental Airlines. Shapiro
was out of the country Thursday and unavailable for comment.
   The reservation system is ``the heart of any airline,'' said Hank
Weber, an ALPA spokesman in Miami. ``It's an indication that he
(Lorenzo) really is in need of money quickly.''
   Talk about the reservation system comes at a time when Texas Air
is taking a number of steps to shore up the foundations of its
airline empire. Late last month, Lorenzo announced that he was
considering selling all or part of Houston-based Continental.
   Last week, a federal bankruptcy judge approved a plan in which
Texas Air would help with a payment of $98.3 million Eastern owes to
employee pension plans. Texas Air is lending Eastern $45 million
toward the payment, Eastern is paying $27 million with the proceeds
of asset sales, and the rest has been deferred until July.
   Texas Air has given no indication of what it might do with the
proceeds from any sale.
   ``The airline is just looking at their options,'' said Raymond
Neidl, an analyst for investment firm Dillon, Read &amp; Co. Inc. The
sale of part of System One ``certainly would give them money to
expand and enhance the system.''
   Louis Marckesano, an analyst with Janney Montgomery Scott Inc. in
Philadelphia, said Texas Air appears to be trying to raise cash.
``It sounds like a continuation of this business with Continental,''
he said.
   In the May-July quarter, Texas Air posted a $109.3 million net
loss as losses at Eastern far outweighed a modest profit at
Continental. The company lost $255.9 million in the same quarter
last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
