<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0332EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AirFares     09-22 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Air Fares,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Major Airlines Match American's Proposed Fare Hikes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Texas Air-GM, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines, historically a leader in
lowering the cost of air travel, also has shown its enormous
influence in raising prices too.
   Several of American's principal competitors have matched its
initiative that will increase some discount fares by more than 15
percent and double cancellation penalties.
   Delta Air Lines, Continental Airlines and Pan Am Corp. said
Thursday they were following American's move. The increases,
proposed by American earlier this week, will take effect Sept. 29.
   United Airlines and Northwest Airlines were still studying the
matter and hadn't decided yet, spokesmen for those carriers said.
   American, based in Dallas, is one of the largest U.S. carriers
and helped pioneer fare discounts in the deregulated airline
industry. In the past it has often been the first to announce
innovative discounts that competitors were forced to match.
   Under the fare increases, the popular ``MaxSaver'' cut-rate fare
often used by vacationers, which must be purchased 14 days in
advance, will be increased by $10 to $20 round trip. A ``MaxSaver''
ticket on American between Dallas and Los Angeles, for example,
would jump from $338 to $358 round trip. The ``MaxSaver'' tickets
would remain non-refundable.
   In addition, fares will be raised on seven-day advance tickets by
$30 to $60 round trip. The same Dallas-Los Angeles round trip ticket
bought seven days in advance would go from $378 to $438. The penalty
for changing or canceling a reservation would double to 50 percent
of the ticket price.
   Atlanta-based Delta said a sharp rise in fuel prices, along with
a large number of discount tickets sold recently, prompted the
airline to match the increases.
   ``Delta has held the line on discount-fare increases for over a
year, while we have seen record numbers of passengers utilizing the
most deeply discounted seats,'' Whit Hawkins, Delta's senior vice
president of marketing, said in a statement.
   ``At the same time, Delta's costs have been rising, most recently
impacted by a 6.65 cents-per-gallon increase in the cost of fuel.''
   The increases follow a recent rise in a type of discount fare
popular with business travelers, reflecting an effort by airlines to
partly recoup revenue lost from bargains offered this summer to fall
vacationers.
   American said it proposed the fare hikes in an effort to improve
its passenger yields.
   An airline's yield reflects the average revenue from passengers
for each mile flown and is a critical barometer of financial
strength.
   Many airline industry analysts expect little improvement in
yields overall for the rest of the year and into 1990.
   In mid-August, the airlines announced steep fare cuts for the
fall season, extending summer travel bargains. They slashed
round-trip fares by as much as $160 to lure passengers in the
historically weak autumn season. Most fares to Europe were reduced
by $100 into next spring.
   Last week, in an effort to recover some of the losses, the
airlines boosted ``Supercoach'' one-way fares, favored by business
fliers because they have more lenient advance-purchase requirements
than cheaper discount fares and don't require a Saturday-night stay.
   Those fares were raised by around $20 for a one-way ticket.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
