<DOCNO> AP890922-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0349EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Campeau-Reichmanns Bjt   09-22 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Campeau-Reichmanns, Bjt,0786</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reichmann Family Increases Its Considerable Power with Campeau Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reichmann family, emerging from intensive
maneuverings with a bigger piece of Campeau Corp.'s retail and real
estate empire, may not seek the spotlight but doesn't shun deals
that make public attention hard to avoid.
   ``There are more scholars than business tycoons among my
forebearers. All we children inherited was character, determination
and will power. ... And perhaps a little brains,'' Paul Reichmann,
who generally serves as the family spokesman, said in a rare
interview with the local Report on Business magazine.
   Paul, Albert and Ralph Reichmann were born in Austria after their
parents moved there in 1928. There were further moves to France,
Spain and Morocco before the family arrived in Canada in 1956.
   Their privately held Olympia &amp; York company now ranks as the
world's largest developer of office space, with interests in about
30 cities in Canada, the United States and Britain. Among them are
such huge projects as the World Financial Center in New York and
Canary Wharf in London.
   All of this _ a fortune estimated at $6 billion _ came from a
company that was tiny at the start of the 1960s.
   The move into real estate came when the family decided to build
its own warehouse for its Montreal tile business, Olympia Floor and
Wall Tile, in the late 1950s. Within a few years the Reichmanns were
building office towers, helped in part by a move to the booming
Toronto market of the 1960s.
   Olympia &amp; York was incorporated in 1969. The family's move into
the international top leagues usually is traced to the decision to
buy eight office buildings in Manhattan in 1977 when that market was
at a low point.
   Recently an attempt was made to buy the Sears Tower in Chicago.
   Their takeovers of newsprint producer Abitibi-Price in 1981 and
Gulf Canada Resources in 1985 placed them in visible spheres outside
of real estate.
   A struggle to take over the Canadian liquor company Hiram Walker
made it clear that even the savvy, seemingly charmed Reichmanns
could run into difficulties. That attempt ended with a swap of their
49 percent interest in the liquor company for 10 percent of the
large British conglomerate Allied-Lyons PLC.
   The Reichmanns are devout Orthodox Jews who live relatively
modestly in the affluent Toronto suburb of North York. The three
brothers have 14 children.
   Albert, 60, is the president, Paul, 58, the senior executive vice
president and secretary, and Ralph, 55, the executive vice president
and treasurer of Olympia &amp; York Developments Ltd.
   Paul Reichmann told Report on Business in December that the
family business is not particularly interested in just growing
bigger.
   ``What drives us is usually the challenge, to be creative, to do
something interesting. No successful businessman really has money in
mind after a certain point,'' he said. ``When we do something, we
want to do it right. It's not monument building; it's more than
that.''
   They gained 25 percent of Toronto-based Campeau Corp. after
providing financing that helped in its the takeover of Federated
Department Stores Inc. in February 1988. That stake expanded this
week to an estimated 35 percent with the recent round of Campeau
difficulties.
   Their movements are rarely heralded in advance, and even senior
Olympia &amp; York executives have been known to complain that they
don't know what project would attract the brothers' attention next.
   Although certainly not publicity seekers, the family, usually
Paul, does emerge to talk to reporters at times when their interests
favor public attention. Their reputation for shunning the limelight
increased after they filed an $86 million ($102 million Canadian)
libel suit in January 1988 against Toronto Life magazine for an
article called ``The Mysterious Reichmanns: The Untold Story.''
   The family then sued The Toronto Sun and the Globe and Mail
newspapers for their reports on the story and the suit.
   Paul Reichmann told Report on Business, which is a part of the
Globe and Mail, that the decision to sue was the most agonizing one
he ever made because the family's privacy would be jeopardized even
more.
   He said the suit was filed to set the record straight about his
parents' activities in North Africa during World War II and not to
discourage publicity about the family.
   ``Because of our position in world Jewry and in Canadian business
we had no choice,'' he said. ``We will spare no cost, time or effort
until every part of this story is proved false in a court of law.''
</TEXT>
