<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0801EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-PSNHBankruptcy     09-22 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-PSNH Bankruptcy,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Control of PSNH Before Judge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ADOLPHE V. BERNOTAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four utilities seeking to control Public
Service Co. of New Hampshire begin their battles today before the
bankruptcy judge who will decide the fate of the state's largest
electricity producer.
   Among the bidders is Public Service itself, forced into U.S.
Bankruptcy Court 20 months ago under the financial stress of its
lead share in the $6.2 billion Seabrook nuclear plant.
   The other contenders are United Illuminating of New Haven, Conn.,
with a plan calling for merger with Public Service; Northeast
Utilities of Berlin, Conn., that state's largest electric utility;
and New England Electric System of Westborough, Mass.
   Judge James Yacos will hold hearings on the proposals through
mid-November, when stockholders and creditors will vote. If they
pick one, Yacos likely will abide by their choice. If they choose
two, he could pick one, or find another solution.
   Public Service believes it is the frontrunner because its plan
has the creditors' and stockholders' approval.
   The other plans do not. The other utilities would have to reach
such agreement and get approval from the Securities and Exchange and
Federal Energy Regulatory commissions. Public Service needs only
state regulator approval.
   But New England Electric's plan has the primary endorsement of
Gov. Judd Gregg because it had the lowest rate projections. The
state, however, has no vote in bankruptcy court, although Yacos
could consider the state's wishes.
   Public Service has noted that its rate plan falls under the
guidelines endorsed by Gregg when the Northeast plan was introduced
in July.
   Public Service valued its plan at $2.2 billion, regardless of
whether Seabrook operates. The plant has been completed for three
years, but lacks an operating license.
   Public Service, Northeast and United Illuminating all called for
seven annual rate increases of 5.5 percent if Seabrook operates.
Public Service and Northeast also tacked on 1.1 percent a year for
five of those years if the plant is canceled, and another 2.4
percent by the end of the period if lower-price contracts can't be
renegotiated with small power producers.
   This week, United Illuminating said it was willing to cut the 5.5
percent annual rate increases to five years, with the total rate
increase at 31 percent instead of the 45 percent in the initial plan.
   The NEES plan called for increases of 4.8 percent during the
seven years, a 39 percent overall increase.
   United Illuminating also valued its plan at $2.2 billion and
Northeast valued its at $1.9 billion regardless of Seabrook. New
England Electric was $1.9 billion if it does not operate, $2.0
billion if it does.
   Public Service, with almost 400,000 customers, filed for
bankruptcy under the burden of its largest 36 percent share of
Seabrook.
   United Illuminating's 17.5 percent is the second-largest share of
Seabrook. NEES and Northeast own smaller shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
