<FIRST>r f BC-NonfatIceCream     09-22 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Nonfat Ice Cream,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ice Cream Free of Fat and Cholesterol About to Hit Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dream of weight-watching ice cream
lovers may be coming true: a fat- and cholesterol-free ice cream
that contains nearly one-third less calories.
   Kraft General Foods will introduce its new product _ Sealtest
Free Nonfat Ice Cream _ into New England markets during the first
week of October.
   Kraft, a division of of Philip Morris Cos. Inc., says the desert
has the appearance and taste of ice cream rich in butterfat.
   In the new product, the butterfat is replaced with cellulose gel,
a naturally occuring fiber found in fruit and vegetables.
   While the company is calling its new product ice cream, it may be
in for a regulatory battle since the Food and Drug Administration
requires at least 10 percent butterfat for the product to be called
ice cream.
   A spokesman for the FDA in Washington, Emil Corwin, said he was
unaware of Kraft's plan for the product.
   ``But if it is a matter of giving wrong information on the label,
it certainly would be an FDA concern,'' he said.
</TEXT>
