<HEAD>Dollar Unchanged, Stocks Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf to CORRECT Nikkei figures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted a bit higher against the Japanese
yen today before closing unchanged, while share prices on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange gained for the second-consecutive day.
   After opening at 145.80 yen, up 0.80 yen from Thursday's close,
the currency ranged between 144.95 yen and 145.80 yen before closing
the week at 145.00 yen.
   Currency dealers said the dollar remained in a relatively narrow
range ahead of the scheduled meeting of the Group of Seven
industrialized countries on Saturday in Washington.
   ``It's not easy for the dollar to find either direction in the
Tokyo market,'' prior to a major international monetary meeting,
said Shigeru Tamaki, a dealer with the Industrial Bank of Japan.
   Participants in the Washington meeting to discuss international
monetary policy include financial ministers from the United States,
Japan, Britain, West Germany, Italy, Canada and France.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues gained 26.77 points, or 0.08 percent, closing the week at
34,771.79. The Nikkei gained 274.44 points Thursday.
   Volume traded on the first section stood at 650 million shares,
the same amount that exchanged hands the previous day.
   Yutaka Yoshino, a stock analyst with the Nikko Securities Co.,
said housing and distribution-related issues are among those
attracting investors recently.
</TEXT>
