<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 0948EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BankersTrust-Bonds 1stLd-Writethru   09-22 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bankers Trust-Bonds, 1st Ld-Writethru,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bankers Trust to Become First Bank to Float Corporate Bonds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, Bankers Trust's ..., to RESTORE dropped word
million.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bankers Trust Co. plans to become the first bank
to handle the public sale of a corporate bond issue as allowed under
a recent Federal Reserve Board ruling.
   In July, the Fed, over the objection of Wall Street investment
houses, granted banks the power to sell new corporate bond issues to
the public, overturning a restriction contained in the
Depression-era Glass-Steagall Act.
   That law was designed to segregate the businesses of banking and
securities. It was prompted by the practice of banks in the 1920s of
selling corporate securities at inflated prices, with the proceeds
used to repay bank loans.
   Under the change approved by the Fed, banks must sell any bond
issues through separately financed subsidiaries in order to ensure
that federally insured bank deposits are not involved in the
financings. These subsidiaries may not borrow from their parent
banks.
   In addition, the Fed imposed rules against the sharing of
information between the subsidiaries and the banks' loan officers.
   Bankers Trust's proposed bond issue involves $150 million in
high-yield, or junk, securities for Morningstar Foods Inc. of
Dallas, a producer and distributor of dairy products.
   The New York-based bank loaned $80 million to help a group of
Texas investors buy Morningstar from Southland Corp., operator of
the 7-Eleven convenience stores, in 1988.
   Some predict the entrance of banks into junk bond financing at a
time when the junk-bond market is unsettled could produce a backlash.
   ``If this does not scare the Federal Reserve, it will certainly
scare Congress,'' William J. Fitzpatrick, general counsel to the
Securities Industry Association, told The New York Times on today's
editions.
   ``Having just rescued the savings and loan industry, I don't
think Congress wants to see the banking industry involved in such
risky businesses,'' he said.
   The trade association has fought the entrance of banks into the
securities field.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
