<FIRST>a f BC-CreditMarkets Adv25   09-22 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Credit Markets, Adv 25,0762</SECOND>
<HEAD>adv25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Sept. 25</HEAD>
<HEAD>Some Experts Say Junk Bond Market Permanently Damaged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The junk bond market's turmoil may have inflicted
lasting damage, making it more difficult to sell new issues and even
raising doubts among the investment houses that are its staunchest
backers, experts say.
   ``This was the first time that the market has really frozen,''
said Paul Getman, an economist with Wefa Group, an economic
consulting firm. ``It tells me that it is not a fully developed,
real market. Markets do not freeze.''
   Junk bond prices plunged a week and a half ago after Campeau
Corp., a major retailer and junk-bond issuer, said it would have
trouble paying its bills. Campeau's crisis mushroomed throughout the
junk-bond market, and for several days many junk issues had sellers
but no buyers.
   ``You shouldn't forget how this one incident that was limited to
one issue in the market triggered such adverse reaction elsewhere,''
said John Lonski, senior economist at Moody's Investors Service Inc.
``It makes you wonder what would happen to junk bond prices if there
were several Campeaus together, which is not an unlikely possibility.
   ``God knows what's going to happen once a downturn finally
hits,'' he said.
   Junk bonds primarily are issued by companies that do not have an
investment-grade evaluation from a major credit rating agency. They
also are used to raise the cash needed in corporate takeovers.
Because of their poor ratings and high risk of default, they pay
more interest than investment-grade bonds.
   The $200 billion market in junk bonds lost an estimated $10
billion in value in the turmoil. It also prompted a pullout by many
investors in junk-bond mutual funds _ the only place where small
investors would have direct exposure to the high-yield market.
   Though the market recovered somewhat last week, jitters remain.
   ``The junk bond market still faces considerable uncertainty,''
said Lonski. He added that the Campeau debacle was ``a shocker''
since the Toronto-based company was not considered to be in such
precarious condition.
   Lonski said nervousness in the junk market was evident before
Campeau. Just prior to the crisis, the average difference in yields
between junk bonds and 10-year Treasury bonds _ considered among the
safest investments _ was 5.4 percentage points, or nearly 1.4
percentage points greater than the yield spread at the start of the
year.
   ``The overall junk bond market may not fully recover to where it
was at the start of this year until it has been put through the test
of a recession,'' Lonski said.
   Some experts are less pessimistic. James C. Goss, a high-yield
analyst at the Chicago investment firm Duff &amp; Phelps Inc., said it's
not the first time the market has taken a hit but then recovered.
   ``It was an important event. But I don't know that it signaled
the end of the market,'' Goss said.
   Goss and other market-watchers said one outcome of Campeau's
troubles is that investors are going to demand that new junk issues
involve less leverage by the issuing companies and more realistic
plans about how the debt is going to be repaid.
   Many experts said Campeau paid too much for Allied Stores Corp.
and Federated Department Stores Inc., deals that led to its trouble,
and was forced to sell assets at prices below its expectations to
raise cash. The easy availability of money through selling junk
bonds doesn't lead to bargain hunting, they say.
   In addition, many analysts said, there's going to be more
awareness of the distinction between ``good'' junk and ``bad'' junk.
   Good junk bonds are issued by companies such as RJR Nabisco Inc.,
financially strong companies in industries that don't usually suffer
in recessions. Bad junk comes from weaker companies in cyclical
businesses.
   Finally, analysts said, more realism should be evident among the
investment houses that promote junk bonds and their clients that
issue them.
   ``You'll find that investment banks are going to scrutinize a lot
more closely these deals that they are putting together,'' said
Getman. ``They are getting stuck with unsold (junk) bonds for the
first time. In the past they passed these deals off on the public.
   ``I guess this is going to be one of the nice examples where Wall
Street is going to fleece itself as well as the public,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday, Sept. 25</NOTE>
</DOC>
