<FIRST>r f PM-FraudSettlement     09-22 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fraud Settlement,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fraud Settlement Could Cost Company $100 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 300,000 California residents are
eligible for refunds of high-interest loans packed with expensive
extras under settlement of a lawsuit that could cost ITT Consumer
Financial Corp. up to $100 million.
   The company did not admit wrongdoing, but state Attorney General
John Van de Kamp said ITT's loan practices since 1986 amounted to
``consumer fraud on a grand scale.''
   Van de Kamp said the Minnesota-based company took advantage of
people ``in desperate need of money'' and charged them up to 35
percent interest on loans and unnecessary extras.
   ``Every person who lost money to ITT can recover every dime, plus
interest. There is no cap on total refund due to consumers,'' Van de
Kamp told reporters Thursday, when the settlement was reached in
Alameda County Superior Court.
   The settlement came on a civil complaint filed by Van de Kamp
that accused ITT of assorted deceptions, lies and bait-and-switch
tactics.
   Van de Kamp said ITT mailed millions of California residents
invitations to apply for ``guaranteed'' loans of $2,300, promising
the money was ``pre-approved with no security required and no credit
checks.''
   Applicants who took up ITT on the offer ``were immediately
subjected to full security checks. ... They were presented with
ready-to-sign loan agreements that pledged their household goods and
cars as security, often far in excess of the loans,'' Van de Kamp
said.
   Applicants ``were often signed up for life, disability, property
and vehicle insurance, insurance that they did not need and did not
know they were buying,'' he said.
   In a statement, ITT did not admit any misdeeds, but said the
practices alleged by the state ``without doubt were contraventions
to our procedures and not a pattern of behavior condoned by the
company.''
   Restitution could be as much as $100 million to 300,000 loan
holders, but the number of consumers who apply for refunds likely
will be closer to 100,000, Van de Kamp said. The lower number of
consumers would cost ITT $25 million to $50 million, with an
additional $10.5 million to be set aside in trust for people who are
located later.
   Loan holders are to be contacted by letter with an explanation of
how to apply for refunds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
