<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1156EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   09-22 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Dip On Reduced Freeze Fears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were narrowly
mixed in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade,
reflecting reduced fears of a crop-damaging freeze this weekend in
the Midwest.
   The steadying of the markets follows sharply higher corn and
soybean futures in the two previous sessions on forecasts for a hard
freeze in the Corn Belt this weekend and early next week.
   But this morning's forecasts showed less of a chance for
widespread frost and a return to normal temperatures next week.
   Wheat futures weakened in reaction to the International Wheat
Council's downward revision _ to 31 million metric tons from 36
million metric tons _ of estimated Soviet grain imports for the
current wheat marketing year, which runs from June through May.
   The revision follows Soviet statements that they plan fewer grain
imports.
   ``We could be looking at a decrease in demand while U.S.
production has increased sharply from a year ago, which would be a
negative scenario,'' said Gerald Zusel, manager of Balfour Maclaine
Corp.'s floor operations at the Board of Trade.
   In early trading, wheat futures were unchanged to } cent higher
with the contract for delivery in December at $3.94 a bushel; corn
was } cent lower to 1\ cents higher with December at $2.31 a bushel;
oats were } cent to 1\ cents higher with December at $1.42} a
bushel; soybeans were { cent lower to 8 cents higher with November
at $5.82\ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were higher in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .30 cent lower to .18 cent higher with October
at 71.40 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .10
cent higher with September at 83 cents a pound; hogs were .18 cent
to .57 cent higher with October at 42.45 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .05 cent to .90 cent higher with February at 49.65
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
