<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     09-22 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Noon,0267</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market drifted lower today, still stuck
in the neutral pattern of the past several sessions.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 3.23 to 2,677.05
by noontime on Wall Street.
   Losers slightly outnumbered gainers in the overall tally of New
York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 577 up, 636 down and 565
unchanged.
   Analysts said nothing had occurred to stir the market out of its
recent torpor.
   The rally that carried prices to record highs just before the
Labor Day weekend crested as it became evident that interest rates
had stopped falling.
   That left investors in something of a stalemate between those who
expect persistent economic growth at a moderate pace and those who
still believe a significant slowdown awaits in the not-too-distant
future.
   J.P. Morgan climbed 1} to 41{. Late Thursday the company
increased by $2 billion its reserves against problem loans to
lesser-developed countries.
   Procter &amp; Gamble dropped 2 to 119~. The company agreed to acquire
Noxell Corp. through an exchange of stock.
   Cummins Engine tumbled 3[ to 59{. The company said it expects to
post a substantial loss for the third quarter, largely because of
reduced demand for its products.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.19 to 192.35. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .09 at 380.13.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 64.42 million shares at noontime,
against 67.49 million at the same point Thursday.
</TEXT>
