<FIRST>u f BC-AmwaySuit 1stLd-Writethru   09-22 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Amway Suit, 1st Ld-Writethru,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canada Drops Suit Against Amway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS dollar figures in Lead to U.S., sted Canadian; RECASTS
6th graf pvs bgng: The 9-year-old ...; picks up 7th graf pvs bgng: Amway
officials ...</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dollars are in U.S.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amway Corp. has agreed to pay $38.1 million to
settle charges it avoided paying Canadian duties, and in exchange
the government dropped a $125.4 million suit against the direct
sales company, an official said Friday.
   A spokesman for Revenue Minister Otto Jelinek said the government
filed notice to drop the suit Wednesday in the Federal Court of
Canada. Amway initiated negotiations to settle the case a year ago,
he added.
   ``It's not a bad settlement,'' said the spokesman, who asked not
to be identified.
   Amway officials at the company's headquarters in Ada, Mich., were
not immediately available for comment.
   Canada's revenue agency had accused the Amway of avoiding custom
duties by undervaluing merchandise it exported from the United
States to Canadian distributors during a six-year period beginning
in 1974.
   The 9-year-old lawsuit sought money for unpaid customs duties,
sales taxes and the value of the Amway products that crossed into
Canada during those six years.
   Amway officials had said they were confident that Revenue Canada
could not collect because the agency's lawyers failed to include
that claim in their original suit.
   In 1983, Amway pleaded guilty to criminal charges related to
fraud allegations and paid a $25 million fine to the Province of
Ontario.
   Amway is second to Avon Products Inc. in direct sales worldwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
