<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1324EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-US-Poland-Debt     09-22 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-US-Poland-Debt,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mosbacher Suggests Debt Moratorium To Help Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western aid to Poland could include a
moratorium on interest payments of $26 billion in debt held by the
country's official creditors, U.S. Commerce Secretary Robert
Mosbacher said Friday.
   ``I think we're going to see some help,'' Mosbacher told the
Swiss-American Chamber of Commerce. ``I think we'll probably end up
giving Poland a moratorium on interet payments.''
   Asked to clarify, he said: ``I'm speaking about the public debt.
I'm not dealing with the private debt, and I think under the right
conditions there could be some sort of moratorium.''
   Mosbacher, speaking after a trip including stops in Poland and
Hungary, said the moratorium idea was a personal view.
   But he added that the Bush administration has asked the World
Bank and other Western countries involved in fighting the debt
crisis to help find ways to ease Poland's $40 billion foreign debt,
of which $26 billion is in government-backed credits.
   Poland in 1988 ran up about $450 million in missed debt payments
and faces debt-servicing costs of about $4 billion this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
