<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1449EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-AmwaySuit     09-22 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Amway Suit,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amway Pays Canada $38 Million to Settle Suit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: All figures are in U.S. dollars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amway Corp. has agreed to pay the
Canadian government $38.1 million to settle a $125.4-million tax
fraud lawsuit filed 10 years ago, officials said Friday.
   ``It was done with the intent of saving a lot of time and expense
in these complex legal procedures,'' said Jean Ouimet, a spokesman
for Revenue Canada's Customs and Excise Division.
   The settlement, combined with a $21-million criminal fine paid by
Amway to the Province of Ontario in 1983, brings to $59 million the
amount the giant direct-sales company has paid to end its legal
troubles in Canada.
   Canada's revenue agency had accused Amway of avoiding custom
duties by undervaluing merchandise it exported from 1974-80 from the
United States to Canadian distributors.
   The lawsuit, which was dropped Wednesday, sought money for unpaid
customs duties, sales taxes and the value of the Amway products that
crossed into Canada during those six years.
   In 1982, Canada also brought criminal charges against Amway
co-founders Richard DeVos and Jay VanAndel and two other top
executives in connection with the case. Those charges were dropped
in 1983 after Amway pleaded guilty and paid the $21 million fine.
   Otto Stolz, Amway's general counsel, said the company is under a
gag order not to discuss the particulars of the settlement.
   Amway is second to Avon Products Inc. in direct sales worldwide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
