<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1539EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Ford-Jaguar 1stLd-Writethru   09-22 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ford-Jaguar, 1st Ld-Writethru,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jaguar Board Calls Ford Overtures Unwelcome</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS lead to CLARIFY Ford initiative unwelcome; uppicks 2nd
graf pvs: Ford announced...; SUBS 8th graf to expand on government restrictions.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jaguar PLC's board of directors on Friday
characterized Ford Motor Co.'s plans to buy a stake in the company
as an unwelcome initiative and vowed to preserve the British luxury
auto maker's independence.
   Ford announced Tuesday it intended to buy as much as 15 percent
of Jaguar's shares, the maximum allowed under current British
government restrictions.
   In its response, Jaguar said in a brief statement following a
board meeting that its directors ``confirmed that the Ford
initiative was unwelcome.''
   In addition, directors ``determined to continue to pursue plans
that would preserve Jaguar's independence, which they believe to be
in the best long-term interests of everyone associated with the
company.''
   A Jaguar spokesman declined to elaborate.
   Jaguar stock rose 52 cents a share to finish at $9.18 on London's
Stock Exchange. Takeover speculation has pushed Jaguar stock sharply
higher this week. On Monday, the day preceeding the Ford
announcement, Jaguar closed at just $6.40 a share.
   Ford said it sought long-term relationship with the unprofitable
British automaker. But Ford added that it was too early to say
whether it would seek to acquire Jaguar once the government's
restrictions on its ownership are lifted at the end of the year.
   Until the end of 1990, the maximum holding allowed in Jaguar is
15 percent and the government has the right to veto any takeover.
The government imposed those restrictions when it privatized Jaguar
in 1984.
   Ford characterized its approach as friendly. Jaguar said it was
notified of Ford's plans shortly before the U.S. automaker made the
announcement.
   There has been speculation that fellow U.S. car manufacturer
General Motors Corp., along with other auto makers, also were
interested in pursuing Jaguar.
   While Jaguar has held out the possibility of collaborating with
another car maker, a spokesman earlier in the week affirmed the
company's desire to remain independent.
   Jaguar has been battered by flagging sales in its principal U.S.
market during the past year. The company expects to sell 20,000 cars
in the United States this year, down from 20,700 in 1988.
   For the first six months of the year, Jaguar posted an after-tax
loss of $1.7 million on sales of $870 million.
   Analysts said Ford, which already has a huge European presence
and is negotiating a possible transaction with Swedish automaker
Saab, could benefit from an association with the well-known Jaguar
luxury car line.
   Ford of Europe, which is headquartered in Brentwood, England,
makes 1.8 million vehicles a year. It has 21 European plants, 11 of
them in Britain, and employs more than 110,000 people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
