<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1454EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-NWA-Skinner 2ndLd-Writethru f0086 09-22 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NWA-Skinner, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0086,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Skinner Informs Checchi of Northwest Decision</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: TOPS with 2 grafs to recast lead, edits throughout to conform,
deletes second DOT spokesman; No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner today
told the new owners of Northwest Airlines his decision on his review
of the $4 billion takeover of NWA Inc., a department spokesman said.
But an announcement was not due until next week.
   Skinner has the option of pulling the airline's operating
license, but there has been no indication that is likely.
   Transportation Department spokesman Hal Paris said a decision has
been made in the department's review of the takeover by Wings
Holdings Ltd. of NWA, Northwest's parent company. He said Skinner
met this morning with California investor Alfred Checchi, who heads
Wings.
   Paris said results of the department's fitness review of the $4
billion takeover would likely be made public next week.
   He said the department's public affairs office had been given no
details of the meeting but Skinner would have told Checchi whether
any restrictions might be put on the airline's operating license
because of the buyout.
   Paris, said conditions could include requiring the airline to
furnish regular financial reports and putting restrictions on the
carrier's management.
   Skinner informed Checchi of his decision before making it public
because he ``didn't want Mr. Checchi reading about (the findings) in
the paper,'' the spokesman said.
   Checchi led a group including KLM Royal Dutch Airlines that
agreed in June to pay $121 a share for NWA. Northwest is the
nation's fourth-largest airline.
   Skinner has expressed concern about leverage buyouts and
increasing foreign investment in U.S. airlines. The Checchi takeover
saddles Northwest with $3.1 billion in debt.
   Without mentioning Northwest, Skinner said in a speech to the
International Aviation Club Tuesday that he would make adjustments
in a heavily leveraged airline's operating certificate if necessary
to protect the public interest.
   ``Or, if absolutely necessary,'' he added, ``and I hope that
doesn't take place, we will revoke the certificate.''
   The Justice Department also investigated the Northwest sale but
did not raise any objections, said spokeswoman Amy Brown.
   The department's review was prompted by antitrust issues raised
by KLM's interest in the sale, Brown said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
