<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   09-22 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Fall as Frost Fears Recede</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices fell steeply Friday,
leading the grain markets lower amid receding fears of a hard frost
in the Midwest this weekend.
   The buying erased the gains made in the previous sesssion, when
soybeans led a strong rally linked to forecasts for a near-record
cold snap in crop-growing areas still vulnerable to frost damage.
   But many meteorologists altered their outlooks on Friday.
   ``Most of the forecasts now are minimizing the chance for frost
this weekend,'' said Gerald Zusel, manager of Balfour Maclaine
Corp.'s floor operations at the Board of Trade.
   ``They're talking about minimal frost in isolated areas with the
potential for a return to normal temperatures next week,'' he said.
   At the close, wheat futures were } cent to 5\ cents lower with
the contract for delivery in December at $3.89 a bushel; corn was 1}
cents lower to \ cent higher with December at $2.29} a bushel; oats
were { cent to 1 cent lower with December at at $1.40} a bushel;
soybeans were unchanged to 8} cents lower with November at $5.74 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
