<DOCNO> AP890922-0287 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1652EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-OPEC     09-22 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-OPEC,0767</SECOND>
<HEAD>OPEC Oil Ministers Gather for Talks on Raising Output Ceiling</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subroto cq as full name</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC ministers, gathering for weekend talks on the
oil market, appeared at odds Friday over whether to lift their
production ceiling in the final three months of the year.
   Even before the start of discussions scheduled for late Saturday,
some ministers arriving in Geneva expressed concern over what they
consider to be weak crude prices. Eight ministers comprising the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries' price monitoring and
long-term strategy committee are scheduled to meet.
   An increase in OPEC production, which some believe the ministers
might authorize, would likely cause prices to slip, analysts say.
   ``There's no need to raise the ceiling as long as the price
objective is not met,'' said Algerian Oil Minister Sadek Boussena.
   But Issam Abdul Raheem al-Chalabi, Iraq's oil chief, said, ``I
would like to see a reasonable increase in the ceiling.'' He didn't
specify a level.
   However, observers as well as some OPEC ministers have said they
don't expect a resolution to the volatile issue of permanent quotas
at this latest meeting. Instead, it appeared the quota issue would
be bumped to November, when the full cartel is to meet in Vienna.
   ``We can always discuss it, but there will not be a decision in
this area,'' said Boussena.
   The 13-nation cartel is pumping about 22 million barrels a day,
according to various estimates, well over the output cap of 19.5
million barrels set by OPEC for the last six months of the year.
   The ministers agreed in June to meet this month to decide whether
to lift the ceiling 500,000 barrels a day to 20 million barrels, or
perhaps more.
   Although world oil prices are weaker than they were last spring
and remain below the catel's benchmark of $18 a barrel, strong
demand has kept them surprisingly firm despite OPEC's excess
production.
   OPEC Secretary-General Subroto has estimated that demand for the
cartel's oil might be around 22 million barrels a day in the
October-December quarter.
   A basket of seven crudes monitored by OPEC averaged $17.04 a
barrel last week. It had topped the $18-mark last spring.
   West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of American oil, has
been trading in the range of $19.50 to $20 a 42-gallon barrel.
   Chalabi, arriving in mid-afternoon from an energy conference in
Montreal, told reporters that the OPEC ministers would review
conditions in the constantly changing oil market.
   He said some countries were opposed to an output increase because
``they want to defend the price.'' Others, he said, think ``supply
and demand warrant a much higher ceiling.''
   Boussena said there was a ``link'' between the cartel's
production level and its price, and he noted that prices had not
reached OPEC's benchmark in the last three months.
   Ecuador's Diego Tamariz also seemed worried about prices.
   ``We still have to obtain the goal of $18,'' he said, adding that
``we should work on it.''
   Fergus MacLeod, an analyst at the investment firm of Barclays de
Zoete Wedd in London, said prices would likely fall 50 cents or a
dollar a barrel if the cartel were to lift the supply cap without
curtailing members' cheating.
   An increase of 500,000 barrels a day, he said, would probably
kick up total output to about 22.5 million barrels.
   The ministers were also expected to begin tackling the tough
issue of how to meet some members' demands for a higher share of the
production pie. Each country is given a quota, or a daily production
level.
   Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates have in recent months ignored
their quotas and pumped as much as double their shares' of about a
million barrels each, analysts' estimate.
   Kuwait's oil minister, Ali Khalifa al-Sabah, said his promise at
the June meeting to hold the line on production was conditional.
   ``If everybody sticks to the quota, fine. If anybody breaks it,
the others have the same right,'' he told reporters outside the
luxury hotel where the ministers' will hold their discussions.
   The talks will technically be held by a monitoring panel of
ministers from Algeria, Indonesia, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Nigeria,
Saudi Arabia and Venezuela. The others - Gabon, Ecuador, Libya,
Qatar and the United Arab Emirates - were also invited to attend.
   Saudia Arabia's oil minister, Hisham Nazer, was reported
recovering from surgery in the United States and was not attending.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890922-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1555EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Chrysler-Mitsubishi Bjt   09-22 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chrysler-Mitsubishi, Bjt,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Selling Nearly Half Its Mitsubishi Holdings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. said Friday it is selling about
half its stock in the Japanese automaker Mitsubishi Motors Corp. and
will receive about $310 million after taxes.
   An analyst said the move indicates the No. 3 American automaker,
which is in the midst of a $1 billion cost-cutting program, is being
cautious about the future of the U.S. auto market.
   Chrysler said the sale of Mitsubishi stock will drop its holdings
in its Japanese partner to 12.1 percent from 21.8 percent. A group
of 25 Japanese financial institutions is buying the stock for about
$592 million, Chrysler said.
   Chrysler, which owns an assembly plant with Mitsubishi in
Illinois, said the stock sale was not directly connected with the
automaker's financial trimming.
   ``The fact is, we didn't need (the $310 million) to meet the
short-term cash needs of implementing our billion-dollar cutting
program,'' Chrysler Chief Financial Officer Robert Miller said.
   He said Chrysler was not making much money on the Mitsubishi
stock investment, and selling 45 percent of its shares would help
boost the U.S. company's cash reserves.
   But analyst David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. of New
York said the sale was an ``indicator of Chrysler's overall caution
on the outlook for the business in the United States.''
   ``It was not producing a cash return and now that they own half
of what they owned before in Mitsubishi, they still will have the
same business relationship and will be able to take a good bit of
cash out,'' he said.
   Miller said the deal would not affect the cooperation between the
two companies.
   ``By selling, we don't think the party's over by any means,''
Miller said.
   Mitsubishi Motor Sales of America Inc., the Japanese company's
U.S. marketing arm in Cypress, Calif., had no comment on Chrysler's
move, spokesman Kim Custer said.
   Chrysler and Mitsubishi are involved in the joint manufacturing
venture Diamond-Star Motors Corp. in Normal, Ill., where Plymouth
Laser, Mitsubishi Eclipse and Eagle Talon are manufactured.
Mitsubishi also supplies more than 500,000 V-6 engines to Chrysler
annually.
   In 1971, Chrysler bought into Mitsubishi, at the time a privately
held company.
   Since then, Chrysler has been on a financial roller coaster. The
U.S. government guaranteed loans during the late 1970s that Chrysler
eventually paid off seven years early.
   Chrysler announced July 27 that it would slash $1 billion from
its $26 billion annual budget by the end of 1990.
   Chrysler Motors Corp. Chairman Ben Bidwell, head of the company's
vehicle-making arm, blamed the cuts on a slumping sales market;
rising costs, especially in consumer incentives; and forecasts of a
softer economy.
   Earlier this week, Chrysler Motors President Bob Lutz said the
company expected total U.S. car sales of 14.2 million vehicles in
1990, 4 percent to 5 percent below this year and 10.1 percent below
1988, the second-best year in auto history.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
