<FIRST>r f AM-Maxwell-Graphics     09-22 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Maxwell-Graphics,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maxwell Reports Several Inquiries To Buy Maxwell Graphics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maxwell Communication Corp. PLC said Friday that
it has received ``a number of inquiries'' regarding its previously
disclosed plans to sell its Maxwell Graphics business, the second
largest commercial printer in the United States.
   Chairman Robert Maxwell said it has retained the investment
banking firm Wertheim, Schroder &amp; Co. Inc. to act as its exclusive
financial adviser in the sale.
   Maxwell Graphics, which is based in Minneapolis, consists of four
printing companies Maxwell acquired over the past four years at a
cost of more than $500 million. It has 15 plants employing 4,500
people throughout the country.
   But the parent company, one of the world's largest media
concerns, has shifted its strategic focus away from printing and
toward publishing.
   In the past year, Maxwell has purchased the publishing and
information services giant Macmillan Inc. for $2.5 billion and the
Official Airlines Guide for $750 million. Earlier this week, it
agreed to buy the textbook concern Merrill Publishing from Bell &amp;
Howell Co. for $260 million in cash.
   Earlier this year, Maxwell sold its commercial and newspaper
printing operations in Great Britain, where the parent company is
based, and said it intended to sell its U.S. printing business by
March 1990.
   Maxwell spokesman David Adler said the U.S. printing operation
had about about $750 million in gross revenue last year and was
second only to R.R. Donnelly &amp; Sons Co. of Chicago.
   Maxwell Graphics prints Parade magazine, which is a supplement to
many Sunday newspapers in the United States, and some of the
editions of several Time Inc. Magazines Co.
</TEXT>
