<FIRST>u f AM-BrokerageSuit 1stLd-Writethru f0194 09-22 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brokerage Suit, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0194,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thomson McKinnon Employees Allege Mismanagement, Seek $100 Million</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT typo in `bankrupted'; SUBS 4th graf to
ADD number of plaintiffs; PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `The lawsuit...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Thomson McKinnon Inc. employees filed
a $100 million lawsuit Friday claiming that executives of the Wall
Street brokerage bankrupted an employee trust fund and used company
assets to pay for apartments and a yacht.
   The federal suit also alleges that a deal to sell struggling
Thomson McKinnon this year fell through after buyer Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. discovered the brokerage was overvalued by $80
million to $95 million.
   After the deal collapsed, Prudential-Bache in July purchased only
Thomson McKinnon's retail brokerage offices and customer accounts.
   The company denied the allegations in the lawsuit, filed by 16
current and former Thomson McKinnon employees in U.S. District Court
in Manhattan as a class action on behalf of an estimated 2,800
employees who owned stock in the firm, which traces its formation to
1885.
   The lawsuit claims Thomson McKinnon executives used assets in an
employee stock ownership plan, or ESOP, in ``a well planned and
executed scheme to personally profit at the expense of'' the firm,
its subsidiaries and the ESOP.
   Thomson McKinnon allegedly kept apartments in Puerto Rico and
Manhattan for senior officers; bought and maintained a $1.3 million
yacht for the company's president; gave executives disguised weekly
cash payments for personal use; and paid school tuition for former
chairman John J. Maloney Jr.'s 13 children.
   The lawsuit alleges broad financial mismanagement, including a
$125 million loan to a real estate investment trust that went
bankrupt and a costly decision to move the company's offices shortly
after the 1987 stock market crash.
   The firm also regularly overstated the company's earnings and
assets to induce employees to buy into the ESOP, the lawsuit claims.
The financial mismanagement, it alleges, led to the collapsed deal
with Prudential-Bache.
   Donald G. McCabe, general counsel for Thomson McKinnon Securities
Inc., the firm's brokerage arm, said the defendants ``will most
firmly deny the allegations'' and that the lawsuit is ``without
merit.''
   He declined immediate comment on specific allegations in the suit.
   The lawsuit says employees held about 77 percent of the stock in
stock in Thomson McKinnon as part of their regular compensation and
the ESOP was worth about $140 million in 1986.
   A year later it was estimated at $125 million, the plaintiffs
claim, but on July 31 this year the employees received a letter from
Thomson McKinnon Chairman J. Ronald Morgan stating that ``it is
possible (the ESOP) will have no value whatsoever.''
   The letter, distributed after the deal for the brokerage
division, also stated the ESOP would be canceled because the sale of
the full company to Prudential-Bache had fallen through.
   The lawsuit claims employees would have received the cash
equivalent of the stock following a sale, but lost that money when
the deal fell through because of the alleged mismanagement.
   The suit seeks more than $100 million in damages, or the amount
in the ESOP allegedly dissipated by executive mismanagement.
   In addition to Thomson McKinnon, Morgan and Maloney, the lawsuit
names company chairman Philip M. Fahey, six other senior executives
and the accounting firm Coopers &amp; Lybrand.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
