<DOCNO> AP890922-0296 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 2025EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PSNHBankruptcy     09-22 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PSNH Bankruptcy,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Says Public Service Can Seek Federal Regulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ADOLPHE V. BERNOTAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge James Yacos ruled
Friday that Public Service Co. of New Hampshire can reorganize under
federal law which means the company can bypass state regulators in
setting electricity rates in its reorganization.
   The decision was issued from the bench. Yacos said he would have
a formal ruling next month.
   Under state law, Public Service cannot charge ratepayers for the
Seabrook nuclear power plant until it operates commercially. The
idle plant has been finished for three years but lacks a full-power
commercial operating license. Public Service was forced into U.S.
Bankruptcy Court 20 months ago under the financial stress of its
lead share in the $6.2 billion plant.
   Under federal regulations, the company could seek wholesale rate
regulation, bypassing state control.
   Nicholas Ashooh, a spokesman for the utility, said however that
Public Service has no intention of seeking federal regulation.
   ``We plan to continue to talk with the state to achieve a
mutually agreeable resolution,'' he said.
   Martin Gross, the utility's lawyer, stressed that Public Service
will try to reach an agreement with the state ``with state
regulation.''
   Larry Smukler, the state's chief negotiator, said the decision
``is adverse to us, to the public interest of New Hampshire.''
   He said the state will appeal the decision, adding that ``the
state of New Hampshire will not let this (federal regulation)
happen.''
   He said the state's ``last resort will be to acquire the company
voluntarily or involuntarily'' under the state's recently enacted
power authority legislation.
   The decision is seen as giving the utility leverage in its
negotiations with the state to set rates in the reorganized company.
   Yacos and parties to the bankruptcy were in federal bankruptcy
court to discuss the plans filed for reorganizing Public Service.
   Yacos reassured critics from Public Service's unsecured
creditors' committee, who say New Hampshire Gov. Judd Gregg is
manipulating the value of the utility for political reasons.
   In papers filed this past week with the court, the creditors'
committee asked Yacos to reassert strong control over the case.
   The governor has given his endorsement to a buyout offer from New
England Electric System of Westborough, Mass. The endorsement
superseded his earlier approval of an offer from Northeast Utilities
of Berlin, Conn.
   United Illuminating of New Haven, Conn., also seeks to merge with
the troubled utility.
   Yacos will hold hearings on the proposals through mid-November,
when shareholders and creditors will vote. If they choose one, Yacos
likely will abide by their choice. If they choose two, he could pick
one, or find another solution.
   Public Service believes it is the frontrunner because its
reorganization plan has the creditors' and shareholders' approval.
   The other plans do not. The other utilities would have to reach
such agreement and get approval from the U.S. Securities and
Exchange Commission and the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
Public Service needs only state regulatory approval.
   But New England Electric's plan has Gregg's endorsement because
it had the lowest rate projections. The state, however, has no vote
in bankruptcy court, although Yacos could consider the state's
wishes.
   Public Service, with almost 400,000 customers, filed for
bankruptcy protection from creditors under the burden of its largest
36 percent share of Seabrook.
   United Illuminating's 17.5 percent is the second-largest share of
Seabrook. NEES and Northeast own smaller shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890922-0297 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 2027EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AlleghenyInternational     09-22 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Allegheny International,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Creditors Want Company To Pay Cash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc.'s plan to emerge
from Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization has developed another
hitch.
   Its latest plan, the sixth it has filed in 19 months, is being
rewritten because senior bondholders and certain lenders insist on
being repaid in cash rather than high-risk junk bonds.
   That will force changes in other major parts of the plan,
although the amount of distributions to creditors and shareholders
probably will not change, said Allegheny attorney Bruce McCullough.
   Among the changes may be a revision in how the reorganized
company, a former conglomerate now best known for making Sunbeam and
Oster appliances, will pay retirees' pensions and health benefits.
   The company previously had proposed paying benefits from a fund
to be financed by selling such non-core assets as real estate and
its half-interest in Titanium Metals Corp. of America. That proposal
may be scrapped, McCullough said.
   The Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp., the government agency that
insures pensions, has objected to that arrangement as too uncertain.
   Robert Sable, an attorney for bondholders and other unsecured
creditors, said at a hearing in U.S. Bankruptcy Court Thursday that
a revised plan could be ready in 20 or 30 days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
