<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose Friday in thin, erratic trading
in advance of a meeting Saturday between finance ministers of the
Group of Seven industrialized nations. Gold prices also rose.
   The Federal Reserve sold dollars for a fourth straight day,
dealers said, but the currency bounced back from the intervention
and ended near the highs of the session.
   Dealers said the dollar rose in spite of some speculation that
the finance ministers would plan more serious steps at their
Washington meeting to push down the dollar to help shrink the U.S.
trade deficit.
   The Group of Seven is the United States, Britain, Japan, West
Germany, France, Italy and Canada.
   Most traders went home Friday without any positions for or
against the dollar because of uncertainty about what the meeting
would produce, said Kevin Lawrie, senior foreign-exchange manager at
Bank of Boston in New York.
   ``We're approaching this next situation very tentatively. People
have been whipsawed,'' he said.
   The market showed little reaction to a Commerce Department report
that consumer spending rose 0.9 percent and personal income rose 0.4
percent in August. The report pointed toward continued economic
expansion.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 145.00 Japanese yen, unchanged
from Thursday. In London late Friday the dollar traded higher at
145.35 yen. At the end of the day in New York the dollar rose to
146.05 yen from 145.65 on Thursday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.5755 late Friday, cheaper
for buyers than Thursday's late $1.5805. In New York the pound fell
against the dollar to $1.5715 from $1.5790.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Thursday's
late rates, included: 1.9530 West German marks, up from 1.9466;
1.6933 Swiss francs, up from 1.6835; 1.1814 Canadian dollars, down
from 1.1830; 6.6025 French francs, up from 6.5740; and 1,405.38
Italian lire, up from 1,400.25.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Thursday's late
rates, included: 1.9495 West German marks, up from 1.9435; 1.6890
Swiss francs, up from 1.6830; 6.5925 French francs, up from 6.5710;
2.1935 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1920; 1,407.50 Italian lire, up
from 1,401.00, and 1.1807 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1842.
   Gold prices were higher in active trading. The late London gold
price was $364.50 bid a troy ounce, up from $363.25 late Thursday.
The Zurich late bid price was $365.50, up from $363.50.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
rose to $366.20 a troy ounce from $365.50 Thursday. Later, Republic
National Bank of New York said gold was bid at $364.25 an ounce as
of 4 p.m. EDT, up from $363.85 Thursday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $364.15 bid, up from $363.85.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $5.27 a troy ounce,
up from $5.14. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for current
delivery rose to $5.286 from $5.181 on Thursday.
