<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1808EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     09-22 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Slip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices finished slightly lower Friday in
light dealings as traders were wary of making big commitments in
advance of this weekend's meeting of major industrialized nations.
   The Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond lost 1-16 point, or 63
cents for every $1,000 face amount, as its yield rose to 8.19
percent from 8.18 percent late Thursday.
   ``It's been like the calm before the storm, but I'm not saying
there is going to be any storm,'' said Maria Ramirez, economist for
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. ``There's nothing going on.''
   She said the relative inactivity reflected some anxiety about
decisions that may be made at this weekend's meeting of the finance
ministers and central bankers from the Group of Seven major
industrialized nations.
   The group includes representatives from the United States, Japan,
West Germany, France, Britain, Italy and Canada.
   The group could make decisions that would affect the course of
the dollar on foreign exchange markets and the attractiveness of
dollar-denominated securities for foreign investors.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
governments were unchanged to down 1-32 point, intermediate
maturities fell [ point and long-term issues dropped as much as 5-32
point, according to Telerate Inc., the financial information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, fell 0.68 to 1,174.66.
   In corporate trading, industrials were lower. Moody's Investment
Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return on a
portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or
longer, fell 0.79 to 330.99.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell 1-32 point. The average yield to
maturity was unchanged at 7.48 percent, the same as late Thursday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 8.01 percent as the
discount lost 6 basis points to 7.74 percent. Yields on six-month
bills held steady at 8.15 percent as the discount was firm at 7.74
percent. Yields on one-year bills issued at auction Thursday rose to
8.21 percent as the discount gained 4 basis points to 7.64 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted at 815-16 percent, unchanged from late Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890922-0305 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1810EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     09-22 0684</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0710</SECOND>
<HEAD>Silver Rally Continues; Gains 23 Cents In Three Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Silver futures prices rose sharply for a third straight day
Friday on New York's Commodity Exchange but analysts were divided on
whether the market could sustain the technically inspired rally.
   On other markets, gold futures also rose; energy, coffee, grain
and soybean futures retreated; and livestock and meat futures were
mixed.
   Silver futures settled 10.5 cents to 11 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $5.286 a troy ounce. That
price reflects a gain of more than 23.1 cents in three days. The
more actively traded December contract finished at $5.38 a troy
ounce.
   Gold futures settled 30 cents to 70 cents higher with October at
$366.70 a troy ounce.
   Several analysts agreed the rally was largely technical,
representing waves of buying triggered by the September contract's
drop to $5.01 an ounce the previous Friday. The proximity to $5 an
ounce, a point of strong psychological resistance, gave market bears
pause and brought in new buyers.
   Although supply-and-demand factors have not changed, said Peter
Cardillo, commodity trading adviser with Josephthal &amp; Co. in New
York, the December contract's close above $5.35 indicated it could
rise as high as $5.55 an ounce before finding substantial resistance.
   But Scott Hinton of Elder Futures Inc. said the December contract
would have a hard time ramming past $5.40.
   ``I think gold has a little bit more to go on the upside but
silver is getting close to the level where you'd expect to find
fairly good resistance,'' he said.
   Most energy futures ended lower on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, although the October gasoline contract advanced slightly
amid speculation about the extent of damage caused by Hurricane Hugo
to an Amerada Hess Corp. refinery on the Caribbean island of St.
Croix.
   Other energy contracts retreated on profit-taking after rallying
sharply on hurricane-related fears earlier in the week.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 27 cents to 35 cents
lower with November at $19.28 a barrel; heating oil was .61 cent to
.84 cent lower with October at 56.97 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was 1.04 cents lower to .09 cent higher with October at
61.95 cents a gallon.
   Coffee futures fell sharply on New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa
Exchange as hopes for a restoration of coffee export quotas faded.
   The International Coffee Organization opens a two-week meeting
Monday in London but most experts do not expect the 74
nation-members to agree on new price-support measures.
   Coffee settled 1.88 cents to 3.38 cents lower with December at
80.65 cents a pound.
   Soybean futures tumbled on the Chicago Board of Trade, leading
the grain markets lower as fears of a hard frost this weekend in the
Midwest receded.
   Wheat futures settled 2\ cents to 5 cents lower with December at
$3.89\ a bushel; corn was 1{ cents lower to \ cent higher with
December at $2.30 a bushel; oats were 1 cent lower to { cent higher
with December at at $1.40} a bushel; soybeans were 8{ cents lower to
1{ cents higher with November at $5.74\ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures advanced on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange ahead of an Agriculture Department
report that showed a record 45.4-million-pound decline in frozen
pork belly stocks last month.
   Analysts said the report was within expectations and should have
little market impact.
   The USDA reported 50 million pounds of pork bellies still in cold
storage as of Sept. 1.
   The USDA announced after the close that 7,000 to 10,000 tons _ or
up to 20 million pounds _ of U.S. pork bellies would be donated to
Poland.
   Live cattle futures settled .28 cent lower to .23 cent higher
with October at 71.42 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent
lower to .23 cent higher with September at 83.25 cents a pound; live
hogs were .25 cent to .90 cent higher with October at 42.80 cents a
pound; frozen pork bellies were .10 cent to .45 cent higher with
February at 49.20 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
