<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 1818EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     09-22 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Sag</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices declined Friday, led by
sagging crude prices after hurricane-related damage earlier in the
week had sent products soaring.
   ``We had profit-taking after the hype-up from the hurricane,''
said Linda Simard, energy broker with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the November contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil,
dropped 34 cents to finish the week at $19.28 a barrel. Contracts
for later delivery posted similar losses.
   With the exception of the front-month unleaded gasoline contract,
refined products also slipped.
   Unleaded gasoline for October delivery inched up .09 cent to
61.95 cents a gallon. The contract had gained 4.19 cents in the
previous two sessions after news that a big refinery in the U.S.
Virgin Islands was severely damaged by Hurricane Hugo.
   Heating oil for October delivery declined .61 cent to close at
56.97 cents a gallon.
   The refinery on St. Croix, Virgin Islands, owned by Amerada Hess
Corp., supplies markets mainly in the eastern United States. The
facility, with a capacity of 545,000 barrels, had been turning out
about 400,000 barrels a day of gasoline, distillates and other
refined oil products before the storm.
   Amerada Hess has said the refinery would resume partial
operations in about 30 days and full operations in 60 days.
   A company spokesman said Friday that officials would continue to
assess the damage over the weekend.
   ``We will have a better fix on things next week,'' said the
spokesman, who asked not to be identified. ``I think we're pretty
confident that we can do it in 60 days.''
   The official said Amerada also had storage terminals in
Charleston, S.C., that sustained minor damage from the same
hurricane as it moved northward.
   Damage to the refinery caused a normal weakening of crude prices,
analysts said.
   ``The shutdown of the refinery puts more crude back on the
marketplace,'' said Richard Redoglio, energy broker with Merrill
Lynch Energy Futures.
   In addition, the OPEC meeting this weekend added some jitters
that helped dampen prices, traders said.
   ``People are taking profits and liquidating positions in advance
of the meeting,'' Redoglio said.
   The meeting of OPEC's eight-member monitoring committee begins
Saturday in Geneva. Analysts said investors are acting cautiously
although no substantial changes are expected to emerge from the
meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
