<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 2054EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AirFares     09-22 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Air Fares,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Big Airlines Jump on Fare Hike Bandwagon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   More major airlines jumped on the fare increase bandwagon Friday,
matching an American Airlines initiative that will raise some
advance-purchase fares by more than 15 percent and double
cancellation penalties.
   United Airlines and Eastern Airlines were among competitors of
Dallas-based American that followed its move. On Thursday, Delta Air
Lines, Continental Airlines, Pan Am Corp. and Trans World Airlines
matched American's increases.
   ``We feel that it makes economic sense at this time,'' said Robin
Matell, a spokesman for strikebound Eastern at its Miami
headquarters.
   Northwest Airlines hadn't decided yet and planned to study the
matter over the weekend, spokesman Doug Miller said from Eagan, Minn.
   ``We're still holding out,'' he said. ``They're going to think
about it a little bit longer.''
   That most major airlines went along, however, virtually assured
that the fare boosts would stick. The increases, proposed by
American earlier this week will take effect Sept. 29.
   Under the changes, the popular ``MaxSaver'' cut-rate fare often
used by vacationers, which must be purchased 14 days in advance,
will be increased by $10 to $20 round trip. A ``MaxSaver'' ticket on
American between Dallas and Los Angeles, for example, would jump
from $338 to $358 round trip. The ``MaxSaver'' tickets would remain
non-refundable.
   Also, fares will be raised on seven-day advance tickets by $30 to
$60 round trip. The same Dallas-Los Angeles round trip ticket bought
seven days in advance would go from $378 to $438. The penalty for
changing or canceling a reservation would double to 50 percent of
the ticket price.
   Most of the carriers said they were matching the move mainly to
stay competitive. Atlanta-based Delta also said a sharp rise in fuel
prices, along with a large number of discount tickets sold recently,
prompted it to follow suit.
   American, one of the nation's largest carriers, said it proposed
the fare hikes in an effort to improve passenger yields. An
airline's yield reflects the average revenue from passengers for
each mile flown and is a critical barometer of financial strength.
   Many airline industry analysts expect little improvement in
yields overall for the rest of the year and into 1990.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890922-0310 </DOCNO>
