<HEAD>Banking Company Sells Stake in Korean Leasing Concern</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Manufacturers Hanover Leasing International Corp.
said Friday it agreed to sell its entire 45 percent stake in Korea
Industrial Leasing Co. Ltd. to Nippon Credit Bank of Japan for $68
million.
   The leasing company, a unit of Manufacturers Hanover Corp., said
the sale reflected a strategic decision to sell most of its
international leasing businesses and redirect resources to business
activities in the U.S. market.
   Thomas Palmer, chairman of the leasing concern, said the sale
does not affect Manufacturers Hanover's other banking activities in
Korea.
   Korea Industrial Leasing, based in Seoul, is the second-largest
leasing company in Korea and had assets of about $800 million at the
end of 1988.
   It provides financing to businesses for general equipment leases.
   The Korea Development Bank owns 50 percent of Korea Industrial
Leasing and the remaining 5 percent is held by the Korea Exchange
Bank.
   Officials of Nippon Credit Bank said the acquisition will enable
the bank to strengthen and expand its relationships with companies
in Korea.
</TEXT>
