<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-89 2055EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-DisneySuit     09-22 0155</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disney Suit,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disney Files Lawsuit Over Store's Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mickie's Gift Shop is infringing on Mickey's
good name, says Walt Disney Co. in a trademark-infringement lawsuit
filed in federal court against the store.
   Disney has tried to get the owner of the shop, Joseph Csokasy, to
change the name of his business, but he refused and Disney is taking
him to court in Orlando.
   The store's name dilutes the ``distinctive quality'' of Disney's
trademarks and ``has confused, and is likely to continue to confuse,
the public,'' according to the lawsuit filed this past week.
   The suit asks that the shop refrain from using its name, the
words ``Mickey Mouse'' or the Mickey Mouse ears logo and
reproductions.
   ``We aren't saying that this shop sells any illegal or inferior
goods,'' said Robert Duckworth, an Orlando lawyer representing
Disney. ``The lawsuit is strictly over the name.''
   Csokasy was unavailable for comment Friday.
</TEXT>
